name: Gluten-Free Patty Melt
description:
1 sandwich of gluten-free patty melt  contains 584 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 21% carbs, 59% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (51% of your Daily Value), potassium (8% of your Daily Value), and calcium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Form beef into patty.Grill the patty about three minutes. Flip the patty to another part of the pan and grill the onion in the fat left by the patty. Continue grilling the patty another three minutes. Place the cheese on the patty when the meat is about done. Move the patty to a cooler part of the pan while you continue to grill the onion slice until softened.While the onion is grilling, coat one side of each bread slice in butter. Grill in a separate pan until toasty. When done, remove the bread from the pan.To assemble: on the bread heel, spread the thousand island dressing. Place the grilled onion. Stack the patty with cheese. Cover with the bread crown. Enjoy,

name: Sweet-and-Sour Celery
description:
1 serving of sweet-and-sour celery  contains 88 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 45% carbs, 52% fat, and 4% protein.  This is a good source of vitamin k (53% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Remove any dark green outer leaves from the celery. Save roughly 1 cup of the inner leaves from the center of of the bunch. Cut celery into 2 inch pieces. Finely chop the parsley. Cut a round of parchment paper to fit just inside a wide heavy 6-to 8-quarts pot, then set round aside.Simmer water, lemon juice, oil, honey, 3/4 teaspoon salt, and 1/2 teaspoon pepper in pot, stirring, until honey has dissolved. Stir in celery (but not leaves) and cover with parchment round. Simmer until tender and liquid is reduced to about 1/4 cup, 35 to 40 minutes.Meanwhile, coarsely chop reserved leaves.Serve celery sprinkled with celery leaves and parsley.What to drink: Yarden Galilee Cabernet Sauvignon '05

name: Halibut in Chard Leaves with Lemon-Thyme Butter
description:
1 serving of halibut in chard leaves with lemon-thyme butter  contains 587 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 3% carbs, 44% fat, and 53% protein.  This is a good source of protein (138% of your Daily Value), vitamin d (131% of your Daily Value), and potassium (42% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Set out butter and let soften. Halve chard leaves lengthwise, removing center stem. Finely chop thyme. Cut lemon into 4 thin slices. Preheat oven to 450F. Blend butter, fresh lemon juice, chopped fresh thyme, chopped fresh chives, and grated lemon peel in small bowl; season butter to taste with salt and pepper.Place four 12-inch squares of foil on work surface. Overlap center edge of 2 chard halves on each square. Sprinkle fillets on each side with salt and pepper, then spread with some lemon-thyme butter. Top each with lemon slice. Place 1 fillet crosswise on widest part of chard. Fold bottom of leaf over fillet, then continue to roll up (sides will be open). Enclose each wrapped fillet in foil. Arrange packets on rimmed baking sheet. Bake until fish is just opaque in center, 12 to 14 minutes. Transfer packets to plates, open foil, and serve.

name: Carrot Puree
description:
1 serving of carrot puree  contains 115 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 34% carbs, 59% fat, and 7% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (7% of your Daily Value) and vitamin a (94% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions PREPARATION:  Halve carrots lengthwise and cut into 1/2-inch pieces.Simmer carrots, garlic, broth, and salt in a 1- to 2-quart heavy saucepan, covered, until carrots are very tender, 12 to 14 minutes. Pure mixture with cream and butter in a food processor until smooth.

name: Basil Cashew Chicken
description:
1 serving of basil cashew chicken  contains 485 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 29% carbs, 34% fat, and 37% protein.  This is a good source of protein (81% of your Daily Value), potassium (19% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (29% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Peel and grate ginger, mince garlic, chop pepper, and slice mango.Prepare rice as per package directions; set aside.Add the chicken to a bowl and toss with the oyster sauce and soy sauce. Let the chicken marinate 10 minutes.Heat a large skillet or wok over medium. Add 1 tablespoon sesame oil. Add the garlic, ginger, and serrano chile, cook 30 seconds or until fragrant. Watch close, you don't want to burn the garlic. Increase the heat to medium high. Add another drizzle sesame oil and the chicken. Stir-fry over medium high heat until cooked through, about 5-7 minutes. Stir in the cashews and cook another minute. Remove from the heat and stir in Thai basil.Serve the chicken over steamed rice with fresh mango slices and extra basil.Enjoy!

name: Curried Apple and Leek Soup
description:
1 serving of curried apple and leek soup  contains 170 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 71% carbs, 17% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (18% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and vitamin k (30% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Peel, core, and chop apples. Chop leeks. Dice potatoes.In a medium saucepan over medium heat, melt butter. Stir in curry powder and cook for 1 minute. Add leeks, potato, and apples and cook for 5 minutes. Pour in broth and bring to a boil. Cover, reduce heat, and simmer for 20 minutes.Puree in a blender or food processor, or using an immersion blender. Season with salt and pepper and serve with a swirl of yogurt.

name: Mushroom Caviar
description:
1 serving of mushroom caviar  contains 593 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 18% carbs, 74% fat, and 8% protein.  This is a good source of protein (21% of your Daily Value), fiber (24% of your Daily Value), and potassium (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Wipe the mushrooms clean and finely chop. Mince shallots and garlic. Coarsely chop parsley.Melt butter in a large skillet on high heat. Add the mushrooms and shallots. Saute for 5 minutes, stirring frequently.In a small skillet on high heat, toast the pine nuts until slightly golden, stirring frequently. Remove from heat and set aside in a small bowl.Sprinkle the cooking mushrooms with salt and pepper. After 5 minutes, add the garlic and white wine. Cook for an additional minute, then remove from heat. Combine with the toasted pine nuts in a bowl and set aside to cool.Once cooled, mix in the lemon juice, sour cream, and parsley. Season with salt, pepper, and cayenne pepper to taste. Chill before serving.Spoon onto a large butter lettuce leaf and serve with crackers. For a gluten-free option, use rice crackers.

name: Kale Edamame Dumplings
description:
1 serving of kale edamame dumplings  contains 490 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 73% carbs, 11% fat, and 16% protein.  This is a good source of protein (35% of your Daily Value), fiber (26% of your Daily Value), and potassium (15% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions To make the filling: Lightly steam kale and edamame (separately) on the stovetop or microwave until tender. Next, blend all ingredients (except the soy sauce, rice vinegar, sesame seeds, and wrappers) together in a food processor until you get a chunky paste. Taste and adjust salt and pepper accordingly. Assembly: place about a tbsp of the filling on each dumpling skin, ensuring not to overfill. Moisten the edge of the skin halfway around with some water with your fingers. Fold over, creating a half-moon or triangle shape (depends on your wrappers). Press firmly and create small folds along the edge. Set aside.Steam the dumplings until the skin is somewhat transparent, about 3-5 minutes. If you don't have a steamer it's ok to fill the bottom of a pan with water and steam the dumplings in this, covering the pan with a lid. Garnish with sesame seeds. Serve with soy sauce and rice vinegar mixed together. Enjoy!

name: Peaches in Ginger Syrup
description:
1 serving of peaches in ginger syrup  contains 143 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 94% carbs, 2% fat, and 4% protein.  This has a relatively low calorie density, with 72 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Peel and coarsely grate ginger. Simmer wine, water, sugar, and ginger, stirring occasionally, until reduced to about 3/4 cup, about 15 minutes.While syrup is simmering, slice peaches and toss with lemon juice.Pour hot syrup through a fine sieve onto peaches, then stir.Let stand 20 minutes.

name: Papaya Salsa
description:
1 serving of papaya salsa  contains 133 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 91% carbs, 4% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (17% of your Daily Value), potassium (12% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (13% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Chop scallion. Cut papaya and pineapple into small cubes.Stir together all ingredients.

name: Yam Muffins
description:
1 serving of yam muffins  contains 624 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 66% carbs, 23% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of protein (35% of your Daily Value), fiber (41% of your Daily Value), and potassium (40% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F. Prepare a muffin pan with paper cups or non-stick spray.

In a large mixing bowl, stir together the oat bran, baking soda, baking powder, allspice, and cinnamon. 

In a small bowl, mix the shredded yam, egg whites, molasses, applesauce, and oil. Pour the wet mixture into the dry and stir to mix thoroughly.

Fill the muffin cups about level. Bake for 30 to 35 minutes, or until a toothpick comes out clean.

name: Chicken Noodle Casserole
description:
1 serving of chicken noodle casserole  contains 728 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 21% carbs, 61% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (57% of your Daily Value), potassium (10% of your Daily Value), and calcium (41% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375 degrees F.Chop chicken into bite sized pieces. Heat oil in a skillet over medium-high heat. Add cubed chicken and sauté for 8-12 minutes, or until cooked through and no longer pink; set aside.Bring a large pot of salted water to boil and cook noodles according to packaging directions, or until al dente.Drain and set aside.In a large bowl combine soups and heavy cream and stir together to mixAdd frozen vegetables, cheddar cheese, cubed chicken, and egg noodles, and season with garlic salt and pepperPour mixture into a large casserole dish and lightly tap it against the counter to remove air bubbles and smooth it outIn a separate bowl, toss together breadcrumbs, parmesan cheese, and melted butter. Sprinkle evenly over the top of casserole.Place baking dish in oven and bake for 30-35 minutes, or until vegetables are tender and sauce is bubbly.Remove from oven and let cool 5 minutes. Transfer to serving bowls and garnish with more cheese

name: Kale, Mozzarella, and Egg Bake
description:
1 serving of kale, mozzarella, and egg bake  contains 216 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 6% carbs, 63% fat, and 31% protein.  This is a good source of protein (30% of your Daily Value), calcium (22% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (32% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375 degrees F.  Spray an 8.5"x12" glass or crockery casserole dish with olive oil or nonstick spray. Heat the oil in a large frying pan, add the kale all at once, and stir just until the kale is wilted, about 1 minute for baby kale or 2-3 minutes for chopped kale.  Transfer the kale to the casserole dish, spreading it around so all the bottom of the dish is covered.  Layer the grated cheese and sliced onions on top of the kale.Beat the eggs with salt and fresh ground pepper to taste. Pour egg mixture over the kale/cheese combination, and then use a fork to gently "stir" so the eggs, kale, and cheese are evenly combined.Bake about 30-35 minutes or until the mixture is completely set and starting to lightly brown.  Let cool about 5 minutes before cutting.  (The egg bake will settle down some as it cools.)  Serve hot.  Recipe inspired by: http://www.kalynskitchen.com/2012/05/recipe-for-baby-kale-mozzarella-and-egg.html

name: Lightened Up Penne alla Vodka
description:
1 serving of lightened up penne alla vodka  contains 566 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 60% carbs, 23% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (42% of your Daily Value), fiber (17% of your Daily Value), and potassium (20% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add the penne and cook according to package directions. Drain, reserving 1 cup of the cooking water.

Whisk the yogurt with the cream in a measuring cup and set aside.

Meanwhile, heat the oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the shallots and 1/2 teaspoon salt and cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly softened, about 3 minutes. Add the garlic and red pepper flakes and cook, stirring, for 30 seconds. Remove from the heat and stir in the tomatoes and vodka. Return the skillet to medium heat, bring to a simmer and cook, stirring often, until the alcohol cooks off and the sauce comes together and thickens, about 7 minutes. Stir in the yogurt-cream mixture and cook until the sauce thickens slightly, about 3 minutes.

Add the pasta, Parmesan, parsley and 1/2 teaspoon salt to the skillet and toss to combine. Use the reserved pasta water to thin the sauce as needed. Enjoy!

Recipe inspired by: http://www.foodnetwork.com/recipes/food-network-kitchens/lightened-up-penne-a-la-vodka.html?oc=linkback

name: BLT Salad with Creamy Chive Dressing
description:
1 serving of blt salad with creamy chive dressing  contains 241 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 19% carbs, 73% fat, and 8% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (11% of your Daily Value), vitamin a (42% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (26% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Bake bacon for 15 minutes in a 400 degree oven.  Drain on paper towels and chop.For dressing:  in a small bowl combine vinegar, garlic and a pinch of salt; let stand 10 minutes. Wisk in sour cream, chives and olive oil.  Thin with milk to desired consistency.Arrange spinach, tomatoes, chopped bacon, and croutons on a platter.  Drizzle with dressing.  Sprinkle with additional chopped chives. Serve and enjoy!

name: Mexican Red Rice
description:
1 serving of mexican red rice  contains 236 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 71% carbs, 21% fat, and 8% protein.  This has a relatively low calorie density, with 131 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Heat oil in a large saucepan over medium heat. Add minced garlic, stir briefly, then add diced onion. Cook for 4 - 5 minutes until translucent.Add rice, broth, salt and tomato paste. Stir until tomato paste is dissolved.Add dice jalapeno. Cover, bring to simmer, then lower heat to low so the water is simmering gently. Cook for 15 minutes or until liquid is absorbed.Remove from heat, leave lid on and rest for 10 minutes. Fluff with fork and serve.

name: 5 Spice Pork Lettuce Cups
description:
1 serving of 5 spice pork lettuce cups  contains 437 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 6% carbs, 74% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (40% of your Daily Value), potassium (13% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (52% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat oil in a pan over medium-high heat. Add pork and chinese five spice. Cook for 10-12 minutes, or until browned throughout.Combine tahini, aminos, sesame oil, and sesame seeds in a small bowl. Mix well.Serve in lettuce cups topped with grated carrot, bell peppers, cucumber, and cabbage. Garnish with cilantro. Enjoy!

name: Seared Salmon with Watercress and Warm Orange Dressing
description:
1 serving of seared salmon with watercress and warm orange dressing  contains 804 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 32% carbs, 32% fat, and 36% protein.  This is a good source of protein (130% of your Daily Value), fiber (41% of your Daily Value), and vitamin d (231% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Remove the thicker stems from the watercress and roughly chop the rest of the bunch.  Slice the radishes.  In a bowl, toss the watercress with 1 tablespoon of the oil and a pinch or two of salt.  Sprinkle with 1 teaspoon of vinegar.  Place salad greens on a serving platter or on 2 individual plates and top with the pineapple and radish slices.Heat a large, heavy skillet over medium-high heat;  when hot, add the remaining tablespoon of olive oil.  Sear the salmon until cooked, taking care to cook through but not overcook, about 4-6 minutes.  Internal temperature should be 145 degrees F.  Sprinkle salt on each side of the salmon during cooking.  Remove the salmon from pan and arrange on the salad.  

To make the dressing, juice the blood orange, then add it to with the remaining tablespoon of vinegar and honey to the same pan, set on high, and bring to a boil.  Cook until liquid is slightly reduced and thickened, about three minutes.Grind some fresh pepper and squeeze a little lemon juice (if desired) over the salad.  Drizzle the sauce over and around the salmon.  Serve immediately while the salmon is still hot.

name: Chicken Sausage Patties From Scratch
description:
1 serving of chicken sausage patties from scratch  contains 134 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 52% fat, and 40% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (33% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat a medium non-stick skillet over medium low heat and add the oil, onions, and garlic and stir frequently, about 4-5 minutes, until onion is translucent. Lower heat, if needed, to avoid browning too quickly. Season with salt and pepper. Once onion is softened, add fennel and toss quickly until fragrant and toasted, about 1 minute. Remove mixture to a medium bowl to cool slightly.Add ground chicken, red wine vinegar, chives, paprika, sugar, and nutmeg to bowl with onions, garlic and fennel and mix together with a fork until all ingredients are well-distributed. Form mixture into 6 even patties and lay on parchment or wax paper while working. If you want to make these for another day, they can be refrigerated or frozen.Spray a non-stick skillet and set over medium-low heat. Once hot, brown the patties, in two batches, 3 minutes on each side. Once you have achieved a nice browned crust on each side, reduce heat to low and cover. Continue cooking until internal temperature reaches 165 degrees F. Remove from heat and repeat with second batch. Enjoy!Recipe inspired by: http://www.skinnytaste.com/2015/02/turkey-sausage-patties-from-scratch.html

name: Matar Pulao
description:
1 serving of matar pulao  contains 291 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 75% carbs, 16% fat, and 8% protein.  This has a relatively low calorie density, with 114 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Heat the oil in a deep heavy skillet over low heat. Add the cloves, cardamom seeds, peppercorns, and cinnamon sticks. Cook for a few minutes to bring out the aroma of the spices. Stir the garlic powder and 2 tablespoons of water together to make a paste; mix into the pan with the spices.Add the green peas to the pan, cover and cook for about 5 minutes.Add the remaining 4 cups of water and rice to the pan. Season with a little salt. Bring to a boil, then cover, and cook for about 15 minutes, until the rice is tender and the water has been absorbed. Taste, and adjust the salt before serving.

name: Crispy Barbequed Tofu Slices
description:
1 serving of crispy barbequed tofu slices  contains 412 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 48% carbs, 37% fat, and 15% protein.  This is a good source of protein (28% of your Daily Value), potassium (7% of your Daily Value), and calcium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Drain tofu, and slice into strips. Place in a plastic bag or container, and freeze overnight. This will give the tofu a meatier texture. Thaw tofu strips, and blot with paper towels to dry.Heat olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat. In a small bowl, whisk together the egg white and 1 tablespoon of barbeque sauce. Combine the flour, salt, and pepper in a separate bowl. Dip the tofu slices into the egg mixture, then into the flour mixture, shaking off excess flour. Fry in the hot oil for about 1 minute on each side, until golden brown. Just fry enough at one time so they are not crowded. Remove from the oil to paper towels to drain and cool.Preheat the oven's broiler. Brush tofu slices with additional barbeque sauce, and allow to marinate while the broiler heats up. Arrange them on a broiler pan, or wire rack set over a cookie sheet for best results.Position the oven rack about 6 inches from the heat source. Broil for 5 minutes on each side, or until browned and crisp, watching closely so as not to burn them. Serve warm with the remaining barbeque sauce for dipping.

name: Linguine with Red Bell Peppers and Kalamata Olives
description:
1 serving of linguine with red bell peppers and kalamata olives  contains 462 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 43% carbs, 40% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (36% of your Daily Value), potassium (8% of your Daily Value), and calcium (29% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Stem,seed the red bell peppers and cut them into 1/3 inch cubes. Pit the olives and cut them into quarters.  Press the garlic cloves without the juice running out.Cook pasta in large pot of boiling salted
water until just tender but still firm to bite.
Drain, reserving 1 cup cooking liquid.Meanwhile, heat oil in large nonstick
skillet over medium-high heat. Add bell
peppers, olives, garlic, and crushed red
pepper. Saute until bell peppers are tender,
4 to 5 minutes. Add pasta, 1/2 cup reserved
pasta cooking liquid, 1 cup basil, 1 cup
cheese, and vinegar. Toss until sauce coats
pasta, adding more reserved cooking liquid
by 1/4 cupfuls if dry, about 1 minute. Season
to taste with salt and pepper. Transfer to
bowl. Sprinkle with remaining 1/4 cup basil
and serve, passing additional cheese.

name: Balsamic-Roasted Pears with Pepper and Honey
description:
1 serving of balsamic-roasted pears with pepper and honey  contains 287 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 46% carbs, 44% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (18% of your Daily Value) and vitamin a (18% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cut goat cheese into (4) 1 ounce cubes.Halve the pears lengthwise and remove the cores.Preheat oven to 400F.Melt butter in an 8-inch square glass baking dish in middle of oven, about 3 minutes.Arrange pears, cut sides down, in 1 layer in butter and roast in middle of oven until tender, about 20 minutes.Pour vinegar over pears and roast 5 minutes more.Transfer pears, cut sides down, to serving plates with cheese and spoon some of juices from baking dish over pears. Drizzle pears and cheese with honey and sprinkle with pepper.

name: Healthy Beef Vegetable Quinoa Stew
description:
1 serving of healthy beef vegetable quinoa stew  contains 286 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 33% carbs, 44% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (30% of your Daily Value), fiber (24% of your Daily Value), and potassium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook quinoa: In a small pot, add ½ cup quinoa and stir in 1 cup water. Bring to a boil, then turn down to simmer, cover, and cook on low heat, until all water is absorbed, about 12-15 minutes.In a large nonstick pot, add ground beef, onions, and garlic. Brown beef thoroughly, stirring often and breaking up beef into very small pieces. Once browned, drain excess fat.Add beef and onions back to pot. Stir in tomatoes, pasta sauce, beef broth, zucchini, mushrooms, red bell peppers, red pepper flakes, Italian seasonings, and black pepper. Mix well. Bring to a boil, turn down to simmer, cover, and cook 25 minutes. Remove cover, stir in spinach and cooked quinoa. Mix well. Cook 2 more minutes, until spinach is wilted.Serve, garnished with Parmesan cheese. Enjoy!

name: Vegan Broccoli Quiche
description:
1 serving of vegan broccoli quiche  contains 348 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 37% carbs, 47% fat, and 15% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value), potassium (12% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (62% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Pre-heat the oven to 425 degrees F.Heat the olive oil in a medium saucepan over medium heat and sauté the onion, green pepper, broccoli, and mushrooms until cooked, about 8 to 10 minutes.In a blender or food processor, blend the tofu, nutmeg, turmeric, basil, salt, and soy milk until smooth. Stir the vegetables and the tofu mixture together and add pepper to taste.Pour the mixed batter into the pie crust.Bake your vegan quiche for 30 minutes, or until a knife inserted just off-center into the quiche comes out cleanRecipe inspired by: http://vegetarian.about.com/od/breakfastrecipe1/r/veganquiche.htm

name: Nutribullet Butter Bean and Broccoli Soba Noodles
description:
1 ½ cups of nutribullet butter bean and broccoli soba noodles  contains 619 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 69% carbs, 15% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (51% of your Daily Value), fiber (71% of your Daily Value), and potassium (40% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add soba noodles and cook as package directions indicate; then drain and rinse well. Set noodles aside.

Steam broccoli until it turns bright green (about 2-4 minutes), and set aside.

In a non-stick pan heat olive/coconut oil. Stir in quartered cherry tomatoes, cayenne, salt, and pepper. Add steamed broccoli and let cook for 1-2 minutes so all the pan ingredients get a little caramelized and soften up. Once tomatoes are softened, add butter beans. Stir everything together and pour into a bowl.

In the still-hot pan, put 1-2 tbsp of rice vinegar. Add cooked soba noodles to the vinegar, seasoning with a pinch each of salt, basil, and oregano. Toss to coat the pasta. Once the pasta is coated and heated through, add back the broccoli, beans, and tomatoes. Taste and season with more salt or pepper if needed.

Plate and drizzle with balsamic or cider vinegar, if desired.

name: Sour Cream Scrambled Eggs
description:
1 serving of sour cream scrambled eggs  contains 327 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 9% carbs, 72% fat, and 19% protein.  This is a good source of protein (28% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (28% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Slice avocado and mushrooms, chop chives.Saute mushrooms over medium heat with half of the butter. Set aside.Mix together the sour cream and eggs in a small bowl. Sprinkle with salt and pepper and whisk until combined.Melt the rest of the butter in a nonstick pan over medium-low heat. Add the eggs and gently scramble. Remove from the heat, sprinkle with the chives and serve with sliced avocado and fried mushrooms.Remove from the heat, sprinkle with the chives and serve with sliced avocado and fried mushrooms.

name: Grilled Salmon with Corn and Tomatoes
description:
1 serving of grilled salmon with corn and tomatoes  contains 284 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 29% carbs, 33% fat, and 38% protein.  This is a good source of protein (48% of your Daily Value), fiber (15% of your Daily Value), and vitamin d (82% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Prepare grill. Defrost corn and salmon.

Add tomatoes, defrosted corn, olive oil, vinegar, and sliced basil; season with 1/4 teaspoon salt, and 1/4 teaspoon pepper. Let the relish sit at room temperature for 15 minutes before serving.

Meanwhile, lightly coat both sides of salmon fillets with cooking spray; season with remaining 1/4 teaspoon salt and 1/4 teaspoon pepper. Place fillets skin side down, and grill 3–4 minutes or until golden brown. Flip fillets, and grill for 3 more minutes. Fish should feel slightly firm in the center and will register 145 degrees F on an instant-read thermometer.Place salmon onto each of 4 plates, and spoon relish over top. Garnish with basil sprigs, if desired.

name: Sticky Chicken Strips
description:
1 serving of sticky chicken strips  contains 328 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 11% carbs, 18% fat, and 72% protein.  This is a good source of protein (98% of your Daily Value), potassium (18% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.Arrange chicken in a single layer in a baking dish. In a medium bowl combine water, soy sauce, splenda, and wine. Pour over chicken and sprinkle with garlic powder.Bake for 10 minutes in preheated oven until sauce is hot and bubbly.Reduce temperature to 350 degrees F, and bake for an additional 15 to 20 minutes, until sauce is thick and sticky, basting repeatedly. Enjoy!

name: Loaded Cauliflower "Mash" Bake
description:
1 serving of loaded cauliflower "mash" bake  contains 586 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 78% fat, and 14% protein.  This is a good source of protein (36% of your Daily Value), potassium (17% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (50% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Cook the bacon in a skillet until crisp; set aside on a paper towel then crumble.
Fill a large pot with water, bring to a boil. Add cauliflower and garlic. Boil until the cauliflower is soft, about 15-20 minutes. Drain, and return to the pot. 
Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F.Add the buttermilk, butter, salt and pepper to the cauliflower and purée with a hand blender. If you don't own a hand blender, a regular blender would work fine as well.Mix in 1 tbsp of the chives  and transfer to 4 individual casseroles (3/4 cups each) or one 8 x 8 casserole dish. Top with cheddar and crumbled bacon. Bake in the oven until the cheese melts, about 5 minutes then top with remaining chives. Enjoy!Recipe inspired by: http://www.skinnytaste.com/2014/12/loaded-cauliflower-mash-bake.html

name: S'more Cups
description:
1 serving of s'more cups  contains 118 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 49% carbs, 48% fat, and 3% protein.  This has a relatively high calorie density, with 475 Calories per 100g.
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Combine graham cracker crumbs, powdered sugar, and melted butter in a bowl.
Use a mini muffin pan and place a small scoop of crumb mixture into each cup.Press the mixture to form a cup.Bake 4 to 5 minutes or until edges bubble and remove from oven.Break candy bar into rectangles and cut marshmallows in half.Place one piece of chocolate into each cup and top with a marshmallow.Bake for another minute or two or until the marshmallow is soft.Remove and cool.
Melt the remaining candy bars and dip each s'more into the chocolate mixture.Let stand until set and enjoy.

name: Banana Chocolate Chip Muffins
description:
1 serving of banana chocolate chip muffins  contains 91 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 55% carbs, 27% fat, and 18% protein.  This has a moderate calorie density, with 150 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375°F. Line a muffin pan with paper cups.Mash banana in a bowl. Add all wet ingredients to the bowl and whisk together well.In a separate bowl, combine all dry ingredients (excluding chocolate chips) and whisk together well.Gradually mix the wet ingredients into the dry ingredients until the batter is homogenous. Fold in the chocolate chips.Pour the batter into the prepared muffin tin.Bake for about 20 minutes, or until a toothpick inserted into the center comes out clean.Let the muffins cool in the pan for a few minutes before transferring them to a wire rack to cool completely.

name: Pan Fried Vegetables
description:
1 serving of pan fried vegetables  contains 41 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 32% carbs, 54% fat, and 14% protein.  This has a relatively low calorie density, with 40 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Heat pan to medium.Slice Squash and Zucchini Add butter, seasoning, and vegetables to pan. Fry for 20 minutes or until desired softness is reached.Sprinkle with Parmesan

name: Steamed Striped Bass with Ginger and Scallions
description:
1 serving of steamed striped bass with ginger and scallions  contains 1218 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 29% carbs, 24% fat, and 48% protein.  This is a good source of protein (251% of your Daily Value), potassium (64% of your Daily Value), and calcium (64% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions PREPARATION:  Cook rice according to package directions. Peel ginger and cut into very thin matchsticks.  Cut scallions lengthwise into very thin matchsticks (1/2 cup).Arrange a steamer rack or an inverted pie plate in a deep 12-inch skillet and add 3 cups water to skillet. Cover skillet and bring water to a boil.Pat fillets dry and arrange on a heatproof plate that will fit into skillet with 1 inch clearance around plate. Sprinkle ginger and 1/4 cup scallions evenly on top of fish. Stir together soy sauce and oil in a small bowl and drizzle evenly over fillets. Carefully transfer plate with fish to rack in skillet and cover tightly, then steam over moderately high heat until fish is just cooked through, 15 to 20 minutes. Carefully remove plate from skillet and sprinkle with remaining 1/4 cup scallions. Serve with rice.

name: High Protein Vegetarian Pasta With Tempeh Tomato Sauce
description:
1 serving of high protein vegetarian pasta with tempeh tomato sauce  contains 433 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 53% carbs, 28% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (41% of your Daily Value), potassium (26% of your Daily Value), and iron (72% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare pasta according to package directions.Slice mushrooms and mince garlic. Make zucchini noodles using a spiralizer or vegetable peeler. Set aside.Crumble tempeh into a large bowl using your hands.Heat 2 large pans over medium heat. Add olive oil and minced garlic to both pans, cooking for 1-2 minutes until slightly browned. In one pan, add crumbled tempeh and cook for 3 minutes. In the other pan, add mushrooms and cook until browned and tender, about 10 minutes.Add tomatoes, tomato paste, thyme, and salt to pan with tempeh. Cook until sauce thickens, about 5 minutes.When mushrooms are cooked, drain and add to tomato mixture. Continue cooking for a few minutes, adding fresh chopped basil at the end. Adjust seasonings as needed.In the used mushroom pan, lightly saute the zucchini noodles for 1-2 minutes. Add zucchini noodles to drained pasta. Pour sauce over top and stir to combine.

name: Broccoli Stuffed Baked Potato
description:
2 Halves of broccoli stuffed baked potato  contains 254 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 61% carbs, 26% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of protein (15% of your Daily Value), fiber (21% of your Daily Value), and potassium (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 425°F. Place potatoes on a baking sheet and bake for about 30 minutes, or until fork tender.Bring a pot of water to boil. Add the broccoli and cook for about 4-5 minutes or until broccoli is tender; drain and set aside.Halve potatoes, scoop, and mash. Add butter, half of the cheese, garlic, and pepper. Return to skins, top with broccoli, sprinkle with remaining cheese and black pepper. Bake just to melt cheese, about 5 minutes.

name: Vegan Chickpea Cakes with Avocado
description:
1 serving of vegan chickpea cakes with avocado  contains 433 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 40% carbs, 52% fat, and 8% protein.  This is a good source of protein (16% of your Daily Value), fiber (33% of your Daily Value), and potassium (9% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Chop herbs and de-seed & chop jalapeno.Bring 2 cups of water to a boil over high heat. Add bulgur wheat and cook until tender, about 10 minutes. Drain carefully.While wheat cooks, combine parsley, mint, cilantro, garlic, jalapeño and coriander in the bowl of a food processor. Pulse until finely chopped, scraping down sides as necessary, about 10 to 12 short pulses. Add half of chickpeas and pulse until a rough puree is formed, scraping down sides as necessary, about 8 to 10 short pulses. Transfer to a large bowl.Add remaining chickpeas to food processor and pulse until roughly chopped, 4 to 6 pulses. Transfer to bowl with chickpea/herb mixture. When bulgur wheat has drained, add to bowl. Season with salt and pepper, then fold mixture together, starting with a rubber spatula, and finishing by hand when cool enough to handle. Form mixture into patties roughly 3/4-inch thick and 3 inches wide (you should be able to work 8 to 12 patties).Combine flour and water in a medium bowl and whisk until smooth. Place breadcrumbs in second medium bowl.Working one patty at a time, dip in flour mixture to coat, then transfer to breadcrumbs. Cover with breadcrumbs on all sides, then transfer to a plate. Repeat with remaining patties.Heat half of oil in a large cast iron or non-stick skillet over medium-high heat until shimmering. Add half the patties in a single layer and cook, swirling pan occasionally, until golden brown on bottoms, about 2 minutes. Carefully flip and cook second side, swirling pan occasionally as they cook, about 2 minutes longer. Transfer to a plate and keep warm while you cook the remaining patties.Place avocado in a medium bowl and mash the flesh with a fork. Season with salt and add lime juice. serve fried chickpea patties with mashed avocado and lime wedges.

name: Coconut Quinoa
description:
1 serving of coconut quinoa  contains 934 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 34% carbs, 57% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of protein (40% of your Daily Value), fiber (35% of your Daily Value), and potassium (28% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Place rinsed and drained quinoa, coconut milk, and agave in a medium-sized pot. Stir ingredients and bring to a boil. Reduce heat to a low simmer and cover pot, preferably with a clear lid (so you can see through it and keep an eye on the quinoa). Stir a few times during cooking. If mixture seems to be boiling out, crack the lid to release steam, otherwise, keep covered. Cook for 10-15 minutes, until liquid is absorbed. In the last few minutes of cooking, feel free to add a little water until desired consistency is reached. 
Divide quinoa into bowls and top with fresh berries. Enjoy!

name: Soy-Wasabi Spread on Toast
description:
1 serving of soy-wasabi spread on toast  contains 312 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 35% carbs, 32% fat, and 32% protein.  This is a good source of protein (47% of your Daily Value), fiber (29% of your Daily Value), and potassium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook edamame in a pot of boiling water until tender, about five minutes. Drain in a colander and rinse under cold running water to stop the cooking. Drain again.Puree the edamame, tofu, lemon juice, wasabi, lemon zest, and salt in a food processor. Toast bread and spread edamame spread onto toast. Garnish with sesame seeds and serve. Spread can be refrigerated in an airtight container for up to two days.

name: Creamed Corn with Basil
description:
1 serving of creamed corn with basil  contains 172 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 58% carbs, 32% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (9% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Working in a large bowl, cut kernels from cobs with a sharp knife and set aside. Scrape back of knife several times against cobs to extract remaining corn pulp, scraping into a large glass measure. (You should have at least 3/4 cup of corn pulp. If not, add 2 tablespoons crme frache.) Transfer pulp to a blender and pure with 2 tablespoons crme frache until smooth.Cook shallot in butter in a 12-inch heavy skillet over moderate heat, stirring occasionally, until softened, 3 to 4 minutes. Stir in kernels, then add corn pure, water, salt, and pepper and simmer, uncovered, stirring occasionally, until kernels are just tender, 3 to 4 minutes. Stir in basil to taste.

name: Buttermilk Biscuits with Green Onions, Black Pepper, and Sea Salt
description:
1 serving of buttermilk biscuits with green onions, black pepper, and sea salt  contains 176 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 48% carbs, 41% fat, and 11% protein.  This has a relatively high calorie density, with 402 Calories per 100g.
instructions:
Directions Cut butter into 1/2-inch cubes, reserving one tablespoon. Position rack in center of oven and preheat
to 425F. Line baking sheet with parchment
paper. Combine buttermilk and green onions
in medium bowl. Whisk flour, cornmeal, sugar, and 1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper in large bowl to blend. Add 1/2 cup chilled
butter and rub in with fingertips until mixture
resembles coarse meal. Add buttermilk
mixture and stir until moist clumps form.Gather dough together. Turn dough out
onto floured surface and knead gently just
to combine, about 3 to 4 turns. Roll out to
3/4-inch thickness. Using floured 2-inch cookie
or biscuit cutter, cut out rounds. Reroll
scraps and cut out additional rounds. Place
2 inches apart on prepared baking sheet.
Brush tops of biscuits with melted butter.
Sprinkle each lightly with coarse sea salt and
ground black pepper.Bake biscuits until golden and tester
inserted into center comes out clean, about
20 minutes. Cool slightly. Serve warm or at
room temperature.

name: Brussels Sprouts with Chestnuts
description:
1 serving of brussels sprouts with chestnuts  contains 212 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 33% carbs, 58% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (18% of your Daily Value), potassium (12% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Coarsely crumble chestnuts. Trim Brussels sprouts and halve lengthwise. Bring butter, salt, pepper, and 1 cup water to a boil over high heat in a deep 12-inch heavy skillet, then add Brussels sprouts and simmer, partially covered, stirring occasionally, until crisp-tender, 6 to 8 minutes. Remove lid and boil over moderately high heat until water is evaporated and sprouts are lightly browned, 3 to 4 minutes. Add cream and remaining 1/4 cup water and bring to a boil, stirring. Add chestnuts, then reduce heat and simmer, stirring occasionally, until heated through, about 2 minutes.

name: Sautéed Broccoli and Asparagus with Eggs
description:
1 serving of sautéed broccoli and asparagus with eggs  contains 753 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 38% carbs, 39% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (80% of your Daily Value), fiber (55% of your Daily Value), and potassium (29% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Bring a large saucepan of water to the boil and place a griddle pan over a high heat. When the griddle pan is hot, place the asparagus spears, broccoli, and bacon directly onto it, sprinkling the vegetables with a little salt and pepper. Cook for 3–4 minutes, turning regularly ungil bacon is crisp and vegetables are lightly charred.Prepare the lentils in the microwave or on the stove-top according to the packet instructions.Carefully crack your eggs into the hot water, reducing the heat until the water is just simmering. Cook the eggs for about 4 minutes for a runny yolk, then carefully lift them out with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels.Once the vegetables and bacon are all cooked transfer to a large bowl, along with the olive oil, sherry vinegar and lentils. Season to taste with salt and pepper and toss together before piling onto plates. Top with the poached eggs and finish with the toasted hazelnuts. Enjoy!

name: Salmon with Capers and Caprese Salad
description:
1 serving of salmon with capers and caprese salad  contains 746 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 9% carbs, 60% fat, and 31% protein.  This is a good source of protein (104% of your Daily Value), fiber (27% of your Daily Value), and potassium (38% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat 1 tablespoon of the olive oil in a frying pan over a medium-high heat. Add the salmon fillets and fry for 1–2 minutes on each side, by which time the fish should be lightly coloured. Using a spatula, break the fish into large chunks and fry for a further 2–3 minutes or until the fish is just cooked through. Remove the pan from the heat and transfer the salmon to a plate.Mix together the mustard, lemon juice, capers, and the remaining olive oil to make a dressing.Arrange the avocado, tomato, and mozzarella over two plates. Top with the salmon chunks, scatter with the basil leaves and walnuts, and finally spoon over the dressing. Enjoy!

name: Quinoa Sushi
description:
1 serving of quinoa sushi  contains 704 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 44% carbs, 46% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of protein (31% of your Daily Value), fiber (62% of your Daily Value), and potassium (30% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook 1/2 cup quinoa as per package directions (yield: 1.5 cup)Lay Nori on cutting board, shiny side down.Spread a small spoonful of vegan mayonnaise and chili sauce onto nori sheets.Spread a scoop of quinoa onto nori sheet.Slice avocado and add to nori sheet.Add a handful of coleslaw mix.Roll tightly and add soy sauce (or liquid aminos) to seal.  Carefully slice and and enjoy.

name: Spiced Baby Potatoes with Bacon and Dill
description:
1 serving of spiced baby potatoes with bacon and dill  contains 402 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 36% carbs, 54% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of protein (18% of your Daily Value), fiber (16% of your Daily Value), and potassium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Place the potatoes in a pan, cover with water, and bring to a boil. Immediately remove from heat, cover, and let stand 10 minutes. Drain par-boiled potatoes and place back in the pan. Heat for 3 minutes over medium to steam dry.Add chopped bacon to a cold pan over medium heat and fry until almost crispy.Add the spices and cook for 1 minute.Halve the potatoes and add to the pan with the bacon and spices and toss to coat well, add the remaining olive oil if the mix is a little dry.Season with salt and pepper.Remove from the heat and add the dill.Toss to combine.Take two large pieces of foil, tip the potato mix in centre of the foil and fold to create parcel.Place the sealed parcel in the oven and cook for up to 30 minutess or until the potatoes are cooked through and slightly crispy.

name: Simple Chicken Meatballs
description:
1 serving of simple chicken meatballs  contains 279 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 5% carbs, 61% fat, and 34% protein.  This is a good source of protein (42% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (51% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat an oven to 450 degrees F. Line a rimmed baking sheet with aluminum foil, and spray with cooking spray.Combine the chicken, eggs, bread crumbs, red pepper flakes, Italian seasoning, garlic powder, vegetable oil, salt, and pepper in a large bowl; mix well. Form mixture into 20 meatballs; place on prepared pan.Bake in center of preheated oven until juices run clear, 17 to 18 minutes. An instant-read thermometer inserted into the center should read at least 165 degrees F.

name: Gluten Free Chocolate Protein Muffins
description:
1 muffin of gluten free chocolate protein muffins  contains 180 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 42% carbs, 15% fat, and 43% protein.  This is a good source of protein (36% of your Daily Value), calcium (17% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b12 (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Combine all ingredients in a bowl. You might need to add more milk/water to reach a good batter consistency.Pour into muffin pan and bake until a toothpick comes out clean, approximately 15-20 minutes. Let cool and enjoy!

name: Oatmeal with Diced Fruit and Pistachios
description:
1 serving of oatmeal with diced fruit and pistachios  contains 320 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 69% carbs, 22% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of protein (15% of your Daily Value), fiber (26% of your Daily Value), and potassium (7% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare the oats according to the package directions. Stir in the nutmeg. Top with the dried cranberries, dried cherries, and pistachios. Drizzle with the honey.

name: Skinny Mini Banana Muffins
description:
2 muffins of skinny mini banana muffins  contains 151 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 75% carbs, 16% fat, and 9% protein.  This has a moderate calorie density, with 235 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. Spray mini muffin tins with non-stick cooking spray and set aside.In large bowl, stir dry ingredients together until combined. In separate bowl, whisk maple syrup, olive oil, egg whites, and vanilla together until combined. Form a well in dry ingredients. Pour in mashed banana and wet ingredients. Stir until just combined. Spoon into prepared pans and bake 10 minutes or until just cooked. Cool 3-5 minutes before removing from muffin tins. Serve warm or store at room temperature for up to 3 days.

name: Bratwurst with Creamy Apple Compote
description:
1 serving of bratwurst with creamy apple compote  contains 733 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 14% carbs, 76% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of protein (32% of your Daily Value), potassium (13% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Peel and core apples, cut into 8 wedges each. Peel and thinly slice onion.Preheat broiler.Heat butter and oil in a 12-inch heavy skillet over medium-high heat until foam subsides, then cook onion and apples with bay leaf, 1/2 teaspoon salt, and 1/4 teaspoon pepper, stirring once or twice, until golden brown, about 6 minutes.Meanwhile, split bratwurst lengthwise (not all the way through) and open up. Lightly brush cut sides of bratwurst with additional oil and transfer to a shallow baking pan (split sides up).Add wine to apple mixture, then simmer, covered, until apples are tender, 6 to 8 minutes. Remove lid and briskly simmer until liquid is reduced by one third, about 2 minutes.While apples simmer, broil bratwurst 4 to 5 inches from heat until browned, about 6 minutes.Stir cream, vinegar, and brown sugar into apple mixture and briskly simmer until slightly thickened, about 2 minutes. Discard bay leaf and serve apple compote over bratwurst.

name: Imitation Eel Rice Bowl
description:
1 serving of imitation eel rice bowl (Roasted long Chinese style eggplant stands in for eel served over rice & shredded seaweed. Vegan dish) contains 589 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 88% carbs, 3% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value), fiber (64% of your Daily Value), and potassium (31% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook rice according to package directions. Poke holes all over eggplant's skin using a fork. Make a shallow cut around stem just through the skin to aid peeling.Roast eggplant over open flame until skin is wrinkled and insides are tender and "deflated". You can use a rack directly over a gas burner on the stove, or roast in a baking dish the oven or toaster oven, or wrap in plastic wrap and microwave at 600w for 2 minutes. Let eggplant cool until it can be handled.Once the eggplant is cool enough to handle, carefully peel off skin and slice eggplant lengthwise to flatten leaving the halves connected and stopping at the stem. (butterfly cut)Mix together soy sauce, mirin, sugar, and sake and cook on low heat in frying pan until it just begins to bubble.Add eggplant to pan and cook until all liquid is absorbed/cooked away.Place cooked rice in bowl, layer with thinly shredded seaweed (you can use scissors to shred it) and finally top with eggplant "eel".

name: Indian Rice Pudding
description:
1 Bowl of indian rice pudding  contains 327 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 65% carbs, 17% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (26% of your Daily Value), potassium (13% of your Daily Value), and calcium (47% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions In a large, heavy-bottomed pot, bring the rice, milk, and cardamom to a boil over medium-high heat, stirring constantly with a heat-safe spatula to help keep the milk from burning.Reduce the heat so that the milk is gently simmering and cook for 45 to 50 minutes, stirring often. The rice should be tender and the milk will have reduced by half, giving a porridge-like consistency.Add the sugar, vanilla, and pistachios. Stir and turn off the heat. Serve either warm or chilled, garnished with extra pistachios.

name: Sauteed Dandelion Greens
description:
1 serving of sauteed dandelion greens  contains 147 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 15% carbs, 81% fat, and 4% protein.  This is a good source of vitamin a (31% of your Daily Value), vitamin e (26% of your Daily Value), and vitamin k (364% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Remove the lower stems of the dandelion greens and discard. Cut the leaves crosswise into 2 inch piecesCook greens in a 10-to 12-quart pot of boiling salted water (3 tablespoons salt for 8 quarts water), uncovered, until ribs are tender, about 10 minutes. Drain in a colander, then rinse under cold water to stop cooking and drain well, gently pressing out excess water.Heat oil in a 12-inch heavy skillet over medium heat until it shimmers, then cook garlic and red-pepper flakes, stirring, until pale golden, about 45 seconds. Increase heat to medium-high, then add greens and sea salt and saut until coated with oil and heated through, about 4 minutes.

name: Lemon and Thyme Cod
description:
1 serving of lemon and thyme cod  contains 343 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 35% carbs, 34% fat, and 30% protein.  This is a good source of protein (47% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (26% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Prepare rice according to package directions.

Pat Cod fillets dry with a paper towel and season with salt and pepper.

Heat oil in a medium nonstick sauté pan. Cook fillets for about 3 minutes on each side, or until it has started to flake and they have turned a golden brown. Place fillets on a plate and cover with aluminum foil to keep warm.

In the same sauté pan, warm butter, thyme, garlic, and lemon juice until melted. Drizzle over Cod fillets and serve with rice.Recipe inspired by: http://www.thewaytohisheartblog.com/lemon-thyme-pan-seared-cod-with-multi-grain-rice/

name: Bacon Wrapped Turkey Breast Stuffed with Spinach and Feta
description:
1 serving of bacon wrapped turkey breast stuffed with spinach and feta  contains 238 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 7% carbs, 65% fat, and 29% protein.  This is a good source of protein (30% of your Daily Value), potassium (7% of your Daily Value), and vitamin k (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350°F (175°C).Butterfly the turkey breast by slicing it down the middle and laying it flat.Season the inside of the turkey breast with salt, pepper, oregano, and cumin.Layer half of the spinach on one side of the butterflied turkey breast, sprinkle with half the feta cheese, then top with the remaining spinach.Fold the other half of the turkey breast over to enclose the filling and wrap the entire breast with bacon, ensuring the bacon covers both the top and bottom.Place the wrapped turkey breast in a baking dish and season with salt and pepper.Bake for 30 minutes, then broil on low for about 2 minutes per side, or until the bacon is crispy.Check the internal temperature of the turkey breast to ensure it reaches 165°F (74°C). If needed, bake for a little longer. Enjoy!

name: Eggplant Parmesan
description:
1 slice of eggplant parmesan  contains 588 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 23% carbs, 54% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (60% of your Daily Value), fiber (19% of your Daily Value), and potassium (11% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Slice the eggplants into 1/4-inch to 1/2-inch thick rounds. Lay the eggplant slices out on a rack over a rimmed sheet pan (or on several layers of paper towels). Sprinkle both sides of the eggplant rounds lightly with salt. Let the eggplant rounds sit and release moisture for 2 hours.Heat olive oil in a 4-quart saucepan on medium heat. Add the minced garlic and gently cook for 1 minute or until fragrant. Add the tomatoes and their juices. Increase heat to bring to a simmer, lower heat to maintain a very low simmer for 15 minutes, uncovered. Add salt and pepper to taste. Add the minced basil and remove from heat.Add breadcrumbs to a shallow bowl or dish. Set up your station so that you have flour in one shallow bowl, beaten eggs in another bowl, and the breadcrumb cheese mixture in another, in that order.Preheat the oven to 425 degrees F. Spread a tablespoon of olive oil each over the bottom of two rimmed baking sheet pans. Pat dry the eggplant slices with paper towels. Working one at a time dredge the eggplant slices first in the flour, then dip in the beaten eggs, and then dredge in the breadcrumb/parmesan cheese mixture. Place on oiled sheet pan. Drizzle a little oil over the top of each breaded eggplant round.Place breaded prepared eggplant slices in the oven. Cook for 18 to 20 minutes, turning the slices over at the half-way point, until they are nicely browned. Remove from oven, and let cool to touch. Reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees F.Spread 1/2 cup of the tomato sauce over the bottom of a 9x13-inch casserole dish. Place a third of the eggplant rounds in a single layer covering the sauce on the bottom of the pan.Layer half of the sliced mozzarella on top of the eggplant rounds. Sprinkle 1/3 of grated Parmesan cheese. Place another third of the eggplant rounds over the cheese. Spread 1 cup of the sauce over the eggplant rounds. Layer the rest of the sliced mozzarella over the sauce. Sprinkle with half remaining grated Parmesan. Add the remaining eggplant in a single layer on top of the cheese. Top with the remaining sauce and the remaining Parmesan. Bake uncovered at 350 degrees F for 35 minutes. Remove from oven and let sit for 10 minutes before cutting into to serve

name: Sesame Mushroom Quinoa Salad with Soft Boiled Eggs
description:
1 serving of sesame mushroom quinoa salad with soft boiled eggs  contains 291 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 44% carbs, 34% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (30% of your Daily Value), fiber (16% of your Daily Value), and potassium (15% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Combine 1 cup quinoa with 2 cups of water. Bring to a boil, reduce heat, cover and simmer until quinoa is fully cooked and can easily be fluffed with a fork, about 12-15 minutes.

Heat sesame oil and grapeseed oil over medium heat in a medium-sized skillet. Add mushrooms; cook, tossing often, until browned, about 10 minutes.

Add scallions to the mushrooms and cook until scallions are tender. About 3-5 minutes.

Meanwhile, soft boil eggs. Add eggs to a pan and cover with water. Bring to a boil and boil for 5 minutes. Remove from, drain, and peel.

In a large bowl toss the mushrooms and quinoa. Add the cilantro and toss some more. Divide salad evenly among plates and top with soft boiled eggs and a drizzle of soy sauce. Enjoy!

name: Cod with Pineapple Avocado Salsa
description:
1 serving of cod with pineapple avocado salsa  contains 207 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 31% carbs, 27% fat, and 42% protein.  This is a good source of protein (40% of your Daily Value), fiber (15% of your Daily Value), and potassium (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.

In a small bowl, combine pineapple, avocado, cucumber, red onion, 1 tablespoon of the lime juice, and a pinch of salt and mix until well incorporated. Set aside to allow flavors to meld.

Meanwhile, very lightly grease a baking dish with cooking oil. Sprinkle cod with salt and pepper and remaining lime juice before transferring to baking dish. Bake until cod is opaque and flakes easily with a fork, about 15-20 minutes depending on thickness.

Remove from pan and top with salsa before serving. If desired, serve over a bed of spinach. Enjoy!

name: Grain-Free Apple Almond Pancakes
description:
1 serving of grain-free apple almond pancakes  contains 263 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 15% carbs, 72% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of protein (16% of your Daily Value), fiber (14% of your Daily Value), and potassium (8% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions In a food processor grind the almonds into a fine meal, stopping before almond butter.
Continue with all the other ingredients in any order, either in your food processor or in a mixing bowl. Mix well.
Add more coconut milk if needed for thinner batter. Cook over medium to medium-high heat in butter or coconut oil until bubbly and slightly dry on the edges, and flip once.
Note: Recommended to be served with butter and maple syrup. Leftovers will refrigerate or freeze fine; can be reheated in the toaster oven.

name: Roasted Acorn Squash with Chile Vinaigrette
description:
1 serving of roasted acorn squash with chile vinaigrette  contains 271 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 33% carbs, 64% fat, and 3% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (17% of your Daily Value), vitamin b6 (27% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (38% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Finely chop cilantro and pepper, keeping seeds of pepper for additional heat if desired.Put oven racks in upper and lower thirds of oven and preheat oven to 450F. Halve squash lengthwise, then cut off and discard stem ends. Scoop out seeds and cut squash lengthwise into 3/4-inch-wide wedges. Toss squash with black pepper, 3/4 teaspoon salt, and 2 tablespoons oil in a bowl, then arrange, cut sides down, in 2 large shallow baking pans. Roast squash, switching position of pans halfway through roasting, until squash is tender and undersides of wedges are golden brown, 25 to 35 minutes.While squash roasts, mince garlic and mash to a paste with remaining 1/4 teaspoon salt. Transfer paste to a small bowl and whisk in lime juice, chile (to taste), cilantro, and remaining 1/4 cup oil until combined. Transfer squash, browned sides up, to a platter and drizzle with vinaigrette.

name: Castellane with Mascarpone and Roasted Grape Tomatoes
description:
1 serving of castellane with mascarpone and roasted grape tomatoes  contains 476 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 51% carbs, 34% fat, and 15% protein.  This is a good source of protein (33% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and calcium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Halve cherry tomatoes lengthwise. Put oven rack in upper third of oven and preheat oven to 400F. Line a large shallow baking pan with foil and butter foil.Arrange tomatoes, cut sides up, in pan and sprinkle with 1/2 teaspoon salt and 1/4 teaspoon black pepper. Roast until slightly plumped, 15 to 20 minutes.Cook pasta in a 6- to 8-quart pot of boiling salted water , stirring occasionally, until al dente, about 12 minutes. Reserve 1 1/2 cups pasta cooking water, then drain pasta well and transfer to a large bowl. Add mascarpone and stir until melted. Add reserved cooking water, tomatoes, half of parmesan, 3 tablespoons chives, 3/4 teaspoon salt, and 1/2 teaspoon black pepper and toss well, then cool to warm.Butter a 3-quart (13- by 9-inch) gratin or other shallow baking dish. Toss pasta mixture again, then spoon into gratin dish. Sprinkle remaining parmesan over top. Bake pasta until golden and bubbly, 18 to 20 minutes. Sprinkle with remaining tablespoon chives.

name: Salmon with Agrodolce Sauce
description:
1 serving of salmon with agrodolce sauce  contains 741 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 48% fat, and 44% protein.  This is a good source of protein (142% of your Daily Value), potassium (44% of your Daily Value), and iron (45% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat 1 tablespoon oil in a 12-inch nonstick skillet over medium heat until hot. Pat salmon dry and sprinkle with 1 teaspoon salt and 1/2 teaspoon pepper, then cook, skin side up, until undersides form a golden crust, 12 to 15 minutes. Turn fish over and cook until just cooked through, about 3 minutes more.Meanwhile, heat remaining 2 tablespoons oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat until it shimmers. Cut onions into small wedges, then saut onions until golden brown and crisp-tender, 6 to 8 minutes. Stir in vinegar, sugar, and 1/2 teaspoon salt and cook until sauce is syrupy, about 2 minutes. Remove from heat and stir in butter.Spoon onions with sauce onto plates and top with salmon, skin side down.

name: Puffy Corn Omelet
description:
1 serving of puffy corn omelet  contains 261 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 24% carbs, 62% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of protein (16% of your Daily Value) and vitamin a (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Put oven rack in middle position and preheat oven to 350F.Add corn to a 4-quart pot of boiling salted water , then remove from heat and let stand, covered, 10 minutes. Drain and, when cool enough to handle, cut kernels from cobs with a sharp knife into a bowl, then scrape cobs over bowl to extract "milk."Melt butter in a 10-inch ovenproof nonstick skillet (preferably lightweight) and remove skillet from heat, then transfer 3 tablespoons melted butter to bowl with corn (leaving remaining butter in skillet to cool). Toss corn to coat and stir in 1/4 teaspoon salt and 1/8 teaspoon pepper.Whisk egg yolks with remaining 1/4 teaspoon salt and 1/8 teaspoon pepper in a large bowl until combined. Beat whites with a pinch of salt in another bowl using an electric mixer at medium speed until they just hold stiff peaks. Fold one third of whites into yolks to lighten, then fold in remaining whites gently but thoroughly. Gently fold in corn mixture.Spoon mixture into skillet and bake until pale golden and set, 10 to 12 minutes. Loosen omelet with a heatproof rubber spatula and slide onto a plate. Serve sprinkled with chives.Grilling Procedure If using a charcoal grill, open vents on bottom of grill, then light charcoal. When charcoal turns grayish white (about 15 minutes from lighting), hold your hand 5 inches above grill rack to determine heat for charcoal as follows:Hot: When you can hold your hand there for 1 to 2 secondsMedium-hot: 3 to 4 secondsLow: 5 to 6 secondsIf using a gas grill, preheat burners on high, covered, 10 minutes, then, if necessary, reduce to heat specified in recipe.

name: Chilled Corn Soup
description:
1 serving of chilled corn soup  contains 549 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 50% carbs, 41% fat, and 8% protein.  This is a good source of protein (22% of your Daily Value), fiber (33% of your Daily Value), and potassium (18% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions PREPARATION:  Shuck corn.  Chop onion and garlic.Cut kernels from cobs with a sharp knife, then cut cobs into thirds.Cook onion and garlic in butter with 1/4 teaspoon salt in a large heavy saucepan over medium heat, stirring occasionally, until onion 
is softened, about 5 minutes. Add corn and cobs, water, 1 teaspoon salt, and 1/2 teaspoon pepper and simmer, uncovered, 20 minutes.Discard cobs, then pure corn mixture in batches in a blender until very smooth (use caution when blending hot liquids). Force soup through a fine-mesh sieve into a bowl, discarding solids.Chill until cold, at least 1 hour. Thin with water if desired and season with salt.

name: Slow Cooker Potato Soup
description:
1 cup of slow cooker potato soup  contains 337 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 28% carbs, 57% fat, and 15% protein.  This is a good source of protein (22% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and calcium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Combine all ingredients except the cream cheese in the slow cooker. Simmer on low for 8 hours.Add cream cheese 1 hour before serving to allow it to melt. Do not use fat-free cheese as it will not melt properly.Top with green onion, cheese, and sour cream before serving.

name: Quinoa Tacos
description:
1 serving of quinoa tacos  contains 263 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 50% carbs, 40% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (24% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Rinse quinoa in a strainer. Let drain.Heat a medium saucepan over medium heat. Once hot, add rinsed quinoa and toast for 4-5 minutes, stirring frequently.Add vegetable broth and water and bring to a boil over medium-high heat. Then reduce heat to low, cover with a secure lid, and cook for 15-20 minutes, or until liquid is completely absorbed. Fluff with a fork, then crack lid and let rest for 10 minutes off heat.Preheat oven to 375 degrees F (190 C).Add cooked quinoa to a large mixing bowl and add salsa, nutritional yeast, cumin, chili powder, garlic powder, salt, pepper, and oil. Toss to combine, then spread on a lightly greased (or parchment-lined) baking sheet.Bake for 20-35 minutes, stirring/tossing once at the halfway point to ensure even baking. The quinoa is done when it's fragrant and golden brown. Be careful not to burn!Serve in hard taco shells with diced tomato and avocado. Enjoy!

*Store leftovers in the refrigerator up to 4-5 days. Reheat in the microwave, in a 350 degree F (176 C) oven, or in a skillet on the stovetop.

name: Omelet Cupcakes
description:
1 serving of omelet cupcakes  contains 209 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 70% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (21% of your Daily Value), vitamin a (12% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b12 (30% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Cook bacon in a sauté pan over medium heat until desired crispiness is reached. Drain on paper towels, chop, and set aside.Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. Grease 8 muffin cups or line with paper liners.Beat eggs together in a large bowl.Mix bacon, bell pepper, onion, salt, black pepper, and water into the beaten eggs. Pour egg mixture evenly into prepared muffin cups.
Bake in the preheated oven until muffins are set in the middle, 18 to 20 minutes.

name: Coriander and Lemon Crusted Fish with Asparagus Salad & Poached Egg
description:
1 serving of coriander and lemon crusted fish with asparagus salad & poached egg  contains 281 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 9% carbs, 45% fat, and 45% protein.  This is a good source of protein (58% of your Daily Value), potassium (15% of your Daily Value), and iron (57% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Position a rack in upper third of oven; preheat broiler to high. Coat a rimmed baking sheet with cooking spray.Toast coriander in a small skillet over medium heat, shaking the pan frequently, until fragrant, about 3 minutes. Pulse the coriander, lemon zest, 1/2 teaspoon salt, and crushed red pepper in a spice grinder until finely ground. Coat the salmon flesh with the spice mixture (about 1 1/2 teaspoons per portion) and place the salmon on the prepared baking sheet.Cut off asparagus tips and very thinly slice stalks on the diagonal. Toss the tips and slices with oil, lemon juice, mint, tarragon, pepper, and the remaining 1/4 teaspoon salt. Let stand while you cook the salmon and eggs.Bring water and vinegar to a boil in a large saucepan.Meanwhile, broil the salmon until just cooked through, 3 to 6 minutes, depending on thickness. Tent with foil to keep warm.Reduce the boiling water to a bare simmer. Gently stir in a circle so the water is swirling around the pot. Crack eggs, one at a time, into the water. Cook until the whites are set but the yolks are still runny, 3 to 4 minutes.To serve, divide the asparagus salad and salmon among 4 plates. Make a nest in each salad and top with a poached egg.Recipe inspired by: http://www.eatingwell.com/recipes/coriander_lemon_crusted_salmon_asparagus_salad_poached_egg.html?socsrc=ewfb0601166

name: Turkey and Spinach Lasagna Rolls
description:
1 roll of turkey and spinach lasagna rolls  contains 348 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 30% carbs, 37% fat, and 33% protein.  This is a good source of protein (52% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and calcium (29% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Cook the lasagna noodles according to package directions. Drain and rinse the noodles and lay them flat on wax paper.

Heat oil in a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat. Add the turkey, onion, and bell pepper and cook, stirring frequently, until all the pan juices evaporate and the turkey browns, about 10 minutes. Stir in the marinara sauce and water; bring to a boil. Reduce the heat and simmer, uncovered, until slightly thickened and the flavors blend, about 5 minutes.

Preheat the oven to 375 degrees F. Meanwhile, combine the ricotta, spinach, basil, Parmesan, egg, and nutmeg in a medium bowl. Spread the ricotta mixture over the length of each noodle and roll up from one short end.

Spread half of the turkey mixture in the bottom of an 8x12-inch baking dish. Add the rolls. Top with the remaining turkey mixture. Cover with foil and bake 30 minutes. Remove the foil and sprinkle with the mozzarella. Bake until heated through and the top is golden, about 10 minutes longer.

name: Pumpkin Ravioli
description:
1 serving of pumpkin ravioli  contains 281 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 39% carbs, 47% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of protein (17% of your Daily Value), fiber (20% of your Daily Value), and calcium (16% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Boil a pot of lightly salted water and cook ravioli according to package directions. Make sure to save ¾-cup of pasta water once the ravioli have finished cooking.In a large skillet, sauté the onions and apples in butter and olive oil over high heat until they become tender and translucent, approximately 8 minutes. Stir often to avoid burning.Reduce heat to medium-low and add the white wine, thyme, sage, rosemary and black pepper. Cook for 5 minutes.Add the pumpkin and stir for an additional minute. Add the reserved pasta water and simmer on medium-low heat for an additional 8 minutes, or until sauce thickens.Add the ravioli to the pumpkin sauce and coat well. Portion out the ravioli, garnish with toasted almonds and enjoy!Recipe inspired by: http://feastonthecheap.net/ravioli-with-a-pumpkin-spiked-white-wine-reduction/

name: Open Face Veggie Hummus Lentil Toast
description:
1 serving of open face veggie hummus lentil toast  contains 489 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 41% carbs, 36% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (52% of your Daily Value), fiber (43% of your Daily Value), and potassium (20% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare lentils as per package directions. Set aside.Toast Bread. Mix lentils, chopped celery and chopped tomatoes in a small bowl.Spread hummus over toast. Scoop lentil mixture on top of hummus. Add sprouts and pumpkin seeds on top for garnish.

name: Maple Baked Apples
description:
1 apple of maple baked apples  contains 448 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 67% carbs, 29% fat, and 4% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (24% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and riboflavin (b2) (68% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.Using a paring knife, remove the apple cores and trim about a 1/2-inch slice from the bottom of each apple, so they sit flat. Place the apples in an ovenproof skillet or 8- to 9-inch baking dish.Drizzle with the syrup. Divide the walnuts and raisins among the apples, filling the cavities, and place any extra in the dish. Dot the apples with the butter. Bake until tender, 40 to 50 minutes.If using a baking dish, pour the liquid from the dish into a skillet. Bring to a boil over medium heat. Cook until it thickens slightly, 2 to 3 minutes. Spoon the sauce over the warm apples and serve with ice cream, if desired.

name: Moist Chocolate Muffins
description:
1 Muffin of moist chocolate muffins  contains 323 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 54% carbs, 40% fat, and 6% protein.  This has a relatively high calorie density, with 326 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F. Grease 12 muffin cups or line with paper muffin liners.Combine flour, sugar, 3/4 cup of the chocolate chips, cocoa powder, and baking soda in a large bowl. Whisk egg, vanilla, yogurt, milk, and vegetable oil in another bowl until smooth; pour into chocolate mixture and stir until batter is just blended. Fill prepared muffin cups 3/4 full and sprinkle with remaining 1/4 cup chocolate chips.Bake in preheated oven until a toothpick inserted into the center comes out clean, about 20 minutes. Cool in the pans for 10 minutes before removing to cool completely on a wire rack.Recipe inspired by: https://www.allrecipes.com/recipe/228553/moist-chocolate-muffins/

name: Balsamic Pork Chops
description:
1 serving of balsamic pork chops  contains 523 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 10% carbs, 54% fat, and 36% protein.  This is a good source of protein (84% of your Daily Value), potassium (22% of your Daily Value), and calcium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat 1 tablespoon oil in a skillet over medium heat. Stir in the onion and cook until golden brown. Set aside.Heat 1/2 tablespoon oil in the skillet. Season pork chops with salt, pepper, and garlic powder, and place in the skillet. Cook to desired doneness, about 5-8  minutes per side (depending on thickness). Set aside and keep warm.Heat remaining oil in the skillet. Return onions to skillet, and stir in tomatoes, garlic, and basil. Cook and stir about 3 minutes, until tomatoes are tender. Mix in balsamic vinegar, and season with salt and pepper. Top chops with the onion and tomato mixture, and sprinkle with feta cheese to serve.

name: Roasted Blueberry Quinoa Parfaits with Coconut Granola
description:
1 parfait of roasted blueberry quinoa parfaits with coconut granola  contains 713 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 37% carbs, 52% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of protein (36% of your Daily Value), fiber (27% of your Daily Value), and potassium (15% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions For granola: Preheat oven to 375 degrees F. Line a baking sheet with aluminum foil

In a large bowl, combine oats, coconut, sugar, cinnamon and salt. Melt coconut oil and add it to the oats, along with honey and vanilla; stir thoroughly to moisten. Spread on a baking sheet and bake for 20-25 minutes, tossing every 5 minutes. Remove and let sit for about 10 minutes to get crumbly.For parfaits: Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.
