instructions: Directions Combine oats, water, and honey in pot and boil until tender. Chop the nectarines and blend the strawberries into a sauce. Fold into the porridge and enjoy!

name: Low Carb Lettuce Burger
description:
1 serving of low carb lettuce burger (Recipe courtesy of Ree Drummond) contains 741 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 65% fat, and 27% protein.  This is a good source of protein (90% of your Daily Value), fiber (21% of your Daily Value), and potassium (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions For the sauce: Mix together the yogurt, adobo sauce, mustard, and Worcestershire sauce in a small bowl. Set aside.

For the burgers: In a bowl, combine the ground chuck, salt, black pepper, and Worcestershire sauce. Form four patties and set aside.

Heat a skillet over medium-high heat. Cook the patties until done in the middle, 4 to 6 minutes per side.

For the toppings: Cut the base of each lettuce leaf on the head and carefully peel it away so that it stays as intact as possible. Place patties onto these large leaves.

Top the patties with avocado slices, tomato slices, red onion rings, and chopped pickles, then drizzle with the sauce to taste. Use two lettuce leaves per patty and wrap them around the patty as tightly as you can. Slice in half and serve immediately.
Enjoy!

name: Peppers, Tomatoes, and Potatoes
description:
1 serving of peppers, tomatoes, and potatoes  contains 477 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 81% carbs, 9% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of protein (23% of your Daily Value), fiber (61% of your Daily Value), and potassium (58% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Peel potatoes and add to a pot, covered with water. Bring to a boil and cook until fork tender.Chop peppers and tomatoes.Put them into a pan and add olive oil or any other oil of your choice. Allows excess water to evaporate, about 15 minutes.Serve potatoes with the pepper mixture and enjoy!

name: Crêpes
description:
4 crepes of crêpes  contains 615 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 74% carbs, 14% fat, and 12% protein.  This is a good source of protein (32% of your Daily Value), potassium (8% of your Daily Value), and calcium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Whisk eggs and sugar in a bowl.Slowly whisk in whole milk and wheat flour.Heat a non-stick skillet over medium heat; spray with non-stick spray.Pour some batter into the pan and tilt the pan to coat the bottom thinly and evenly. Allow to cook until it begins to brown. Flip the crêpe and let brown on the other side. Remove from pan and repeat with remaining batter.

name: Linguine with Red, Yellow, and Orange Tomatoes
description:
1 serving of linguine with red, yellow, and orange tomatoes  contains 518 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 43% carbs, 40% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (39% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and calcium (25% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook pasta in large pot of boiling salted water until just tender but still firm to bite, stirring occasionally. While pasta is cooking, dice tomatoes into small chunks. Chop watercress.Meanwhile, heat oil in heavy large skillet over medium-high heat. Add garlic and crushed pepper; stir 30 seconds. Add tomatoes; saut just until heated through, about 2 minutes. Mix in vinegar; season sauce with salt and pepper.Drain pasta and add to skillet; add watercress and 1 cup Parmesan cheese. Toss until watercress wilts and sauce coats pasta. Transfer to bowl. Serve, passing additional cheese separately.

name: Bangladeshi-Style Chicken Korma
description:
1 serving of bangladeshi-style chicken korma  contains 627 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 4% carbs, 61% fat, and 35% protein.  This is a good source of protein (97% of your Daily Value), potassium (19% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (18% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cut chicken into bite-sized pieces and set aside. Cut the onion in half: finely chop one half and thinly slice the other half. Set both aside.Heat the butter and olive oil in a large frying pan over medium heat.When the oil is hot, add the cinnamon stick, bay leaves, and cardamom pods to the pan. Let them sizzle for a few seconds.Add the sliced onions to the pan and cook until lightly browned, about 2-3 minutes.Add the chicken to the pan and stir well. Cook for 10 minutes.In a small bowl, combine the chopped onion, grated ginger, crushed garlic, curry powder, and 1/2 teaspoon of salt. Add the heavy cream and mix well.Pour the cream mixture over the chicken, stir well, and cook for 5 minutes.Add 2-3 tablespoons of water to the pan, cover, and simmer for 10 minutes, or until the water has evaporated and the chicken is cooked through. Serve hot.

name: Sloppy Joes and Mushrooms
description:
1 serving of sloppy joes and mushrooms  contains 450 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 34% carbs, 32% fat, and 34% protein.  This is a good source of protein (71% of your Daily Value), potassium (19% of your Daily Value), and iron (65% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Coat a large skillet with spray and place over medium heat. Add turkey and mushrooms. Cook for 3 minutes, stirring to break up the meat. Add garlic powder, then reduce heat to low and cook for another 3 minutes.Stir in ketchup, vinegar, mustard, chili powder, and Worcestershire sauce. Continue cooking over low heat for 5-10 minutes, stirring occasionally.Season with pepper to taste. Serve on toasted buns and enjoy!

name: Layered Mushroom Cabbage Casserole
description:
1 serving of layered mushroom cabbage casserole  contains 315 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 67% carbs, 23% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of protein (15% of your Daily Value), fiber (34% of your Daily Value), and potassium (16% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Put stone-ground yellow cornmeal in cold water for 3-4 hours and drain well before using. Preheat oven to 400F (200C). Puree tomatoes in a food processor or blender and set aside. Dice mushrooms, onions, and dill.In a frying pan heat oil over medium high heat. Cook onion for about 5 minutes, until soft. Add mushrooms and cook until any water has evaporated. Stir in paprika, rice and stone-ground cornmeal, fresh dill, salt and pepper. Remove from heat. Split the mushroom mixture in 2. Cut the cabbage into quarters, remove the white hard core and cut each quarter using a mandolin or a sharp knife. Sprinkle with salt and split in 3. Assemble the layers in a 10 inch ceramic baking dish. One layer of cabbage, one of mushroom mixture, cabbage, mushroom mixture and finish with cabbage layer. Mix the tomatoes with water an pour all over the surface of the casserole.Cover with aluminum foil or a lid and bake for about 1 hour. For the last 5 minutes remove the lid and use the broiler function. Enjoy!

name: Vegan White Bean Pate
description:
1 serving of vegan white bean pate  contains 225 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 55% carbs, 28% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (17% of your Daily Value), fiber (25% of your Daily Value), and potassium (17% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Roughly chop the onion and garlic. Fry them in one tbsp oil for a couple of minutes over medium heat until lightly browned. When ready, throw both into a large mixing bowl.Drain and rinse the beans and place them in the bowl. Finally, add the rest of the ingredients and using a hand blender, give it all a good blend. Alternatively throw it all in a food processor instead. Serve with cucumber slices. Enjoy!

name: Collards
description:
1 serving of collards  contains 143 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 67% carbs, 22% fat, and 12% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (13% of your Daily Value), vitamin b6 (33% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (35% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Place potatoes in a large pot with enough water to cover. Bring to a boil over medium heat. Before the potatoes are finished, add the collards to the pot.Place bacon in a deep skillet over medium-high heat. Cook until evenly browned, about 10 minutes. Remove bacon to paper towels to drain, and saute the onion in bacon grease until tender. Drain onions of grease, and add to the greens. Crumble in the bacon, and stir in the wine vinegar. Simmer over low heat until greens are tender, about 1 hour.

name: Roasted Fennel, Carrots, and Shallots
description:
1 serving of roasted fennel, carrots, and shallots  contains 126 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 46% carbs, 48% fat, and 7% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (19% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (65% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Position 1 rack in top third and 1 rack in bottom third of oven and preheat to 425F. Brush 2 large rimmed baking sheets with oil; warm sheets in oven 10 minutes.Quarter fennel bulbs through core. Cut each quarter into 3 wedges; place in large bowl. Add 2 tablespoons oil, sprinkle with salt and pepper, and toss fennel to coat.Peel carrots and cut on a diagonal 1/4 inch thick ovals. Blanch shallots for 1 minute. Peel and cut in half through root end.Combine carrots and shallots in another large bowl. Add 2 tablespoons oil, sprinkle with salt and pepper, and toss to coat. Spread fennel on 1 hot baking sheet and carrot-shallot mixture on second sheet. Return sheets to oven; roast vegetables 10 minutes. Reverse sheets. Roast vegetables 20 minutes. Turn vegetables over. Roast until tender, 10 to 15 minutes longer.Arrange vegetables on platter. Sprinkle with parsley. Garnish with fennel fronds.

name: Tomato Avocado Burgers
description:
1 serving of tomato avocado burgers  contains 287 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 17% carbs, 46% fat, and 37% protein.  This is a good source of protein (50% of your Daily Value), fiber (21% of your Daily Value), and potassium (23% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cut the tomatoes in half horizontally. With the handle-end of a spoon or a fork, scoop out the seeds and seeds membrane. Set aside.Place half of the avocado in a bowl and mash with a fork until almost smooth. Add yogurt, mayo, lime juice, and cumin, and stir to combine. Dice remaining half of the avocado and add it alongside ¼ teaspoon salt. Stir gently to combine. Set aside.In a bowl season ground beef with ½ teaspoon of salt, black pepper, and chili powder, and mix well. Divide into equal 4 portions and gently shape each portion into ½ inch thick patty.Preheat grill (or grill pan) to medium-high heat. Grill patties 3 minutes on each side or until desired degree of doneness.In the meantime, lightly grease with olive oil a medium non-stick pan/skillet and heat over medium-high heat. Cook halved tomatoes face down for 2 to 3 minutes, until they begin to brown. Flip and cook for 20 seconds on the other side so that they get a bit of color.To assemble burgers, place a large pinch of sprouts on the bottom part of each tomato, top with a beef patty, about 2 tablespoons of avocado sauce and finish with the other half of each tomato. Enjoy!

name: Cowboy Breakfast Skillet
description:
1 serving of cowboy breakfast skillet  contains 294 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 20% carbs, 61% fat, and 19% protein.  This is a good source of protein (25% of your Daily Value), potassium (7% of your Daily Value), and calcium (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Add canola oil to large oven-safe skillet over medium-heat. Heat oil.Add potatoes to skillet. Season with salt and pepper. Brown potatoes until crisp.Add 1/2 cup cheddar cheese, eggs, remaining cheese, and scallions.Bake for 10 minutes, or until eggs have set and cheese has melted. Enjoy!

name: Skinny Cheeseburger Stuffed Peppers
description:
1 serving of skinny cheeseburger stuffed peppers  contains 529 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 25% carbs, 53% fat, and 22% protein.  This is a good source of protein (52% of your Daily Value), fiber (18% of your Daily Value), and potassium (20% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare rice as per package directions; set aside. Cut off the top of 4 bell peppers about 1-inch down from top. Clean out seeds and membranes. Throw away the tops. Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.In a large nonstick pan, brown ground beef and onions. Season beef with a little salt and pepper. Be sure to break up ground beef into small pieces as it cooks.Stir in Worcestershire sauce, ketchup, mustard, pickle relish, tomato sauce, and 3 tablespoons water. Mix well. Stir in ¾ cup shredded cheese and cooked rice. Mix well and continue to cook until heated through. Add 1-2 more tablespoons of water, if getting a little dry. Remove from heat.Stuff each bell pepper with ground beef mixture, top each stuffed pepper with 1 tablespoon shredded cheese. Place each in a 9-inch baking dish.  Pour 1 cup water in bottom of baking dish. Cover dish with foil and bake for 40-45 minutes. If peppers are not soft enough, cook about 5 minutes more.Recipe inspired by: http://www.skinnykitchen.com/recipes/skinny-cheeseburger-stuffed-peppers/

name: Skillet Chicken with Creamy Cilantro Lime Sauce.
description:
1 serving of skillet chicken with creamy cilantro lime sauce.  contains 379 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 2% carbs, 65% fat, and 33% protein.  This is a good source of protein (56% of your Daily Value), potassium (8% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (15% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375 degrees F.Ppound chicken breasts to even thickness. Sprinkle each with salt and pepper.In a large ovenproof skillet heat the oil over medium-high heat. Add the chicken and cook for 6-7 minutes, turning once. You want the chicken nice and browned on the outside. (It doesn't have to be cooked all the way through yet.) Set chicken on a plate and cover tightly with foil.Remove skillet from heat and add the broth, lime juice, onion, cilantro, and red pepper. Return to heat. Cook and stir to scrape up the browned bits from the bottom of the skillet. Bring to a boil. Allow to boil gently, uncovered, for 10 minutes or until the liquid is reduced to around 1/4 cup. Reduce heat to medium-low, then add the cream and butter. Stir until butter has melted.Add chicken to the sauce and place the skillet in the preheated oven. Bake uncovered until the chicken is completely cooked through, about 5-10 minutes.Serve chicken with sauce spooned on top. Enjoy!

name: Crispy Asian Brussels Sprouts
description:
1 serving of crispy asian brussels sprouts  contains 181 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 40% carbs, 48% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (17% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (129% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F and move rack to topmost position.Prepare the brussel sprouts by cutting off the base of each sprout, slicing them in half from top to bottom and remove the excess or loose exterior leaves.
Soak the cut brussel sprouts for a minute in water to clean them.Drain and spread brussel sprouts out on a paper towel to dry while the oven is preheating.Cover a large rimmed baking sheet with foil and spread the brussel sprouts out on the pan.Generously drizzle the brussel sprouts with the oil and sprinkle with kosher salt. Stir with your hands to ensure brussels are all well-oiled and salted.Place in the oven on the top rack for about 45-60 minutes. After 20 and 40 minutes, stir the brussel sprouts to ensure all sides get crispy and charred.During the last 5-10 minutes of cooking, reduce remaining ingredients (soy sauce, maple syrup, garlic, sriracha, lemon juice and black pepper) in a sauté pan over medium-high heat until sauce is thickened, about 5 minutes.Remove brussel sprouts from the oven once all sprouts are crispy and slightly charred.Place them in a bowl and toss with some of the reduced sauce. Do this a little at a time as you don’t want them to be soaked in sauce, so they retain their crispy texture. You may have a little leftover sauce. Recipe inspired by: http://thebakermama.com/recipes/crispy-asian-brussels-sprouts/

name: Healthy Chicken Fajita Casserole
description:
1 serving of healthy chicken fajita casserole  contains 487 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 34% carbs, 38% fat, and 28% protein.  This is a good source of protein (61% of your Daily Value), fiber (23% of your Daily Value), and potassium (18% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions In a small bowl mix the chili powder, paparika, salt, cumin, onion powder, garlic powder, and oregano. Use half of the mixture to season the chicken; set the remainder aside.Heat a large skillet over medium-high with 1 tsp olive oil. Sauté the peppers and onion in two batches until they just start to soften (3 minutes).  Season with salt and pepper, to taste.  Set aside.Preheat oven to 375 degrees F.In the same skillet, lightly drizzle the pan with olive oil and cook the chicken strips, on medium heat about 4-5 minutes on each side or until juices run clear when thickest part is sliced.  Remove the chicken from pan and cube into bite sized pieces. In a large bowl, combine the beans, tomatoes, and the remaining fajita seasoning.  Add the chicken and pepper/onions and mix all together.  Place 1/2 cup or so of the mixture on the bottom of a 9x13" baking dish, and spread out.  Next, place 3-4 tortillas on top (its okay if they overlap).  Then add more chicken mixture on top - covering all tortillas.  One more layer tortillas on top of that and then top with the remaining chicken mixture.  Finally top with cheese, cover with aluminum foil and bake for 30 minutes.  Remove aluminum foil and bake for an additional 10-15 minutes.  Slice like lasagna and serve warm. Recipe inspired by: http://www.hungryhappens.com/recipes/dinner/healthy-chicken-fajita-casserole.html

name: Apple Cookies
description:
2 cookies of apple cookies  contains 367 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 64% carbs, 30% fat, and 6% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (16% of your Daily Value) and vitamin a (12% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350°F. Peel the apple(s), dice the flesh, and discard the seeds and core. Toss the diced apple pieces with 2 tablespoons flour and set aside.In a medium bowl, whisk together the remaining 1 cup flour, oats, salt, cinnamon, and baking soda.In a large bowl, cream together the butter and sugars. Mix in the maple syrup, egg, and powdered sugar.Add the dry ingredients to the wet ingredients and mix until just combined. Stir in the flour-coated apple pieces.Drop spoonfuls of cookie dough onto a lightly greased baking sheet.Bake for 10-14 minutes, or until golden brown. Allow to cool for 10 minutes on the baking sheet, then transfer to a cooling rack to finish cooling completely. Enjoy!

name: Seared Chilean Sea Bass
description:
4 serving of seared chilean sea bass (with Asian Glaze and Sesame Spinach) contains 891 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 12% carbs, 45% fat, and 43% protein.  This is a good source of protein (168% of your Daily Value), fiber (27% of your Daily Value), and potassium (41% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Wash and pat dry sea bass fillets. Drizzle with fish sauce, lemon juice, and add salt and pepper to taste on both sides.Heat pan over medium-high heat until hot. Add 1 teaspoon sesame oil. When hot add sea bass fillets, in a single layer. Cook for 4-6 minutes per side until browned and cooked through. Add 1 more teaspoon sesame oil if needed.In a small bowl whisk together the sauce ingredients - lime juice, minced ginger, fish sauce, rice vinegar, agave, 1 teaspoon sesame oil, olive oil, and sambal olek (thai chili garlic sauce). Whisk until smooth.Remove cooked fish from pan and drain on paper towels. In the same pan cook the spinach in 1 teaspoon remaining sesame oil until just wilted, about 1-2 minutes.To plate, first divide spinach onto four plates, sprinkle with sesame seeds, top with sea bass, and drizzle with sauce.

name: Sinless Deviled Eggs
description:
2 eggs of sinless deviled eggs  contains 174 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 5% carbs, 58% fat, and 36% protein.  This is a good source of protein (27% of your Daily Value), vitamin a (20% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b12 (45% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Place the eggs in a single layer in a large saucepan. Cover with water to 1 inch above eggs; bring just to a boil. Remove from heat; cover and let stand 15 minutes. Drain and cover the eggs in ice-cold water until cool enough to handle.
Peel the eggs and halve eggs lengthwise with a sharp knife. Gently remove the yolks. Place 18 yolk halves in a food processor or blender (discard the rest). Add yogurt, mayonnaise, mustard, salt and paprika; process until smooth.
Pipe or spoon about 1 tablespoon of yolk mixture into each egg white half. Cover and chill for at least 1 hour. Top with relish before serving.

name: Australian Vegemite Pasta
description:
1 serving of australian vegemite pasta  contains 524 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 63% carbs, 18% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (45% of your Daily Value), calcium (24% of your Daily Value), and iron (52% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare pasta as per package directions, until al dente.Drain pasta and return to pot.Stir in Vegemite until mixed through.Serve with grated cheese on top and enjoy!

name: Fish Stick Wrap
description:
1 serving of fish stick wrap  contains 326 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 55% carbs, 28% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook fish fingers following instructions on packaging .Wrap the fish fingers in the tortilla. Top with ketchup. Enjoy!

name: Chicken and Black Bean Burrito Bowl
description:
1 serving of chicken and black bean burrito bowl  contains 594 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 60% carbs, 20% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (54% of your Daily Value), fiber (37% of your Daily Value), and potassium (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.Combine 2 1/2 cups water with 2 cups of brown rice. Bring to a bowl, reduce to a simmer, and cook covered for 30-45 minutes until rice is tender and water is absorbed. Remove from heat and set aside.Pat chicken breast dry and season with salt and pepper. Place on a baking sheet and bake uncovered for 25-35 minutes until no longer pink and cooked through. Remove from heat and allow to rest for at least 10 minutes. Chop into bite sized pieces and set aside.Chop cilantro and avocado.Combine cooked rice, lime juice, and cilantro in a medium bowl; mix well.Evenly divide lettuce between 4 serving bowls. Top evenly with rice mixture, beans, chicken, cheese, salsa, and avocado.Top each bowl with 1 Tbsp. of yogurt; serve immediately.

name: Mahi-Mahi with Fresh Cilantro Chutney
description:
1 serving of mahi-mahi with fresh cilantro chutney  contains 333 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 13% carbs, 41% fat, and 46% protein.  This is a good source of protein (69% of your Daily Value), potassium (7% of your Daily Value), and iron (51% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Finely chop jalapeno, removing seeds. Finely chop cilantro. Peel and cut kiwi into small cubes. Coarsely puree first 5 ingredients in processor. Season chutney with salt and pepper. Sprinkle fish with salt, pepper, and cumin. Heat oil in medium skillet over medium heat. Add fish. Saute until just opaque in center, about 5 minutes per side. Transfer to plates; top with chutney.

name: Salad with Homemade Creamy Sesame Dressing
description:
1 serving of salad with homemade creamy sesame dressing  contains 169 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 39% carbs, 49% fat, and 12% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (17% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and calcium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Lightly toast unhulled sesame seeds in a pan over medium heat for 3 minutes, shaking pan frequently.Blend all ingredients except lettuce and tomatoes in a high-powered blender until smooth and creamy. Serve dressing over lettuce and top with cherry tomatoes.

name: Basic Crock Pot Black Eyed Peas
description:
1 serving of basic crock pot black eyed peas  contains 77 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 84% carbs, 3% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (15% of your Daily Value) and potassium (8% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Rinse the black-eyed peas in a colander under cold running water. Pick them over and remove any damaged or malformed peas. Put the peas in the slow cooker along with the quartered and sliced onion and minced garlic. Add the freshly ground black pepper and the water.Cover the slow cooker and cook on low for about 5 to 6 hours (about 3 hours on high). Taste and add salt or a seasoned salt blend, as desired. Continue cooking for 15 to 20 minutes. Serve warm.

name: Skinny Mexican Chicken and Brown Rice Casserole
description:
1 serving of skinny mexican chicken and brown rice casserole  contains 550 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 51% carbs, 27% fat, and 22% protein.  This is a good source of protein (56% of your Daily Value), fiber (26% of your Daily Value), and potassium (25% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. Coat a 9x9 inch square baking pan or 2-quart casserole with cooking spray; set aside.Heat oil in a skillet over medium-high heat. Add chicken and cook for 7-12 minutes, or until cooked through and no longer pink. Set aside.In a large saucepan, cook rice according to package directions.Meanwhile, in a microwave safe bowl, add the onions and garlic and cook in the microwave for about 1 minute, to soften onions.When rice is done, add it to a large mixing bowl. Mix in cooked onions and garlic, corn, diced chicken, tomatoes, tomato sauce, ½ cup of the cheese, chili powder, and cumin.  Mix well. Transfer to the casserole dish. Sprinkle with the remaining ½ cup cheese. Bake, uncovered, for 20 to 25 minutes or until cheese is lightly browned and casserole is heated through.Cool at least 10 minutes to set. Cut into 6 servings. Enjoy!Recipe inspired by: http://www.skinnykitchen.com/recipes/skinny-mexican-chicken-and-brown-rice-casserole/

name: Light Loaded Potato Soup
description:
1 serving of light loaded potato soup  contains 328 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 50% carbs, 33% fat, and 16% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value), potassium (24% of your Daily Value), and calcium (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook bacon in a sauté pan over medium heat until desired crispiness is reach, chop and set aside.Heat the oil in a Dutch oven or large heavy bottomed saucepan over medium-high heat. Add the onion and cook for 3 minutes. Add the broth and the potatoes. Bring to a simmer. Cook the potatoes, covered, until they are fork tender, about 15 minutes.Combine the flour and the milk in a large measuring cup. Bring to a boil, stirring often, being careful to not let the milk boil over. Cook for 1 minute. Coarsely mash potatoes into soup using a potato masher. For a smoother texture, use an immersion blender to blend the soup. Remove from heat and stir in sour cream, salt, and pepper.Ladle the soup into four bowls and top with the bacon, cheese, and green onions.Recipe inspired by: http://www.handletheheat.com/light-loaded-potato-soup/#jump

name: Avocado and Chicken Quesadilla
description:
1 serving of avocado and chicken quesadilla  contains 1024 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 24% carbs, 53% fat, and 22% protein.  This is a good source of protein (105% of your Daily Value), fiber (63% of your Daily Value), and potassium (43% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Heat oil in a skillet over medium-high heat. Add chopped chicken and sauté until cooked through and no longer pink; set aside.Spread sliced or mashed avocado on a whole wheat tortilla.
Add chicken, cheeses, beans, and chopped bell pepper to one side of the open tortilla. Sprinkle over with cilantro. Once you pack in the ingredients, fold the empty part of the tortilla over the other half so that it easily closes. Gently mash down on it once you fold it over in order to pack in the ingredients.
Coat a nonstick skillet with olive oil and set it on medium high heat. Toss in the quesadilla and cook on each side until the quesadilla is golden brown and crispy.

Slice down the middle and enjoy! Serve with salsa.

name: Chicken and Zucchini Noodle Caprese
description:
1 serving of chicken and zucchini noodle caprese  contains 412 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 14% carbs, 54% fat, and 32% protein.  This is a good source of protein (60% of your Daily Value), potassium (23% of your Daily Value), and calcium (23% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Start by cutting the zucchini into noodles by using a spiralizer or a peeler. Season the chicken with 1/2 teaspoon salt, pepper and oregano. In a large non-stick pan set over med-high heat, heat 1/2 tablespoon of the oil. Add the chicken and cook, stirring until browned and cooked through, about 6 minutes. Set aside.Reduce heat to medium, add the remaining oil and garlic and cook until golden, 30 seconds. Add the tomatoes, and crushed red pepper flakes, and season with 1/4 teaspoon of the remaining salt, and black pepper. Reduce the heat to low. Simmer, covered, until the tomatoes soften, 15 minutes.Increase heat to high, stir in the zucchini and basil, season with 1/4 teaspoon remaining salt and cook 2 minutes. Add the chicken back to the skillet along with the mozzarella and serve right away.
Enjoy!Recipe inspired by: http://www.skinnytaste.com/2015/12/chicken-zucchini-noodle-caprese.html

name: Breakfast Mac and Cheese
description:
1 serving of breakfast mac and cheese  contains 1043 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 22% carbs, 54% fat, and 24% protein.  This is a good source of protein (113% of your Daily Value), potassium (17% of your Daily Value), and calcium (57% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Set oven to 375 degrees F. Heat a sauté pan over medium heat and cook bacon until desired crispiness is reached. Drain bacon on paper towels and reserve fat in the pan. Crumble bacon; set aside.Cook pasta according to package directions until al dente. Drain and toss with the reserved bacon fat.Melt the butter in a saucepan and stir in the flour. Cook for about a minute, and then slowly pour in the milk, stirring or whisking constantly to combine all the flour into the milk. Continue heating and stirring until the mixture thickens, this will happen just as the milk is getting to the boiling point.Take the pan off the heat and add the cheese, a little at a time, stirring to melt.Add the cooked pasta and half the bacon crumbles to the sauce, tossing to combine well. Divide the mixture between 4 oven safe bowls.Make an indentation in the center of each bowl with the back of a large spoon for the egg. Crack an egg into each . Put the bowls on a baking sheet and bake until the eggs are just set, about 20 minutes or so, depending on how you like your egg done. Turn up the heat to 400 degrees F if your egg is slow to set.Grind some fresh black pepper over each bowl, and scatter the rest of the crumbled bacon around the egg just before serving.

name: Sweet and Sour Chicken with Rice
description:
1 serving of sweet and sour chicken with rice  contains 431 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 62% carbs, 20% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (35% of your Daily Value), potassium (12% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (58% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare rice as per package directions. In a large bowl, mix the cornstarch, water, pepper, and egg whites. Add the chicken and toss until well coated.In a large non-stick skillet, heat oil over medium-high heat. Season chicken strips and add to pan. Brown chicken and remove to plate. Add red and green peppers and onions and cook for 1 minute. Stir in pineapple chunks, juice, sugar, vinegar and chicken stock and bring to a simmer. Simmer until sauce begins to reduce. Stir in cornstarch mixture and bring liquid to a simmer. Stir in chicken strips and cook for 5 minutes. Serve over rice.

name: Easy Sweet Potato Hash
description:
1 servings of easy sweet potato hash  contains 160 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 57% carbs, 38% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (8% of your Daily Value), vitamin a (100% of your Daily Value), and vitamin k (20% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Mince garlic, thinly slice scallions, and dice all other vegetables.Heat oil in large pan over medium-high heat.Add the potatoes, onion and celery to the oil and sprinkle with the salt and pepper. Stir to combine. Cover and cook for 15-20 minutes, stirring occasionally, until the potatoes are almost tender.Turn the heat to high and add the garlic, stirring to combine. Cook on high for 2-5 more minutes until sweet potatoes are nicely browned.Top with green onions and serve.

name: Hummus Quesadilla
description:
1 serving of hummus quesadilla  contains 295 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 32% carbs, 61% fat, and 6% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (16% of your Daily Value), vitamin b6 (28% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (32% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Thinly slice olives and sautee spinach if desired (can also be used raw).Spread hummus across tortilla and cover one half with fillings. Fold in half.Warm a medium skillet over medium heat and warm quesadilla for a minute or two. Flip, brush with olive oil, cook another minute or two. Repeat steps until both sides are gold and crisp.Slice and serve!

name: Keto Kitchen Cauliflower "Mac" & Cheese
description:
1 serving of keto kitchen cauliflower "mac" & cheese  contains 401 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 9% carbs, 78% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and calcium (33% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.  Dizzle melted coconut oil over cauliflower. Season with salt and pepper and toss to combine well. Bake for about 20 minutes. Remove from oven and move to a casserole dish. Reduce oven temperature to 375 degrees F.Heat cream to a simmer.  Add cream cheese (in chunks) and 1.5 cups cheddar cheese (reserve .5 cup for later), add garlic powder mustard seed, and white pepper; whisk/stir well until all melted.  

Pour mix into baking dish with cauliflower, mix well. Cover with remaining .5 cup cheddar.

Bake uncovered for 15-20 minutes. Enjoy!

name: General Tso's Baked Tofu
description:
1 serving of general tso's baked tofu  contains 449 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 44% carbs, 39% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (36% of your Daily Value), fiber (15% of your Daily Value), and potassium (10% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat the oven to 375 degrees F. Line a half sheet pan with parchment.Mix olive oil, 1 minced garlic clove, and bread crumbs.Cut tofu into 1 inch cubes, and fold into breadcrumb mixture.Bake for 20 minutes, flipping halfway through the cooking time, until the breading has started to brown.Make the sauce by combining the honey, salt, pepper, soy sauce, fish sauce, remaining garlic, and Sriracha in a small saucepan and bringing to a boil. Lower the heat and simmer for about 5 minutes, until slightly thickened.Once the tofu is done, coat in the sauce. Sprinkle on the sesame seeds and sliced green onions.

name: Creamy Chicken and Potato Soup
description:
1 serving of creamy chicken and potato soup  contains 261 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 29% carbs, 40% fat, and 31% protein.  This is a good source of protein (36% of your Daily Value), potassium (19% of your Daily Value), and calcium (15% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions In a microwave safe bowl or plate add potatoes, onions, carrots and celery. Cook in microwave for about 6 minutes until soft.In a large nonstick pan or pot, melt butter.  Add garlic and cooked vegetables. Season with thyme and a little salt and pepper, if desired. Mix well. Cook for 3 minutes. Stir in chicken broth and raw chicken. Mix well. Bring up to a boil then down to low heat to simmer, for 20 minutes. Stir often. Mix in milk. Continue to simmer for 10 minutes, or until chicken is cooked. Enjoy!Recipe inspired by: http://www.skinnykitchen.com/recipes/creamy-chicken-and-potato-soup-made-skinny/

name: Browned Butter Flounder with Lemon Snap Peas
description:
1 serving of browned butter flounder with lemon snap peas  contains 252 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 15% carbs, 49% fat, and 36% protein.  This is a good source of protein (40% of your Daily Value), potassium (8% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b12 (77% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Sprinkle fish evenly with pepper and salt. Place flour in a shallow dish; dredge fish in flour. Heat a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat. Add 1 tablespoon oil to pan; swirl to coat. Add fish to pan; cook 3 minutes on each side or until fish flakes easily with a fork. Remove fish from pan; keep warm.Return pan to medium heat. Add butter; cook 45 seconds or until butter begins to brown. Remove pan from heat; stir in parsley and 1 tablespoon lemon juice. Place butter mixture in a small bowl.Return pan to medium-high heat. Add remaining 1 teaspoon oil to pan; swirl to coat. Add snap peas; sauté 3 minutes or just until crisp-tender. Stir in remaining 2 teaspoons lemon juice, mint, and lemon zest. Drizzle browned butter mixture evenly over fish. Serve with snap peas.

name: Sole Fillet with Zucchini
description:
1 serving of sole fillet with zucchini  contains 150 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 15% carbs, 21% fat, and 63% protein.  This is a good source of protein (42% of your Daily Value), potassium (15% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (32% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Place all ingredients in a large skillet. If necessary, add just enough water to completely cover fish.


Bring mixture to a boil, reduce heat, cover, and simmer until fish is no longer opaque and flakes easily, 10-15 minutes.

name: Almond Peanut Butter Chip Muffins
description:
1 serving of almond peanut butter chip muffins  contains 138 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 32% carbs, 56% fat, and 12% protein.  This has a relatively high calorie density, with 377 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F. Lightly grease a mini muffin tin and set aside. Place ingredients, except peanut butter chips, into the bowl of a food processor and blend until well combined.Transfer batter to a mixing bowl, stir in the peanut butter chips and then spoon the batter until nearly full into the muffin tin. Cook for 8-10 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean. Let cool and enjoy!

name: Fuji Apple Chicken Salad
description:
1 serving of fuji apple chicken salad  contains 1589 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 14% carbs, 64% fat, and 22% protein.  This is a good source of protein (158% of your Daily Value), fiber (65% of your Daily Value), and potassium (36% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Season chicken breasts with seasoning salt and cook on both sides for 3-4 minutes each in a greased skillet or pan over medium heat or until cooked through and no longer pink. Cut into pieces and set aside.
In a large bowl toss together mixed greens, sliced onions, and chicken. Sprinkle pecans, cheese crumbles, and apple chips on top. Serve with dressing and enjoy.

name: Jamaican curry chicken
description:
1 serving of jamaican curry chicken (This dish is traditionally served on white rice or in a roti, but feel free to get creative!") contains 256 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 19% carbs, 39% fat, and 41% protein.  This is a good source of protein (47% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (12% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cut up chicken, (not too big).  In a separate bowl, peel and cut up potato, carrots, ginger, and cut up the scallion and scotch bonnet pepper as well. Put asideWhisk 2 tablespoons curry powder, garlic powder, onion powder, salt, thyme leaves, allspice, and pepper together in a bowl. Add chicken and coat with curry mixture until curry mixture is wet and sticks to chicken.Heat oil and 2 tablespoons curry powder in a large cast-iron skillet over high heat until oil is hot and curry powder changes color, 2 to 3 minutes. Add chicken to the hot oil mixture and reduce heat to medium. Add water, potato, carrots, scallions, ginger, and scotch bonnet pepper to skillet.Cover skillet and simmer until chicken is no longer pink in the center and gravy is thickened (30 to 40 Minutes), allowing chicken to cook undisturbed for last 15 minutes of cooking. An instant-read thermometer inserted into the thickest part of the thigh, near the bone, should read 165 degrees F (74 degrees C). Remove chicken to a serving dish; continue simmering gravy, uncovered, to thicken (if needed). Serve chicken with gravy.  Best serve with white rice.

name: Linguine with Tuna, Capers, and Raisins
description:
1 serving of linguine with tuna, capers, and raisins  contains 812 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 53% carbs, 31% fat, and 16% protein.  This is a good source of protein (62% of your Daily Value), potassium (15% of your Daily Value), and iron (86% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Coarsely chop parsley leaves. Drain tuna. Cook pasta in a 6- to 8-quart pot of boiling salted water until al dente. Reserve 1 cup pasta-cooking water, then drain pasta and return to pot.While pasta cooks, heat oil in a 12-inch heavy skillet over high heat until hot but not smoking and cook onions and garlic with salt and pepper, stirring occasionally, until golden, 6 to 8 minutes. Stir in tuna, capers, raisins, parsley, and reserved cooking water. Add tuna mixture to pasta, tossing to combine, and serve immediately.

name: Quinoa Capresi Salad
description:
1 salad of quinoa capresi salad  contains 1290 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 21% carbs, 57% fat, and 21% protein.  This is a good source of protein (123% of your Daily Value), fiber (29% of your Daily Value), and potassium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook quinoa according to package directions, and place cooked quinoa in a large bowl. Add all remaining ingredients and toss well to combine. Taste and see if salad needs more vinegar, salt, etc. and season accordingly.Salad can be served immediately or transfer to an airtight container and refrigerate. Salad will keep airtight in the fridge for up to 3 days, noting that vegetables will release water as time passes.

name: Balsamic-Glazed Steak Rolls
description:
1 serving of balsamic-glazed steak rolls  contains 225 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 24% carbs, 38% fat, and 38% protein.  This is a good source of protein (36% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (60% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Rub each side of the steak slices with a little extra virgin olive oil. Sprinkle with salt, freshly ground black pepper and some chopped fresh rosemary.Heat one tablespoon of extra virgin olive oil in a skillet over medium-high heat and cook the vegetables until crisp-tender, seasoning with salt and pepper.Place a few of the vegetable strips vertically on one end of each steak cutlet so that once rolled up the end of the vegetables are sticking out of each end of the steak roll. Roll it up, and secure it with a toothpick. Repeat for each steak roll.For the rosemary balsamic glaze: Heat the olive oil in a small saucepan over medium-high heat. Add the garlic and cook for one minute, until fragrant. Add the balsamic vinegar, red wine, brown sugar and bring to a rapid boil. Reduce the heat and simmer uncovered for 5 minutes. Add the broth, return to a boil, reduce the heat to low and simmer for another 15 minutes. Prepare the grill and grill on each side for about 2 minutes or according to desired doneness. Do the same if cooking them in a skillet, frying over medium-high heat until done. Serve immediately drizzled with the balsamic glaze. Enjoy!

name: Vegan Beetroot and Tofu Patties
description:
1 serving of vegan beetroot and tofu patties  contains 354 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 50% carbs, 38% fat, and 12% protein.  This is a good source of protein (20% of your Daily Value), fiber (21% of your Daily Value), and potassium (9% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions In a saucepan, place the millet and quinoa. Cover with the cold water, close the lid and bring to boil.When the water is boiling remove the lid and cook on low heat for 10-15 minutes. It is cooked when the grains are sticky and soft and the water has been absorbed. Stir every so often to avoid the grain to stick to the saucepan. Drain into a drainer to evaporate the water until no more steam.Grate beetroot using a box grater or food processor. Chop onion. In a food processor with the S blade attachment, add the grated beetroot (if not already present), basil, soy sauce, crumbled tofu, seeds and red onion.Process until it forms a moist and chunky pinkish mixture - about 1-2 minutes. If needed, stop the food processor scrap down the side and process again until it forms a consistent crumbly and pinkish mixture.Add the cooked and drained quinoa/millet mix. Process again.until it forms a pinkish paste. Add the buckwheat flour, salt and pepper to taste. Blend to combine. Refrigerate in a bowl for 15 minutes to firm up slightly.Prepare a plate covered with plastic wrap. Set aside. Slightly oil your hands with olive oil and forms 8 balls with the patties mixture. Place each ball onto the prepared plate and press them to form patties. Refrigerate for 1 hour to firm up.In a frying pan add olive oil. Warm until hot about 1 minutes on medium high.Place the patties into the warm olive oil gently with your hands to avoid them to break. Let fry for 3-5 minutes on one side before cooking the over side. Use a large spatula to flip over the patties and avoid them to break. Cook on both sides until crispy.Place onto a plate covered with paper towels or clean paper bags when cooked. It will absorbs the extra oil.Serve immediately or set aside at room temperature and rewarm in the oven at 320F/160C for 20 minutes. 

(Note: patties can be frozen before frying.)

name: Tomato Gratin
description:
1 serving of tomato gratin  contains 907 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 42% carbs, 44% fat, and 15% protein.  This is a good source of protein (60% of your Daily Value), fiber (44% of your Daily Value), and potassium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Slice tomatoes approximately 1/2-inch thick.Preheat oven to 500F.Arrange tomato slices, slightly overlapping, in an oiled 9-inch gratin dish or shallow casserole. Season with salt and pepper and sprinkle with basil.Cook garlic in oil in a small skillet over moderate heat, stirring, until fragrant, about 1 minute. Remove from heat and stir in bread crumbs, cheese, and salt and pepper to taste. Sprinkle over tomatoes.Bake in middle of oven until crumbs are golden, about 15 minutes.

name: Keto Spinach and Sausage Breakfast Muffins
description:
1 muffin of keto spinach and sausage breakfast muffins  contains 164 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 7% carbs, 69% fat, and 24% protein.  This is a good source of protein (17% of your Daily Value), vitamin a (12% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b12 (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.

Add 20 ounces of frozen spinach to a microwave safe bowl and microwave on the vegetable setting

Brown 16 oz of pork sausage in a skillet over medium heat until cooked through; add to large bowl.

Chop pepper and onion and add to the cleared pan. Cook over medium heat for about 5-7 minutes, until onions are translucent, add to the bowl with the sausage.

Add cheese to the bowl and mix together.

In a separate bowl whisk 10 eggs, cream, and spices Add eggs to the rest of the ingredients and mix together. Split into muffins (full recipe makes about 20 muffins).
Bake for 30 minutes or until firm when pushed on with a finger. Enjoy!

name: Watermelon Acai Smoothie
description:
1 serving of watermelon acai smoothie  contains 224 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 70% carbs, 22% fat, and 8% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (26% of your Daily Value), potassium (12% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Combine all ingredients in a blender and pulse until smooth. Enjoy!

name: Coconut Ginger Shrimp
description:
1 serving of coconut ginger shrimp  contains 229 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 21% carbs, 57% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value), fiber (15% of your Daily Value), and potassium (7% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat grill to medium.In a sauce pan, heat the coconut oil. Add the garlic, green onion, 1 tbsp of the fresh ginger, and 1 tbsp of the shredded coconut. Sauté briefly.

Add the coconut milk, lime juice, and black pepper to the sauce pot. Cook over medium heat for a minute or two, stirring frequently.

Remove the sauce pot from the heat and allow mixture to cool a bit. Pour mixture in a small bowl or dish. In a separate bowl or dish place the remaining 3 tbsp of ginger and 3 tbsp of shredded coconut.

Coat each shrimp with the coconut oil mixture and then coat with the dry ginger and coconut. Lace the shrimp on skewers.
Cook the skewered shrimp on a grill until done, about 2 minutes per side.

name: Spring Salad with Buttermilk Herb Dressing
description:
1 serving of spring salad with buttermilk herb dressing  contains 68 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 46% carbs, 35% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (9% of your Daily Value), vitamin a (19% of your Daily Value), and vitamin k (100% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Bring a pot of water to boil with a steam tray over top. Add asparagus to tray, cover, and steam until crisp/ tender (about 4-8 minutes depending on thickness of asparagus).  Shock in cold water.Combine Dill and next seven ingredients (through garlic) in small bowl, stirring with wisk.  Divide lettuce, asparagus and radish evenly between 4 plates.  Drizzle each with 1 1/2 tablespoons dressing. Enjoy!

name: Steak and Potatoes
description:
1 serving of steak and potatoes  contains 1038 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 31% carbs, 47% fat, and 21% protein.  This is a good source of protein (100% of your Daily Value), fiber (44% of your Daily Value), and potassium (60% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Chop potatoes into bite-sized pieces.  Mince garlic.  Place potatoes in an 8x8 inch baking dish.In a small bowl combine melted butter, garlic, salt and lemon juice; pour over potatoes and stir to coat. Sprinkle Parmesan cheese over potatoes.Bake, covered, in preheated oven for 30 minutes. Uncover and bake an additional 10 minutes, or until golden brown.Cook and stir meat in oil in skillet on high heat, about 2 minutes. or until browned. Remove from skillet; set aside.Add potatoes and carrots, and water to skillet. Bring to boil; cover. Reduce heat to low; simmer 20 minutes. or until vegetables are tender.Stir in onions, any juices left from potatoes, and meat; cook and stir on high heat 5 minutes or until heated through.

name: Easy Cashew Chicken
description:
1 serving of easy cashew chicken  contains 437 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 9% carbs, 74% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (35% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and total omega 3 (1 g).
instructions: Directions Heat a pan over low heat and toast the cashews for 8 minutes. Toast them until you start to see some browning. Remove and set aside.Dice chicken thighs into 1 inch chunks. Cut onion and pepper into equally large chunks.Increase heat to high and add canola oil to pan.Once oil is up to temperature, add in the chicken thighs and allow them to cook through.Once the chicken is nearly fully cooked. Add in the pepper, onions, garlic, chili sauce, and seasonings (ginger, salt, pepper). Allow to cook on high for 2-3 minutes.Add soy sauce, rice wine vinegar, and cashews. Cook on high and allow the liquid to reduce down until it is a sticky consistency, There should not be a lot of liquid in the pan upon completing cooking.Serve in a bowl, top with scallions, sesame seeds and drizzle with sesame oil. Enjoy!

name: Bison Beer Burgers with Beer-Caramelized Onions
description:
1 serving of bison beer burgers with beer-caramelized onions  contains 351 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 43% carbs, 21% fat, and 36% protein.  This is a good source of protein (54% of your Daily Value), potassium (16% of your Daily Value), and iron (73% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions  Melt butter in a skillet over medium heat. Add onion and cook for 5 minutes. Stir in brown sugar and a couple of pinches each of salt and pepper. Reduce heat to medium low, cover, and heat for 15 minutes, stirring occasionally. Add 1/2 cup beer, raise heat to medium, and cook until little beer remains. Stir in mustard.
 Preheat grill to medium high. In a large bowl, gently mix together bison, 1/3 cup beer, garlic, tomato paste, Worcestershire, paprika, and salt and pepper to taste. Form into 4 patties. Grill for 5 minutes on each side, or until cooked through.
Serve burgers on toasted buns and topped with barbecue sauce, onions, roasted red pepper, and spinach.

name: Pasta Puttanesca
description:
1 serving of pasta puttanesca  contains 2701 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 62% carbs, 23% fat, and 15% protein.  This is a good source of protein (184% of your Daily Value), fiber (140% of your Daily Value), and potassium (98% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Mince onion. Chop garlic, olives , fresh parsley and anchovies coarsely.
Heat the olive oil over medium-high heat in a large, deep saute pan. When the oil is hot, saut the onions until they're soft and translucent, about 4-5 minutes. While the onions are cooking, stir in the chopped anchovies along with some of the oil from the can. Add the garlic and cook another minute.Mix in the tomato paste and cook it for 2 minutes, stirring occasionally. Add the crushed tomatoes, oregano, chili pepper flakes, and olives. Turn the heat down to a gentle simmer.Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. When you add the spaghetti to the boiling water to cook, add the capers to the sauce and continue to simmer it gently. Cook the pasta according to the package instructions, to al dente, cooked but still slightly firm.Drain the pasta and put in a large bowl. Drizzle a little olive oil over the pasta and mix to combine. Stir the parsley into the pasta sauce. Add a ladle's worth of sauce to the pasta and mix to combine. Serve in shallow bowls with more sauce on top.

name: Cider-Braised Chicken
description:
1 serving of cider-braised chicken  contains 732 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 4% carbs, 71% fat, and 25% protein.  This is a good source of protein (78% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Rinse chicken, pat dry and cut into quarters.Sprinkle chicken with 2 teaspoons coarsely ground pepper and 1 teaspoon salt.Heat oil in a 12-inch heavy skillet over medium-high heat until it shimmers, then brown chicken, skin side down first, turning once, 8 to 10 minutes total. Transfer to a plate, discarding oil.Wipe out skillet, then boil remaining ingredients until reduced by half, 3 to 5 minutes. Return chicken to skillet and braise, covered, turning once, until chicken is just cooked through, 25 to 30 minutes. Transfer chicken to a platter. Boil sauce to thicken if necessary. Whisk sauce if separated and season with salt, then pour over chicken.

name: Cafe Au Lait Puddings
description:
1 serving of cafe au lait puddings  contains 236 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 49% carbs, 46% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of vitamin a (17% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Whisk together milk, coffee granules, cornstarch, 1/4 cup sugar, and a small pinch of salt in a heavy medium saucepan. Bring to a boil over medium heat, stirring occasionally, then boil 1 minute, stirring constantly. Transfer to a metal bowl set in an ice bath and cool, stirring often, about 10 minutes. Pour into cups or ramekins and chill, uncovered, 20 minutes.Beat cream with vanilla and remaining 
2 tablespoon sugar using an electric mixer just until soft peaks form. Spoon whipped cream onto puddings and dust cream lightly with cinnamon.

name: Pappardelle with Squash, Mushrooms, and Spinach
description:
1 serving of pappardelle with squash, mushrooms, and spinach  contains 709 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 49% carbs, 37% fat, and 14% protein.  This is a good source of protein (48% of your Daily Value), fiber (29% of your Daily Value), and potassium (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Remove stems from mushrooms and thinly slice caps. Cook pasta in large pot of boiling salted water until tender but still firm to bite, stirring occasionally. Drain, reserving 1 cup pasta cooking liquid.Meanwhile, melt 1/4 cup butter in large skillet over medium-high heat. Add squash and cook until almost tender, stirring often, about 6 minutes. Add mushrooms, sage, and remaining 1/4 cup butter; saute until mushrooms are soft and squash is tender, about 8 minutes. Add spinach; stir until wilted, about 2 minutes. Stir in 1/2 cup cheese. Season with salt and pepper. Add pasta to sauce in skillet. Toss to coat, adding pasta cooking liquid by 1/4 cupfuls if dry. Sprinkle with 1/4 cup cheese.

name: Chocolate, Almond, and Banana Parfaits
description:
1 serving of chocolate, almond, and banana parfaits  contains 543 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 54% carbs, 37% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of protein (23% of your Daily Value), fiber (19% of your Daily Value), and potassium (12% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 325°F.Slice almonds and toast on a sheet pan in the preheated oven for approximately 10 minutes. Let cool slightly.Peel bananas and cut diagonally into about 24 slices total.In a 1-cup glass measuring cup, combine chocolate chips and 4 tablespoons of heavy whipping cream.Microwave on 50% power for 30 to 35 seconds, or until the chocolate is melted. Stir until smooth and cool to lukewarm.In a medium bowl, whisk together ricotta cheese, sugar, and the remaining 2 tablespoons of heavy whipping cream until blended and the mixture just starts to thicken.If necessary, cut the angel food cake slices into rounds using a 2 1/2-inch cookie cutter.Place 1 cake round in the bottom of each of 4 wine goblets or old-fashioned glasses.Top each cake round with 3 banana slices, 1 heaping spoonful of the cheese mixture, a drizzle of the chocolate sauce, and a sprinkling of toasted almonds.Repeat the layering process one more time.Serve immediately.

name: Provolone and Broccoli Rabe Panini
description:
1 serving of provolone and broccoli rabe panini  contains 794 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 25% carbs, 55% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (72% of your Daily Value), fiber (18% of your Daily Value), and potassium (15% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions PREPARATION:  Discard tough broccoli ends.  Rinse, pat dry, and chop anchovies.  Mince garlic.  Slice Italian bread 1/4 inch thick.  Slice provolone.Cook broccoli rabe in a 4-quart pot of boiling salted water , uncovered, until tender, about 3 minutes. Drain well in a colander, then chop.Cook anchovies and garlic in 1 1/2 tablespoons oil in a 10-inch heavy skillet over moderate heat, stirring, until garlic just begins to turn golden, about 1 minute. Add broccoli rabe and cook, stirring, 1 minute.Heat a panini or sandwich press according to manufacturer's instructions until hot. (Alternatively, heat a well-seasoned ridged grill pan over moderate heat.)Brush 4 center slices of bread on 1 side with remaining 1 1/2 tablespoons oil. (Reserve remainder of loaf for another use.) Put slices, oiled sides down, on a work surface, then divide half of cheese between 2 slices. Top with all of broccoli rabe mixture, remaining cheese, and remaining 2 bread slices, oiled sides up.Put sandwiches on press, then pull down top onto sandwiches and cook until sandwiches are browned and crisp, 4 to 8 minutes. (If using grill pan, put a heavy pan on top of sandwiches and cook, turning sandwiches over once.)

name: Pumpkin Breakfast Cookie
description:
1 serving of pumpkin breakfast cookie  contains 200 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 44% carbs, 46% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of vitamin a (25% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 325°F. Line a baking sheet.In a small bowl, warm coconut oil and agave nectar (either microwave, inside preheating oven, or on the stove top).In a large bowl, combine oats, cranberries, pumpkin seeds, ground flax, pumpkin pie spice, and salt. Add pumpkin puree, eggs, and warmed coconut oil and agave nectar. Stir until fully combined.Drop about ¼ cup sized scoops of the mixture onto a cookie sheet and flatten (cookies won't spread while baking). Bake for about 15-20 minutes until edges are lightly browned.Let cookies cool on baking sheet before moving to an airtight storage container.

name: Paleo Pineapple Fried "Rice"
description:
1 serving of paleo pineapple fried "rice"  contains 225 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 31% carbs, 58% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (16% of your Daily Value), potassium (13% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (65% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Remove the core and seeds from the bell pepper and cut it lengthwise into ½ inch thick strips. Then cut the pepper strips crosswise into ½ inch pieces.Peel the carrots and cut off both ends before thinly slicing them.Grate the cauliflower using a box grater and set it aside.Crack the egg into a bowl and lightly whisk them together with a fork.Mix the liquid aminos and sriracha together in a small bowl and set it aside.Once the prep work is done, preheat a very large skillet over medium-high heat for a few minutes until it's hot but not smoking.Add a quarter of the oil to the pan and sear the pineapple chunks to create caramelized edges, 2-3 minutes. Remove the pineapple from the pan and set it aside while you finish the fried riceAdd the remaining oil to the pan and sauté the bell pepper, carrots, and garlic until the veggies are crisp tender. Then add the green onions, and cauliflower to the pan, cook 1-2 minutes to just soften the cauliflower. Add the eggs and cook stirring until the egg scrambles around the stir-fry - 1-2 minutesAdd the sauce to the pan and cook for another 1-2 minutes until the sauce is absorbed and thoroughly mixed inRemove the fried rice from the heat and stir in the caramelized pineapple. Taste test to see if you'd like to add some sea salt. Serve immediately and enjoy!

name: Black Beans, Carrots, and Rice
description:
1 serving of black beans, carrots, and rice  contains 218 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 79% carbs, 9% fat, and 12% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (21% of your Daily Value), potassium (8% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Bring water to boil, then add rice.  When water begins to boil again, reduce heat to a simmer and cover.

Cook covered for 40-45 minutes until rice is tender; stir once after about 20 mins.

While rice is cooking, heat oil in large skillet on medium heat; sauté carrots for about 5 minutes until soft.

Add onions and garlic to carrots in skillet and cook for 5 minutes until onions are translucent.

Stir in drained black beans, thyme, cumin, cinnamon, red pepper flakes, and honey; cook for about 2 minutes.

Add cooked rice to vegetables and mix well.

Add salt and black pepper to taste. Enjoy!

name: Spanish Green Beans with Bacon
description:
1 serving of spanish green beans with bacon  contains 232 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 21% carbs, 71% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (7% of your Daily Value) and vitamin k (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Cook bacon in a skillet over medium heat to desired crispiness. Drain and chop.In a large pot of salted water cook the green beans about 5-6 minutes, only until just tender but still with some "bite".
In a saucepan, heat the olive oil on medium heat and fry the onion for 5 minutes, until softened. Add the garlic and cook another minute, being careful not burn.
Drain the green beans well and add to the saucepan with the garlic. Cook, stirring constantly for 2-3 minutes. Stir in the crumbled bacon. Season with salt and pepper.Serve warm and enjoy!

name: Asian Quinoa BBQ
description:
1 serving of asian quinoa bbq  contains 492 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 56% carbs, 25% fat, and 19% protein.  This is a good source of protein (41% of your Daily Value), fiber (28% of your Daily Value), and potassium (18% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat to 325 degrees F and grease a baking sheet.Cut tofu into 1 cm/1/2 inch chunks, drain, roll in flour, and coat in sauce.Bake for 30 minutes; cover tofu with aluminum, and set aside.Meanwhile, Prepare quinoa as per package directions. Warm chickpeas in a pan over medium heat.While the quinoa and beans cook, heat a medium sauté pan to medium-high. Add 1 tablespoon olive oil and let sit until the oil glistens. Add chopped onion to the pan and sauté for 4-5 minutes until onion turns translucent. Add garlic and continue to cook for 1 minute and then add spinach. Add another tablespoon of olive oil if needed and let spinach cook down, 3-5 minutes. Once cooked, remove from heat and cover.Add cooked spinach mixture and chickpeas to the quinoa. Add salt and pepper, stir and cover. Let sit for 3-5 minutes.Serve the quinoa mixture with the tofu and enjoy!

name: Overnight Banana Nut Porridge
description:
1 bowl of overnight banana nut porridge  contains 599 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 14% carbs, 78% fat, and 8% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value), fiber (25% of your Daily Value), and potassium (14% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Place the nuts in a large bowl and sprinkle the sea salt over them. Fill the bowl with filtered water so the nuts are covered by at least 1 inch of water. Cover and soak overnight.Drain the nuts and rinse 2 or 3 times, until the water runs clear.Add the drained nuts to a food processor or high-speed blender. Blend the nuts with the banana, coconut milk, and cinnamon until smooth.Divide it into bowls and microwave for 40 seconds or put all of the porridge in a pot on the stove and heat over medium-high heat for 5 minutes.Serve and enjoy!

name: Ham and Cheese Chicken Roll-ups
description:
1 breast of ham and cheese chicken roll-ups  contains 1633 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 25% carbs, 47% fat, and 28% protein.  This is a good source of protein (201% of your Daily Value), fiber (32% of your Daily Value), and potassium (35% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.Cut about ¾ of the way through the chicken horizontally, making sure not to cut through the other side. Flip the chicken open and flat. Lay a sheet of plastic wrap on top of the chicken and pound it to even thickness. Remove the plastic wrap. Season with the salt, pepper, and garlic powder, rubbing the seasoning in evenly. Lay 2-3 slices of ham over the chicken, followed by 2 slices of provolone cheese. Carefully roll the chicken up.Transfer the flour, eggs, and breadcrumbs into 3 separate bowls. Dip the chicken roll into the flour, tapping off any excess, and then into the egg, followed by the breadcrumbs. Place on a baking sheet.Add the broccoli to the baking sheet, mixing it with the olive oil, salt, and pepper to taste. Make sure to save a little oil to drizzle on top of the chicken.Bake for 20 minutes, slice, then serve. Enjoy!

name: Quinoa and Berries
description:
1 serving of quinoa and berries  contains 490 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 60% carbs, 29% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of protein (25% of your Daily Value), fiber (31% of your Daily Value), and potassium (14% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions In medium saucepan, combine the quinoa, water, milk, and salt and bring to gentle boil, watching to prevent the milk from boiling over. Turn the heat down and let simmer until most of the moisture has evaporated.Add honey, stir. Cover and let sit for a few minutes. Top with berries and pecans.

name: Lentil Pear Salad
description:
1 serving of lentil pear salad  contains 769 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 35% carbs, 49% fat, and 16% protein.  This is a good source of protein (59% of your Daily Value), fiber (90% of your Daily Value), and potassium (30% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare lentils as per package directions. Slice pears.Combine all ingredients together in a bowl and toss together well.Top with the dressing and serve.Inspired by: http://www.thekitchn.com/salad-swag-the-cure-for-the-common-salad-201121

name: Zucchini and Ham Pinwheels
description:
1 serving of zucchini and ham pinwheels  contains 87 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 20% carbs, 50% fat, and 30% protein.  This has a relatively low calorie density, with 80 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Preheat grill to medium.Cut zucchinni into thin slices.Grill zuchinni slices until soft, just a few minutes.Spread cream cheese onto the slices of ham. Roll up and cut into rounds.Place one round on each slice of zucchini. Enjoy!

name: Balsamic Potatoes
description:
1 serving of balsamic potatoes  contains 307 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 79% carbs, 12% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (28% of your Daily Value), potassium (31% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (20% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Wash the potatoes thoroughly and cut into small cubes. Place in saucepan, cover with water, and bring to a boil. Cook until just tender, 10-15 min. (Do not overcook; keep firm.) Drain, rinse, drain again, and let cool.Mix the mustard, vinegar, oil, pepper, and onion in a large bowl. Add the potatoes and toss gently to coat. Cover and refridgerate. Serve cold.

name: Quick "Lasagna"
description:
1 serving of quick "lasagna"  contains 871 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 40% carbs, 42% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (72% of your Daily Value), potassium (12% of your Daily Value), and calcium (15% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Bring a large pot of water to boil. Add the pasta and cook according to the package directions. When done, drain well.Meanwhile, heat the oil in a large skillet. Add the onion and garlic and sauté until the onion is soft, about 5 minutes.Add the beef and cook, stirring to break up clumps, until the meat is cooked through, about 10 minutes. (There should be no grease to drain) Add salt and pepper to taste.Add the cottage cheese and mix well. It will start getting gooey.Divide the pasta into bowls. Spoon the meat mixture on top, and sprinkle with the parmesan cheese.

name: Corn, Scallion, and Potato Frittata
description:
1 serving of corn, scallion, and potato frittata  contains 403 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 37% carbs, 45% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (34% of your Daily Value), fiber (18% of your Daily Value), and potassium (17% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions PREPARATION:  Slice white and green parts of scallion separately, mince garlic, peel and cut potatoes into 1/4-inch dice, thaw corn kernels, grate mozzarella.
Cook white part of scallions and garlic in 2 tablespoons oil in a 10-inch nonstick skillet over moderate heat, stirring, until softened, about 2 minutes. Add potato and cook over moderately low heat, stirring, until tender, about 10 minutes. Add corn and salt and pepper to taste, then cook, stirring, about 1 minute for thawed corn or 3 minutes for fresh corn.Preheat broiler.Whisk together eggs, mozzarella, and salt and pepper to taste. Stir in potato mixture and scallion greens.Heat remaining tablespoon oil in cleaned skillet over moderate heatuntil hot but not smoking. Then cook frittata without stirring, shaking skillet once or twice to loosen frittata, until underside is golden but top is still wet, about 6 minutes. Remove from heat.If skillet handle is not ovenproof, wrap handle in a double layer of foil. Broil frittata about 3 inches from heat until top is just set and golden, about 2 minutes. Slide onto a plate and cool to warm or room temperature

name: Quinoa and Egg Enchilada Skillet
description:
1 serving of quinoa and egg enchilada skillet  contains 388 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 42% carbs, 39% fat, and 19% protein.  This is a good source of protein (34% of your Daily Value), fiber (36% of your Daily Value), and potassium (13% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375°F.Prepare quinoa as per package directions.In a mixing bowl, combine the cooked quinoa, black beans, and corn.Mix cumin, garlic powder, oil, and lime juice in a smaller bowl. Pour over the quinoa mixture and toss to combine. Season with salt and pepper to taste.Spread the mixture into a 12 inch cast-iron skillet. Top with enchilada sauce and cheese. Make six indentations for the eggs and crack them over the cheese, evenly spaced. Season the eggs with salt and pepper.Bake for 20-30 minutes, until egg whites are set but yolks are still runny, and edges are bubbly.Serve with fresh cilantro, green onions, avocado slices, and hot sauce on the side.

name: Turkey Jalepeno Poppers
description:
2 poppers of turkey jalepeno poppers  contains 135 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 9% carbs, 56% fat, and 35% protein.  This is a good source of protein (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat grill to 350°F.Set a nonstick skillet on medium-high heat and spray lightly with olive oil. Cook red onions and garlic until onions are brown and translucent. Add ground turkey and cook, breaking up clumps with a wooden spatula.Slice turkey bacon vertically in half to create two strips from one slice. Repeat for all strips.Slice jalapeños down the middle and remove seeds with a small spoon.Mix cooked ground turkey, Greek yogurt, goat cheese, and seasonings in a bowl.Fill each jalapeño half with the mixture, wrap with a turkey bacon strip, and grill with the mixture facing up for 23-25 minutes until jalapeño edges brown and bacon crisps.Remove from heat and serve immediately.

name: Baked Sweet Potato with West African-Style Peanut Sauce
description:
1 potato of baked sweet potato with west african-style peanut sauce  contains 217 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 59% carbs, 32% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (21% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (107% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375°F (190°C). Pierce potatoes several times with a fork and bake for 1 hour or until tender.Allow potatoes to cool slightly as you prepare the sauce.Heat butter in a medium pan over medium-low heat. Cook onion, ginger, and garlic for 3 minutes.Add cumin, coriander, and cayenne pepper and cook for 1 minute.Add tomato sauce, water, salt, sugar, and peanut butter. Bring to a boil, then simmer 3 minutes or until desired thickness is achieved.Cut potatoes lengthwise, but do not cut all the way through the other side.Spoon about 1/4 cup sauce into each potato. Top with cilantro.

name: Cilantro Lime Chicken Breast
description:
1 serving of cilantro lime chicken breast  contains 485 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 19% carbs, 42% fat, and 39% protein.  This is a good source of protein (88% of your Daily Value), fiber (24% of your Daily Value), and potassium (26% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Mince the garlic and rub the garlic, salt, olive oil, cilantro, and juice of 1 lime into the chicken.Let it rest for 15 minutes.Meanwhile, bring a pot of water to boil with a steam tray over top. Add broccoli, cover, and steam for 4-5 minutes, until tender. Set aside.Pan-fry the chicken in 1 tbsp olive oil over medium-high heat for 7-10 minutes per side, or until cooked through and no longer pink. Serve with the broccoli and enjoy.

name: Paleo Pad Thai
description:
1 serving of paleo pad thai  contains 520 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 39% carbs, 52% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value), fiber (41% of your Daily Value), and potassium (25% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Place a metal steamer basket in a large pot and add three inches of water. Steam the spaghetti squash in the basket for 20 minutes, or until tender when pierced with a fork. Remove the spaghetti squash from the basket and allow to slightly cool so you can handle it.

While the squash is cooking and cooling, create the tangy peanut sauce. Purée the lime juice, ginger, garlic, and vinegar until very smooth. Blend in the almond butter and coconut milk until thoroughly combined. Divide 1/4 cup for your pad thai and store the rest in a glass jar for up to three days.

Once the squash is cool enough to handle, scoop  the spaghetti squash out of the skin using a fork to create the "spaghetti" and set aside.

Heat the coconut oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Sauté the onion for 8-10 minutes, until soft and translucent. Add the broccoli and sauté for about 10 minutes, until tender. Stir in the bok choy and sauté for 3-4 minutes, until wilted. Add the squash to the skillet, stir briefly to incorporate, then add the scallions. 

Top with toasted cashews and tangy peanut sauce. Garnish with a little crushed red pepper if desired. Serve hot!

name: Cheesy Tuna Casserole
description:
1 serving of cheesy tuna casserole  contains 484 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 4% carbs, 72% fat, and 24% protein.  This is a good source of protein (52% of your Daily Value), potassium (7% of your Daily Value), and calcium (52% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.In a medium pot, cook the green beans as directed on the package; drain well (or steam for about 4-6 minutes). Meanwhile, sauté the mushrooms, celery, and onion in the butter over medium heat until very soft and starting to brown a bit. Add the broth; bring to a boil.
