Let the liquid reduce by half, then stir in the cream. Bring back to a boil. Turn down the heat a bit and cook until reduced and thickened, stirring frequently and watching closely so it doesn't boil over. Season to taste. Stir the tuna and mushroom soup mixture into the green beans. Add salt and pepper, if needed. Mix in the cheese; put into a 1 1/2-2 quart casserole dish. Bake until hot and bubbly.

name: Sweet Potato Cauliflower Soup
description:
1 serving of sweet potato cauliflower soup  contains 137 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 72% carbs, 16% fat, and 12% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (16% of your Daily Value), potassium (13% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (40% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat your oven to 400 degrees F and cut up your cauliflower into bite sized pieces.  Place cauliflower onto ungreased cookie sheet and lightly drizzle with olive oil. Place in oven and let roast until golden brown on the tops and tender, but not mushy, about 20-30 minutes. Remove from oven and let cool while you cook the rest of the soup.In large stockpot, bring sweet potato, onion, corn, garlic, and water to a boil. Salt and stir. Reduce heat and allow to remain at a constant simmer until sweet potatoes are tender. Add in cooked cauliflower and divide soup into 2 parts.Let soup cool and then blend one part soup in blender until very smooth. Combine with second part soup and stir. Salt to taste and warm up over stovetop if needed. Enjoy!

name: Italian Breaded Pork Chops
description:
1 serving of italian breaded pork chops  contains 450 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 31% carbs, 41% fat, and 28% protein.  This is a good source of protein (56% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and calcium (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 325 degrees F.In a small bowl, beat together the eggs and milk. In a separate small bowl, mix the bread crumbs, Parmesan cheese, and parsley.Heat the olive oil in a large, oven-proof skillet over medium heat. Stir in the garlic, and cook until lightly browned. Remove garlic, reserving for other uses.Dip each pork chop into the egg mixture, then into the bread crumb mixture, coating evenly. Place coated pork chops in the skillet, and brown abut 5 minutes on each side.Place the skillet and pork chops in the preheated oven, and cook 25 minutes, or to an internal temperature of 145 degrees F.

name: Skinny Chicken Mexican Stew
description:
1 serving of skinny chicken mexican stew  contains 294 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 50% carbs, 19% fat, and 31% protein.  This is a good source of protein (43% of your Daily Value), fiber (37% of your Daily Value), and potassium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Spray a pan with non-stick spray. Add chopped chicken and cooked for 8-12 minutes, or until cooked through and no longer pink. Set aside.Add the onions to a microwave safe bowl and cook for 3-4 minutes to soften. In a large nonstick soup pot or pan, heat 1 tablespoon oil. Add tomatoes, ½ of the cooked onions, chilies, garlic, and ½ teaspoon cumin. Sauté over medium heat for 10 minutes. Stir often.Add 2 cups broth and tortillas; simmer 20 minutes. Stir often. Transfer mixture to a blender and purée. Set aside.In the same large, nonstick pot, or pan, heat 1 teaspoon oil. Add the remaining cooked onions, paprika, chili powder, 1½ teaspoon cumin, red pepper flakes, ¼ teaspoon salt and black pepper. Cook for 2 minutes. Stir often.Mix in 3 cups broth, cooked chicken, black beans, corn, and puréed mixture from the blender; simmer 10 minutes.To serve. Ladle 1¾ cups into each bowl. Enjoy!Recipe inspired by: http://www.skinnykitchen.com/recipes/skinny-chicken-mexican-stew-pozole/

name: One Pot Pasta Bolognese
description:
1 serving of one pot pasta bolognese  contains 745 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 40% carbs, 37% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (78% of your Daily Value), fiber (18% of your Daily Value), and potassium (29% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions In a dutch oven or large skillet over medium heat, cook the bacon until lightly crisped. Mix in the onion, celery, and garlic, and season liberally with salt and pepper. Mix in ¼ teaspoon red chili flakes (or powder), adding slightly more if you prefer more heat in your sauce. Cook together until the onion has softened, about 5 minutes.

Add in the ground chuck. Cook, breaking up the meat with a wooden spoon, for 5-10 minutes or until browned all over. Once browned, stir in the tomato paste, crushed tomatoes, chicken stock, and thyme.

Bring the mixture to a boil, then reduce to a simmer, cover, and cook for 5 minutes. Then, uncover, remove the thyme sprigs, stir the pasta in, and continue to simmer for 15 minutes or until the pasta is cooked through and the sauce has thickened, stirring occasionally.

Stir in the milk, parmesan cheese, and shredded basil, and adjust the seasonings to taste. Serve with additional basil, to garnish.

name: Roasted Red Bell Pepper and Cauliflower Soup
description:
1 serving of roasted red bell pepper and cauliflower soup  contains 305 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 10% carbs, 81% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (7% of your Daily Value), vitamin a (42% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (86% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 450 degrees F.
Slice peppers in half and de-seed them. Broil for 10-15 minutes or until skin is charred and blackened. Once done, place in container with lid to steam while cauliflower cooks.
Cut cauliflower into florets and season with 2 tbsp melted butter, salt, and pepper. Roast cauliflower in oven for 30-35 minutes.
Remove the skins from the peppers by peeling it off carefully.
In a pot, bring 4 tbsp butter to heat and add diced green onion. Add seasonings into the pan to toast, then add chicken broth, red pepper, and cauliflower to the pan. Let this simmer for 10-20 minutes.
Take an immersion blender to the mixture. Make sure that all fats are emulsified. Then add cream and mix.
Serve with some goat cheese. Garnish with extra thyme and green onion. Enjoy!

name: Pappardelle with Vegetable "Bolognese"
description:
1 serving of pappardelle with vegetable "bolognese"  contains 499 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 63% carbs, 24% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of protein (29% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and iron (51% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Boil the water in a saucepan.Soak mushrooms in boiling-hot water 15 minutes.Meanwhile, quarter the carrots  and cut them into 1 inch pieces.Cut the celery and bell pepper into 1 inch pieces and quarter the shallots.Pulse carrots, celery, shallots, and bell pepper together in a food processor until chopped.Heat oil in a 12-inch heavy skillet over moderately high heat until hot but not smoking. Add chopped vegetables, rosemary, salt, and pepper and saut, stirring occasionally, until vegetables  are golden brown and tender, about  12 minutes.Lift mushrooms out of soaking liquid, squeeze excess liquid back into bowl (reserve liquid), and rinse mushrooms well to remove any grit. Finely chop mushrooms, then add to vegetables in skillet along with tomato paste. Cook over moderate heat, stirring, 1 minute. Add wine and boil until wine is reduced by about half, about 2 minutes.While sauce is cooking, cook pasta in a 6- to 8-quart pot of boiling salted water until al dente. Reserve 1 cup pasta-cooking water in a heatproof measuring cup, then drain pasta in a colander.Add reserved mushroom-soaking liquid to sauce and bring to a simmer. Add pasta and 1/2 cup reserved cooking water to sauce, tossing to coat (thin sauce with additional cooking water if necessary). Stir in cheese and serve immediately.

name: Mexican Cauliflower "Rice"
description:
1 serving of mexican cauliflower "rice"  contains 122 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 61% carbs, 22% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (25% of your Daily Value), potassium (23% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (44% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Finely chop the cauliflower using a grater or food processor until it resembles rice; set aside.Heat the oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. When hot, add the diced onions, tomatoes, and jalapeno, and sauté until just tender, about 3-5 minutes. Add the garlic and cauliflower, sauté until the cauliflower is just tender, about 2 minutes.Add the tomato paste, cumin, paprika, cayenne, salt, and pepper. Stir to evenly coat the vegetables and cook for 1 minute or until heated through. Add chopped cilantro and serve.

name: Sweet Potato and Beef Chili
description:
1 serving of sweet potato and beef chili  contains 422 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 16% carbs, 61% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (44% of your Daily Value), potassium (15% of your Daily Value), and iron (57% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Season the ground turkey with salt and pepper. Create a spice mixture by tossing coriander, cumin, paprika, and chili powder together. Set these aside.Prep remaining items.  Peel potatoes, measure out stock, open can of tomatoes, chop onions, and mince garlic.Heat a Dutch oven (bigger than 5 quarts) over medium-high heat. Add oil and then garlic to heated oil. Once you can smell the garlic, add onions with a generous dash of salt. Sauté until softened, about 3 minutes.Next add in ground beef with half the spice mixture and diced tomatoes. Brown and break up with a wooden spoon, 3 to 5 minutes. If there is a lot of grease, drain from the pot.Add in sweet potatoes, chicken stock, and remainder of spices. Cover and bring to a boil. Lower heat to a simmer and cook covered for another 15 minutes or until the sweet potatoes are softened.While soup is cooking, cube avocados and chop cilantro. Turn off heat and add in a squeeze of lime juice.Season to taste with salt and pepper. Top with avocado and cilantro when serving.

name: Cold Mediterranean Quinoa Salad
description:
1 serving of cold mediterranean quinoa salad  contains 488 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 51% carbs, 38% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of protein (25% of your Daily Value), fiber (32% of your Daily Value), and potassium (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare quinoa as per package directions; let cool completely.Dice all the vegetables. Drizzle the olive oil over the quinoa, then add olives, cucumber, tomatoes, parsley, and mint. Squeeze 1/2 lemon over it and toss well. Taste for salt and adjust as needed, add more lemon juice if needed.

name: Black Olive Spread with Crostini
description:
1 serving of black olive spread with crostini  contains 237 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 26% carbs, 70% fat, and 4% protein.  This is a good source of iron (46% of your Daily Value) and vitamin e (23% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 425 degrees F.Combine capers, olives, and garlic in a food processor. Pulse until evenly chopped. Slowly stream in 1/4 cup oil until mixture is evenly combined but not a paste.Slice baguette on a bias into thin slices. Pace on a baking sheet and brush slices with oil.Bake in the preheated oven for 3-4 minutes until lightly toasted. Top with olive spread and enjoy!

name: Make Ahead Bacon Cheeseburger Burrito
description:
1 serving of make ahead bacon cheeseburger burrito  contains 733 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 17% carbs, 63% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (65% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and calcium (66% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 375 degrees F. Lay out bacon on a foil lined baking sheet. Bake for 15-20 minutes, to desired crispiness.Cook beef in a skillet over medium heat. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Add in flour after browning for structure, mix well..

Drain bacon on paper towels. Cut into 1 inch pieces or leave whole.

Fill burritos with meats, lettuce, cheese, and salsa. Roll up.

Freeze until ready to eat. Microwave wrapped in a paper towel for 2 minutes. Enjoy!

name: Chocolate Chip Zucchini Bread
description:
1 serving of chocolate chip zucchini bread  contains 269 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 66% carbs, 27% fat, and 8% protein.  This has a moderate calorie density, with 248 Calories per 100g.
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 325 degrees F. Prepare a bread tin with non-stick spray.

Combine flour, sugar, baking soda, and salt in a large bowl. Mix well.

Add chocolate chips and gently mix to combine.

In a medium bowl, mix egg, vanilla, melted butter, apple sauce, and grated zucchini. Add to the flour mixture and stir until just blended.  Pour into prepared bread tin.

Bake for 45-55 minutes, or until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out clean. Cool for about 10 minutes. Remove loaf from pan and let it cool before slicing.

name: Linguine with Garlicky Clams and Peas
description:
1 serving of linguine with garlicky clams and peas  contains 379 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 53% carbs, 26% fat, and 22% protein.  This is a good source of protein (37% of your Daily Value), calcium (18% of your Daily Value), and iron (44% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook pasta according to package directions. Drain; keep warm.Heat oil in a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat. Add garlic to pan; sauté 1 minute. Drain clams, reserving clams and 1/2 cup juice. Add reserved clam juice, broth, wine, and red pepper to pan; bring to a boil. Reduce heat, and simmer 5 minutes, stirring occasionally. Add clams and peas to pan; cook 2 minutes or until thoroughly heated. Add pasta to pan; toss well. Sprinkle with cheese and basil and serve. Enjoy!

name: Scrambled Eggs on Toast with Vegemite and Avocado
description:
1 serving of scrambled eggs on toast with vegemite and avocado  contains 400 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 25% carbs, 55% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (36% of your Daily Value), fiber (19% of your Daily Value), and potassium (12% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Toast bread.Top toasted bread with butter and vegemite. Mash avocado onto bread.Scramble eggs and milk in a non-stick skillet over medium heat.Top prepared toast with scrambled eggs and freshly cracked pepper.

name: Ham and Cheese Breakfast melt
description:
1 serving of ham and cheese breakfast melt  contains 1179 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 30% carbs, 47% fat, and 24% protein.  This is a good source of protein (125% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and calcium (91% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat a sauté pan to medium. Brush one side of each piece of bread with a tablespoon of fat-free mayonnaise.
Place bread and ham separately on the sauté pan.
Flip ham after 1-2 minutes, or until slightly crispy.
Transfer ham slices, cheddar cheese, and spinach to one slice of bread, then cover with second piece of bread.
Cook for 30-60 seconds or until cheese begins to melt and bread is golden brown, then flip. Cook for 30 more seconds to seal sandwich (or until golden brown). Enjoy!

name: Sausage, Arugula, and Piquillo Pepper Sandwiches
description:
1 serving of sausage, arugula, and piquillo pepper sandwiches  contains 185 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 34% carbs, 48% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (15% of your Daily Value) and vitamin b12 (29% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Finely chop olives.Combine olives and oil, then spread on bottom halves of rolls.Heat a grill pan or large heavy skillet (not nonstick) over medium-high heat until hot, then cook sausages until hot and cooked through, about 8 minutes.Make sandwiches on rolls with peppers, sausages, and arugula. Cut in half.

name: Sweet Potato Soup with Fried Pancetta and Rosemary Croutons
description:
1 serving of sweet potato soup with fried pancetta and rosemary croutons  contains 303 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 56% carbs, 34% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (18% of your Daily Value), potassium (17% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (31% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Finely chop rosemary and shallots. Coarsely chop bacon. Peel yams, cut into cubes and mash, enough for 2 cups. Cut bread into 1/3-inch cubes, enough for 1 cup.Saut pancetta in heavy large saucepan over medium-high heat until crisp, about 5 minutes. Using slotted spoon, transfer pancetta to paper towels.Add 1 1/2 tablespoons butter to drippings in same saucepan; add shallots and reduce heat to medium. saut until shallots are soft and golden, about 4 minutes. Stir in 1 teaspoon rosemary, then mashed sweet potatoes and 31/2 cups broth. Bring to boil. Reduce heat to medium-low and simmer 10 minutes to blend flavors, adding more broth by 1/4 cupfuls to thin soup, if desired. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Puree soup in blender or processor if necessary.Meanwhile, melt remaining 11/2 tablespoons butter in small skillet over medium-high heat. Add bread cubes and remaining 1/2 teaspoon rosemary and saute until croutons are crisp and golden, about 3 minutes.Ladle soup into bowls. Top with croutons and pancetta and serve.

name: Salmon with Hoisin, Orange and Bok Choy
description:
1 serving of salmon with hoisin, orange and bok choy  contains 543 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 18% carbs, 26% fat, and 56% protein.  This is a good source of protein (140% of your Daily Value), fiber (32% of your Daily Value), and vitamin d (231% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Peel the bok choy into leaves.Peel and grate the ginger finely. Finely chop the onions and crack the coriander seeds.Preheat oven to 425F. Form bed of bok choy in center of each of two 12-inch square pieces of foil. Top bok choy with fish. Mix orange juice, green onion, hoisin, ginger,
and orange peel in small bowl. Spoon
mixture over fish, dividing equally. Sprinkle
with salt and coriander. Top with cilantro.
Fold up foil sides and pinch tightly to
seal above fish and at both ends of packets,
enclosing contents completely. Place
packets on baking sheet. Bake until fish
is just opaque in center, 12 to 14 minutes.
Transfer packets to plates and serve.

name: Penne with Lemon and Root Vegetables
description:
1 serving of penne with lemon and root vegetables  contains 378 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 64% carbs, 20% fat, and 16% protein.  This is a good source of protein (29% of your Daily Value), fiber (21% of your Daily Value), and potassium (15% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Peel and cut the carrots, parsnips, and beets into 2x1/2x1/2 inch sticks. Cut the celery stalks into half lengthwise.Heat extra-virgin olive oil in a large nonstick skillet over medium heat. Add assorted root vegetables; sprinkle with salt and pepper. Saut for 9 minutes. Using a garlic press, squeeze in garlic. Add sliced celery stalks. Saut vegetables 1 minute longer. Add 1 cup water. Cover and simmer until vegetables are tender, stirring occasionally, 12 to 15 minutes.Meanwhile, cook pasta in a large pot of boiling salted water until just tender but still firm to bite, stirring occasionally. Drain, reserving 1 cup cooking liquid.Add pasta to vegetables in skillet. Add 3/4 cup reserved cooking liquid, finely grated Parmesan cheese, finely grated lemon peel, ground nutmeg, and 4 tablespoons chopped celery leaves. Toss until heated through and sauce coats pasta, adding more cooking liquid if pasta is dry, about 2 minutes. Season pasta to taste with salt and pepper. Transfer pasta to bowls; sprinkle with remaining 2 tablespoons chopped celery leaves.

name: Broccoli Tots
description:
5 tots of broccoli tots  contains 379 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 48% carbs, 33% fat, and 19% protein.  This is a good source of protein (31% of your Daily Value), fiber (16% of your Daily Value), and potassium (8% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat the oven to 400°F. Grease a baking sheet with oil or line with parchment paper.Blanch the broccoli in boiling water for 1 minute, then shock in cold water to stop cooking. Drain well.Chop broccoli finely and mix with the egg, onions, cheddar, breadcrumbs, and seasoning. Scoop about 1.5 tablespoons of mix and shape into tater-tot shapes. Place on the prepared baking sheet.Bake until golden brown and crispy, 18-24 minutes, turning halfway through. Serve hot.

name: Low Carb Crockpot Ham & Cheese Cauliflower Soup
description:
1 serving of low carb crockpot ham & cheese cauliflower soup  contains 379 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 13% carbs, 59% fat, and 29% protein.  This is a good source of protein (49% of your Daily Value), potassium (15% of your Daily Value), and calcium (44% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Chop and add cauliflower flowerets, broth, mustard, and garlic to slow cooker. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Cook on high for 3 to 4 hours.Add cheddar cheese and puree with an immersion blender. Alternatively, you can transfer to a blender or food processor but you will need to work in batches.Add ham, pepper flakes, and additional salt and pepper to taste. Garnish with a little added cheese and some chopped green onion. Enjoy!

name: Mediterranean Beats with Garlic
description:
1 serving of mediterranean beats with garlic  contains 150 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 51% carbs, 41% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (21% of your Daily Value) and potassium (14% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook the beets: place them in a pot. Add water ( make sure the beets are fully covered with water). Bring the water to a boil and cook the beets until you can easily pierce them with a fork. It may take over one hour depending on the size of the beets. Note that the beets might stain the pot. Cool the beets before handling as they will be very hot.After beets are cooked, peel and chop them into bite-size pieces. Place them in a bowl. Add chopped garlic, olive oil and chopped cilantro. Sprinkle with salt. Enjoy!

name: Wine Glazed Grilled Shrimp
description:
1 serving of wine glazed grilled shrimp  contains 155 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 11% carbs, 13% fat, and 77% protein.  This is a good source of protein (42% of your Daily Value), vitamin b6 (24% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b12 (78% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Whisk the wine and garlic together in a bowl, toss in the shrimp, then pour everything into a resealable plastic bag. Squeeze out excess air, and seal the bag. Place the bag into a bowl to catch any leaks, then marinate in the refrigerator for at least 2 hours.Heat a cast iron grill pan over medium-high heat until it begins to smoke. Remove the shrimp from the marinade, and shake off excess. Discard the remaining marinade. Cook the shrimp until the shells turn pink and they are no longer translucent in the center, about 5 minutes.

name: Bean, Egg, and Kale Soup
description:
1 serving of bean, egg, and kale soup  contains 408 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 40% carbs, 37% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (44% of your Daily Value), fiber (38% of your Daily Value), and potassium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Heat 1 tablespoon of the oil in a medium saucepan over medium-high heat. Add the onions and cook, stirring, until soft, about 4 minutes.Add the beans and reserved bean liquid, chicken broth, soy sauce, 1/2 teaspoon salt, and a few grinds of black pepper. Bring to a simmer, add the kale and stir until wilted; bring back to a simmer and cook until the kale is tender and the stew is slightly thickened, about 15 minutes. Remove from the heat, cover and keep warm.Heat the remaining 1 tablespoon oil in a large nonstick skillet. Once the oil is hot, crack the eggs into the skillet and cook until the whites begin to set up, about 2 minutes.

Sprinkle each egg with pepper, cover and continue to cook until the whites are completely set and the yolks are still runny, about 2 minutes more. Remove from the heat.

Top each slice of bread with cheese and broil until melted. Cut each slice in quarters. Divide the stew among four bowls, top each with an egg and serve with a piece of cheese toast. Garnish wtih parsley. Enjoy!

Recipe inspired byt: http://www.foodnetwork.com/recipes/food-network-kitchens/bean-kale-and-egg-stew.html?oc=linkback

name: Ginger Garlic Baked Chicken Recipe
description:
1 serving of ginger garlic baked chicken recipe  contains 265 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 50% fat, and 42% protein.  This is a good source of protein (49% of your Daily Value), potassium (7% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (42% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Rinse the chicken and pat dry with paper towels. Add the ginger and garlic to the chicken and gently rub them on the chicken. Add the rest of the ingredients to the chicken, stir to mix well so the chicken drumsticks are nicely coated with all the ingredients.Set aside to marinate for at least 30 minutes to 2 hours in the fridge.Pre-heat the oven to 375 degrees F. Line the chicken on a parchment lined baking sheet and baking for 30-40 minutes on the middle rack, until golden brown and cooked thorugh. Enjoy!

name: Lemon and Herb Roasted Potato Nuggets
description:
1 serving of lemon and herb roasted potato nuggets  contains 360 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 74% carbs, 17% fat, and 9% protein.  This is a good source of protein (15% of your Daily Value), fiber (18% of your Daily Value), and potassium (33% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Bring a large pot of salted water to boil.Parboil the potatoes in the salted water for about 3-4 minutes, no longer.Meanwhile in a 375 degree F oven, heat a baking pan of sufficient size to hold your potatoes without crowding them. A glass or metal pan is fine, as long as it is well heated beforehand. This will help to prevent the potatoes from sticking to the pan.After parboiling, drain the potatoes and let them stand for 5 minutes. Then toss the potatoes with the lemon juice.Toss together so that the potatoes absorb the lemon juice.Add the salt, pepper, herbs, garlic cloves, and olive oil.Transfer the seasoned potatoes, garlic and oil to the hot baking pan. These should sizzle as they hit the pan; a good indication that they will not stick. Roast the potatoes for about 60-75 minutes or until they are nicely golden brown all over, turning them every 20 minutes or so. After the first 10 minutes, give the pan a shake to make sure the potatoes are not stuck to it. The roasted garlic may have to be removed before the potatoes are finished as it generally cooks faster.Recipe inspired by: http://www.rockrecipes.com/lemon-herb-roasted-potatoes/

name: Leftover Mashed Potato Quesadilla
description:
1 serving of leftover mashed potato quesadilla  contains 431 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 49% carbs, 32% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (37% of your Daily Value), potassium (12% of your Daily Value), and calcium (35% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Spread half of the mashed potatoes onto one side of the tortilla. Sprinkle half of the cheese on top and fold the tortilla in half. Repeat this step to make another quesadilla.Place both of the quesadillas into a large skillet, and cook for about 2-3 minutes on each side, until the quesadillas look golden brown and crispy.Garnish with basil and serve with some sour cream. Enjoy!

name: Pork Chops and Sugar Snap Peas with Mint Julep Glaze
description:
1 serving of pork chops and sugar snap peas with mint julep glaze  contains 447 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 15% carbs, 34% fat, and 51% protein.  This is a good source of protein (76% of your Daily Value), potassium (18% of your Daily Value), and iron (49% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Stir broth, 3 tablespoons whiskey, sugar,
and vinegar in small bowl until sugar
dissolves. Sprinkle pork with salt, pepper,
and allspice. Melt butter in medium
nonstick skillet over medium-high heat.
Add pork. Saute until just cooked through,
about 4 minutes per side (butter will
brown). Transfer pork to platter.Add whiskey mixture to skillet and
bring to boil. Add sugar snap peas and
cook until crisp-tender, about 2 minutes.
Using slotted spoon, scatter peas over
pork. Remove skillet from over heat. Add
remaining 3 tablespoons whiskey to sauce
in skillet. Boil over high heat until sauce
is reduced to thin glaze and coats spoon
lightly, about 3 minutes. Mix in mint; spoon
over pork and serve.

name: Radishes with Tarragon Beurre Blanc
description:
1 serving of radishes with tarragon beurre blanc  contains 127 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 9% carbs, 89% fat, and 2% protein.  This has a moderate calorie density, with 195 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Finely chop shallots and tarragon. Cut butter into individual tablespoon pats.Cook shallot in 1 tablespoon butter in a small heavy saucepan over moderately low heat, stirring, until softened. Add wine and boil until liquid is reduced to about 1/4 cup.Reduce heat to low and whisk in remaining 5 tablespoons butter, 1 piece at a time, lifting pan occasionally to cool mixture and adding each piece of butter before previous one has completely melted. Whisk in juice, tarragon, and salt and pepper to taste.Serve beurre blanc in a separate dish with radishes and salt.

name: Linguine with Pancetta and Sauteed Cherry Tomatoes
description:
1 serving of linguine with pancetta and sauteed cherry tomatoes  contains 652 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 33% carbs, 50% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (49% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and calcium (29% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook and coarsely chop bacon.Cook pasta in pot of boiling salted water until tender but still firm to bite. Drain, reserving 1 cup liquid. Return pasta to pot.Meanwhile, heat oil in large skillet over medium-high heat. Add garlic; stir 30 seconds. Add bacon and crushed red pepper; saut until bacon is crisp, about 4 minutes. Add tomatoes; saut until soft, about 4 minutes.Transfer tomato mixture to pot with pasta. Add 3/4 cup cheese and 1/3 cup basil. Toss over medium heat until cheese melts and sauce coats pasta, adding cooking liquid by 1/4 cupfuls if dry. Season with salt and pepper. Transfer to bowl. Sprinkle with basil. Serve remaining cheese alongside.

name: Mahimahi with Brown-Sugar Soy Glaze
description:
1 serving of mahimahi with brown-sugar soy glaze  contains 274 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 15% carbs, 21% fat, and 65% protein.  This is a good source of protein (77% of your Daily Value), potassium (18% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (126% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 200F.Cut white and pale green parts of scallions crosswise into 2-inch pieces, then thinly slice enough scallion greens to measure 3 tablespoons.Stir together brown sugar, soy sauce, and lemon juice in a small bowl until sugar is dissolved.Pat fish dry and sprinkle with salt. Heat oil in a 12-inch nonstick skillet over moderately high heat until hot but not smoking, then cook fish on 1 side until browned, 3 to 4 minutes. Turn fish over and brown 1 minute. Add soy sauce mixture and simmer, covered, until fish is almost cooked through, about 3 minutes. Transfer fish with a slotted spatula to a heatproof platter and keep warm in oven. (Fish will cook through from residual heat.)Add 2-inch scallion pieces and juices from fish platter to sauce and boil, stirring occasionally, until glaze is very thick and reduced to less than 1/4 cup, about 5 minutes. Spoon glaze over fish and sprinkle with scallion greens.

name: Bilbao-Style Red Snapper
description:
1 serving of bilbao-style red snapper  contains 77 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 28% fat, and 63% protein.  This is a good source of protein (20% of your Daily Value), vitamin d (37% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b12 (68% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions PREPARATION:  Clean and butterfly but do not bone fish.Put oven rack in middle position and preheat oven to 400F.Rinse fish and pat dry, then rub inside and out with 1 teaspoon oil and sprinkle with salt. Place opened fish, skin side down, in a large shallow baking dish (13 by 9 by 2 1/2 inches) and bake until fish is just cooked through, about 20 minutes (fish will be opaque).While fish bakes, thinly slice garlic cloves. Heat remaining 1/3 cup oil with garlic in a 10-inch heavy skillet over moderate heat, shaking skillet gently, until garlic is pale golden, about 5 minutes. Remove from heat and carefully pour in vinegar (mixture will splatter), then stir to combine. Pour garlic sauce over fish (mixture may splatter).

name: Braised Potato Salad with White Beans
description:
1 serving of braised potato salad with white beans  contains 224 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 50% carbs, 37% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (17% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (26% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cut the potatoes in half, lengthwise. Place cut side down in a non-stick skillet (I used a well-seasoned cast iron skillet). Add the water, garlic cloves, butter, and salt. Bring to a simmer over medium heat, cover, and let potatoes cook until just tender, 12 to 15 minutes.Uncover, remove and save the garlic, turn up the heat to medium-high, and cook, swirling the pan often to keep the potatoes from sticking. Water should evaporate and butter should start to sizzle. Cook, checking the bottoms of the potatoes occasionally, until the potatoes have a golden crust on the cut side, 15 minutes or so. Transfer to a medium bowl.In a small bowl, mash the cooked garlic into a paste. Add in the ingredients for the dressing and stir well.Add the beans and scallions to the bowl with the potatoes. Stir in the dressing and toss until everything is well combined.

name: Low Carb Cauliflower & Ham Soup
description:
1 serving of low carb cauliflower & ham soup  contains 211 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 22% carbs, 40% fat, and 37% protein.  This is a good source of protein (37% of your Daily Value), fiber (17% of your Daily Value), and potassium (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Combine the cauliflower, stock, water, garlic powder, and onion powder in a large soup pot. Bring to a boil and simmer for 20-30 minutes, or until the cauliflower is tender. Blend in the pot with an immersion blender (or remove to a large blender and blend in batches then return to the pan) until smooth. Stir in the ham, and thyme leaves and simmer another 10 minutes. Add the butter and apple cider vinegar. Remove from the heat and season with salt and pepper to taste. Enjoy!

name: Sweet Potato, Kale & Corn Chowder
description:
1 serving of sweet potato, kale & corn chowder  contains 240 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 73% carbs, 16% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (26% of your Daily Value), potassium (17% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (73% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Chop kale, shallots, garlic, leeks. Peel and cube sweet potato.In large, heavy bottomed soup pan sauté diced shallots and coconut oil over medium/low heat until softened. Add garlic, sweet potatoes, sea salt, pepper, cinnamon and sauté an additional minute.Add vegetable broth and water, cook until potatoes are easily pierced with a fork. Add leeks and cook an additional two minutes.Use an immersion blender (or carefully transfer to a standing blender) to rough puree the soup.Return to pan if not using an immersion blender. Add kale, corn and cook until kale is softened. Add additional salt and pepper to taste. Serve hot and enjoy!

name: Roasted Pineapple with Honey and Pistachios
description:
1 serving of roasted pineapple with honey and pistachios  contains 355 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 81% carbs, 12% fat, and 7% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (16% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (34% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Peel and core pineapple. Cut lengthwise into 8 wedges. Coarsely chop pistachios. Tear mint leaves into smaller pieces to release flavor.Preheat oven to 450F. Line a large rimmed
baking sheet with parchment paper. Stir
first 3 ingredients in a large bowl until sugar
dissolves. Add pineapple; toss to coat.
Let marinate, tossing occasionally, for
10 minutes. Place pineapple, one flat side
down, on prepared sheet; reserve marinade.Roast pineapple for 15 minutes. Turn,
brush with marinade, and roast until tender
and caramelized, 10-15 minutes. Drizzle
remaining marinade over; let cool slightly.Divide pineapple among plates. Spoon
crme frache alongside. Garnish with nuts
and mint.

name: Heavenly Chicken Tortilla Soup
description:
1 serving of heavenly chicken tortilla soup  contains 285 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 37% carbs, 27% fat, and 36% protein.  This is a good source of protein (47% of your Daily Value), fiber (22% of your Daily Value), and potassium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat 1 tbsp olive oil in a skllet over medium-high heat. Add chicken and cook for 5-7 minutes per side or until cooked through and no longer pink. Let rest 5 minutes before chopping. Set aside.In a large nonstick pot add olive oil, onions, and garlic. Sauté for 1 minute.Add chopped tortillas, tomato paste, smoked paprika, chili powder, cumin, garlic powder, and black pepper, to taste. Sauté for 2 minutesStir in chicken broth and tomatoes.  Bring up to a boil, turn down heat and simmer for 15 minutes.Add corn, beans, chicken, and fresh squeezed lime juice.  Mix well.  Cook 10 minutes more.Top with some crushed tortilla chips, if desired. Enjoy!Recipe inspired by: http://www.skinnykitchen.com/recipes/youll-love-our-heavenly-chicken-tortilla-soup/

name: Turkey, Mushroom, and Spinach Egg Muffins
description:
3 muffins of turkey, mushroom, and spinach egg muffins  contains 140 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 30% fat, and 62% protein.  This is a good source of protein (39% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (17% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 325 degrees F. Brown turkey in a sauté pan over medium-high heat, remove from pan and set aside.

Saute mushrooms and spinach until tender, about 5-10 minutes, then add back turkey.

Divide equally among 24 muffin tin cups. Pour in about 3 tablespoons of egg white mixture per each muffin cup.


Bake for about 15 minutes, or until egg is cooked through.

name: Avocado Brownies with Avocado Frosting
description:
1 serving of avocado brownies with avocado frosting  contains 439 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 48% carbs, 45% fat, and 8% protein.  This is a good source of protein (17% of your Daily Value), fiber (53% of your Daily Value), and potassium (20% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. Prepare a 9x9 inch baking tray with parchment; set aside.Melt the dark chocolate and coconut oil over a hot water bath until homogenous.Mix 1 cup cocoa power with the almond flour, 1 tsp baking powder, and 1/4 tsp of sea salt.Blend 2 avocados with the dates and 1 tsp vanilla extract. When they are blended to a paste add 2 eggs and blend again. Pour in the melted chocolate, mix and blend once more.Pour batter into the prepared pan and spread it evenly over the bottom. Bake for 30-35 minutes until a toothpick comes out mostly clean. Remove from oven and set aside to cool.Frosting: Blend 1 avocado with 1/2 cup cocoa powder, 1/2 cup maple syrup, 2 tsp vanilla extract and a pinch of salt. Cover the baked cooled brownies with the frosting. Cut onto pieces and enjoy.

name: Twice Baked Potatoes
description:
4 potato halves of twice baked potatoes  contains 1363 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 38% carbs, 51% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of protein (67% of your Daily Value), fiber (59% of your Daily Value), and potassium (70% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375 degrees F.Cook bacon to desired crispiness is reached. Drain and chop; set aside.Clean potatoes and pre-bake for 30-40 minutes, or until tender.Let potatoes rest, then cut each potato in 1/2 and scoop out insides into large bowl.Place skins cut side down on baking sheet and lightly butter then salt skins with course salt. Bake for 10 minutes.While skins bake, mix together potato mash,  1/2 of the diced bacon, 4 tbsp butter, sour cream, 4 oz cheddar, salt, pepper, and 2 tbsp of the chives until butter is thoroughly melted, and potato mix is smooth.Let skins rest, then add mixture level to skin edge, top with remaining cheddar, chives and bacon, then bake for another 15-20 minutes (or until cheese is melted). Enjoy!

name: Eggplant Lasagna Rolls
description:
2 Rolls of eggplant lasagna rolls  contains 351 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 29% carbs, 43% fat, and 28% protein.  This is a good source of protein (46% of your Daily Value), fiber (30% of your Daily Value), and potassium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat the oven to 425 degrees F.To slice the eggplants, chop the top and bottom ends off, and slice into 6-8 pieces lengthwise. Add the slices to a colander, and generously sprinkle with salt. Set aside for about 15 minutes or until the slices start to “sweat”. (Little droplets will form along the cut surfaces of the eggplant slices.)Rinse the eggplant slices well, and pat dry with a paper towel. Arrange in a single layer on a cookie sheet, and generously spray with cooking oil. Flip the slices, and add oil to the other side. Bake for about 12 minutes or until slices are just beginning to get slightly browned. Remove from the oven and set a side to cool.As the eggplant slices bake, make the cheese filling by combining the ricotta, spinach, egg, basil, garlic, and 1 cup of the mozzarella cheese together in a large bowl. Sprinkle with salt and pepper, and stir to combine.When the eggplant slices are cool enough to handle, you are ready to make your rolls. Spread 1/2 cup of the tomato sauce evenly along the bottom of a 9-inch by 13-inch baking dish.

Take a slice of eggplant, and add about 2-3 tablespoons of cheese filling to the center of the slice. Roll into a burrito shape so that the two ends fold over each other, and place end side down into your prepared baking dish. Continue rolling the eggplant slices until you’ve used up your cheese and eggplant slices.Spoon the rest of the tomato sauce along the tops of the eggplant rolls in your pan. Top evenly with the rest of your mozzarella cheese.

Bake for 20-30 minutes or until cheese is melted and sauce in the bottom of the pan is bubbly.

Serve with chopped fresh parsley.

name: Spring Minestrone
description:
1 servings of spring minestrone  contains 423 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 64% carbs, 17% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (40% of your Daily Value), fiber (30% of your Daily Value), and potassium (51% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Wash, peel and chop carrots and potatoes, thinly slice leeks, and chop dill. Slice asparagus. Drain and rinse beans. Put these aside until recipe calls for them.In 8-quart sauce pot, heat 2 tablespoons olive oil on medium. Add carrots, leek, fresh thyme, and 1/4 teaspoon salt. Cook 8 minutes, stirring.Add red potatoes, and lower-sodium vegetable or chicken broth. Partially cover and heat to boiling on high; reduce heat to simmer. Cook 25 minutes or until potatoes are tender. Add asparagus and simmer 3 minutes or until tender. Discard thyme. Stir in navy beans (optional), fresh dill, 1/4 teaspoon salt and 1/2 teaspoon pepper.

name: Baked Egg Custard with Gruyre and Chives
description:
1 serving of baked egg custard with gruyre and chives  contains 295 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 7% carbs, 64% fat, and 29% protein.  This is a good source of protein (38% of your Daily Value), calcium (41% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (25% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Coarsely grate Gouda cheese.Preheat oven to 350F with rack in middle. Butter a 2-quart shallow baking dish (2 inches deep).Sprinkle Gouda and chives evenly in dish.Blend eggs, milk, cream cheese, and nutmeg in a blender with 
1/2 teaspoon pepper and 1/4 teaspoon salt until smooth.Pour egg mixture over Gouda and chives in dish and bake until puffed, set, and golden, 35 to 45 minutes. Serve warm or at room temperature.

name: High Fat Chorizo, Cheese, and Egg Burrito
description:
1 burrito of high fat chorizo, cheese, and egg burrito  contains 715 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 35% carbs, 45% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (64% of your Daily Value), fiber (16% of your Daily Value), and potassium (10% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook chorizo over medium to high heat, stirring and breaking up meat often, until bubbling and completely separated, approximately 4-5 minutes. Drain.Whisk together eggs in a large bowl and stir in chorizo.Scramble egg/chorizo mixture over medium to high heat to desired consistency.Meanwhile, prepare rice as per package directions.Fill tortilla with desired amounts of chorizo/egg mixture, rice, cheese, and salsa. Fold and enjoy.

name: Scotch Egg
description:
1 serving of scotch egg  contains 2259 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 14% carbs, 65% fat, and 21% protein.  This is a good source of protein (207% of your Daily Value), fiber (26% of your Daily Value), and potassium (37% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Place 3 of the eggs in a saucepan and add cold water to cover completely. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer for 10 minutes.Pour off the hot water and add cold water to the pan. Once the eggs are cool, peel them and set aside.Preheat oven to 350°F (175°C).In a bowl, beat the remaining egg.Place the flour and panko in separate bowls.In a medium bowl, combine the ground beef, garlic, hot sauce, Worcestershire sauce, salt, and pepper. Mix well.Divide the meat mixture into 4 equal portions. Flatten each portion into a patty and place a peeled egg on top.Carefully shape the meat around each egg, pinching the seams to seal. Gently roll the meat-wrapped eggs between your palms to ensure the meat is evenly distributed.Roll each meat-wrapped egg in the flour, then dip in the beaten egg, and finally coat in the panko.Heat the olive oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Brown the meat-wrapped eggs on all sides for about 1 minute per side.Transfer the browned eggs to a baking sheet lined with aluminum foil or a silicone mat. Bake for 15-20 minutes.To make the sauce, whisk together the mayonnaise, sour cream, mustard, and cayenne pepper sauce.Cut each Scotch egg into quarters and drizzle with the sauce. Serve warm.

name: Broccoli & Feta Omelet with Toast
description:
1 omelet of broccoli & feta omelet with toast  contains 377 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 34% carbs, 40% fat, and 26% protein.  This is a good source of protein (44% of your Daily Value), fiber (16% of your Daily Value), and potassium (12% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat a non-stick skillet over medium heat. Coat pan with cooking spray. Add chopped broccoli, and cook 3 minutes.Combine egg, feta, and dill in a small bowl. Add egg mixture to pan. Cook 3 to 4 minutes; flip omelet and cook 2 minutes or until cooked through. Serve with toast.

name: Peanut Butter, Spinach, and Banana Smoothie
description:
1 serving of peanut butter, spinach, and banana smoothie  contains 379 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 48% carbs, 26% fat, and 26% protein.  This is a good source of protein (47% of your Daily Value), fiber (18% of your Daily Value), and potassium (26% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Combine all ingredients in a blender and pulse until smooth. Enjoy!

name: Spaghetti Squash with Moroccan Spices
description:
1 serving of spaghetti squash with moroccan spices  contains 233 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 46% carbs, 50% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (22% of your Daily Value), potassium (10% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (14% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Finely chop cilantro. Cut butter into 4 pieces.Pierce squash (about an inch deep) all over with a small sharp knife to prevent bursting. Cook in an 800-watt microwave oven on high power (100 percent) for 6 to 7 minutes. Turn squash over and microwave until squash feels slightly soft when pressed, 8 to 10 minutes more. Cool squash for 5 minutes.Meanwhile, melt butter in a small heavy saucepan over moderately high heat. Add garlic and cook, stirring, until golden, about 1 minute. Stir in spices and salt and remove from heat.Carefully halve squash lengthwise (it will give off steam) and remove and discard seeds. Working over a bowl, scrape squash flesh with a fork, loosening and separating strands as you remove it from skin. Toss with spiced butter and cilantro.

name: Crispy Baked Honey Sriracha Chicken Drumsticks
description:
1 serving of crispy baked honey sriracha chicken drumsticks  contains 272 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 36% carbs, 43% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F. Line a baking sheet with foil, then top it with wire cooling racks to hold the chicken up off the baking sheet. For easy cleaning, spritz the wire racks with non-stick spray.Place the chicken drumsticks in a large bowl and season with a pinch of salt and pepper. Sprinkle the cornstarch over top, then stir until the drumsticks are evenly coated in cornstarch.Place the coated chicken pieces on the prepared baking sheet. Bake the drumsticks for about 50 minutes, or until the surface is golden brown and crispy.While the chicken is in the oven, combine the sriracha, butter, and honey in a small sauce pot. Heat over a low flame until the butter is melted and the sauce is smooth. Set the sauce aside.When the chicken comes out of the oven, brush the sauce liberally over the surface of the chicken, then serve.

name: Overnight-Marinated Baked Chipotle Chicken
description:
1 serving of overnight-marinated baked chipotle chicken  contains 392 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 54% fat, and 38% protein.  This is a good source of protein (66% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (73% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Stir together everything but the chicken.Add chicken and marinade to a large plastic bag and seal. Chill overnight or up to 24 hours.Preheat oven to 400 degrees F. Remove chicken from plastic bag and discard excess marinade. Place chicken side by side in a large, greased baking dish. Cover with foil.Bake for 25-35 minutes until chicken is cooked through. Uncover and bake 5-10 minutes longer. Serve chicken as desired and enjoy!

name: Keto Breakfast "Potatoes"
description:
1 servings of keto breakfast "potatoes"  contains 214 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 82% fat, and 10% protein.  This has a moderate calorie density, with 207 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Peel and dice turnips.Add the oil to a large skillet over medium-high heat. Add in the turnips and salt. Cook 5-7 minutes stirring occasionally. Chop the bacon into small pieces and add to the skillet. Continue to cook another 5-7 minutes until the bacon is crispy.Transfer to a plate and serve.

name: Feta & Pesto Omelette
description:
1 omelette of feta & pesto omelette  contains 471 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 3% carbs, 77% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (42% of your Daily Value), calcium (24% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (48% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Melt butter in heated skilled.Beat your eggs in a bowl with heavy cream, salt, and pepper. Pour into pan cook until almond done.Spread pesto on half and sprinkle with feta cheese.Fold the omelette over onto itself and cook for another 4-5 minutes so that the feta cheese melts and the eggs cook thoroughly.

name: Lemony Roasted Carrots
description:
1 serving of lemony roasted carrots  contains 152 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 67% carbs, 28% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (22% of your Daily Value), potassium (15% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (200% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 450 degrees F.
In foil lined roasting pan, toss carrots with oil and cayenne and season with salt.
Arrange in single layer, using two pans if needed.
Roast ,tossing once halfway through, for 30-40 minutes, or until tender.
In a small bowl, whisk together honey, zest and lemon juice. Season with salt. Drizzled over carrots and toss to coat. Serve and enjoy!

name: Idaho Bacon Bit Hot Dog
description:
1 serving of idaho bacon bit hot dog  contains 480 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 56% carbs, 30% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of protein (29% of your Daily Value), fiber (17% of your Daily Value), and potassium (36% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 425 degrees F.Bake potato for about 60 minutes.Cook hot dog as per desired preference (e.g. boil, grill, microwave).Open potato like a bun and top with hot dog, sour cream, chives, and bacon bits. Enjoy!

name: Spoon-Bread Muffins
description:
1 serving of spoon-bread muffins  contains 173 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 53% carbs, 24% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (18% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and calcium (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 425F with rack in middle. Butter muffin cups.Whisk together cornmeal, baking soda, and salt in a bowl. Whisk buttermilk into eggs, then add to cornmeal mixture and whisk vigorously until smooth. Whisk in butter.Divide batter among muffin cups and bake until edges begin to pull away from sides and a wooden pick inserted in center of a muffin comes out clean, 20 to 25 minutes. Turn out onto a rack and serve warm.

name: Peppery Pasta Carbonara with Poached Egg
description:
1 serving of peppery pasta carbonara with poached egg  contains 757 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 46% carbs, 35% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (62% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and calcium (40% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Cook bacon in a 10-inch nonstick skillet over medium heat until crisp. Transfer bacon with a slotted spoon to paper towels to drain.Meanwhile, cook spaghetti in a 4-quart saucepan of salted boiling water until al dente. Reserve 1/3 cup cooking water, then 
transfer spaghetti with tongs to a small bowl, shaking off excess water, and keep pan of water simmering.Pour off all but 2 teaspoons bacon fat from skillet, then whisk butter, 1 tbsp. at a time, into fat in skillet over medium heat. Add spaghetti, reserved cooking water, cheese, and a rounded 1/4 teaspoon pepper and cook, stirring, until sauce is thickened and almost completely absorbed, 2 to 3 minutes. Add bacon and 1 tablespoon chopped parsley and toss. Season with salt and pepper.Break egg into a cup and gently slide into water. Poach at a bare simmer to desired doneness (we prefer a firm white with a runny yolk, 2 to 3 minutes).Serve pasta topped with egg (transfer using a slotted spoon). Sprinkle with remaining chopped parsley if desired.

name: Roasted Cauliflower with Kalamata Vinaigrette
description:
1 serving of roasted cauliflower with kalamata vinaigrette  contains 185 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 24% carbs, 68% fat, and 8% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (17% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (29% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions PREPARATION:  Finely chop olives.Preheat oven to 450F with rack in lower third.Cut cauliflower lengthwise into 3/4-inch-thick slices. Put in a large 4-sided sheet pan and toss with 2 tablespoon oil and 
1/2 teaspoon each of salt and pepper. Roast, turning once or twice, until golden and just tender, about 25 minutes.While cauliflower roasts, mince and mash garlic to a paste with a pinch of salt, then whisk together with lemon juice, remaining 2 tablespoons oil, olives, 1/8 teaspoon salt, and 1/2 teaspoon pepper. Serve cauliflower drizzled with Kalamata vinaigrette.

name: Whole-Wheat Pasta with Pecorino and Pepper
description:
1 serving of whole-wheat pasta with pecorino and pepper  contains 400 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 59% carbs, 23% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (32% of your Daily Value), calcium (29% of your Daily Value), and riboflavin (b2) (30% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions PREPARATION:  Chop parsley.Toast peppercorns in a dry small skillet over medium-high heat, shaking  skillet, until fragrant and beginning to pop, 2 to 3 minutes. Coarsely crush peppercorns with a mortar and pestle or wrap in a kitchen towel (not terry cloth) and press with bottom of a heavy skillet.Cook spaghetti in a pasta pot of boiling salted water (2 tablespoons salt for  6 quarts water) until al dente.Meanwhile, fill a large ceramic bowl with hot water to warm it. Just before pasta is done cooking, drain bowl but do not dry.Reserve 1 cup pasta-cooking water, then quickly drain pasta (do not shake off excess water) and add to warm bowl. Sprinkle 1 1/4 cups cheese and 1/2 cup cooking water evenly over pasta and toss quickly. Toss in parsley (if using) and 2 teaspoons crushed pepper. If pasta seems dry, toss with some additional cooking water. Serve pasta immediately, sprinkled with remaining pepper and cheese. Serve additional cheese on the side.

name: Pumpkin Protein Bars
description:
1 square of pumpkin protein bars  contains 80 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 61% carbs, 17% fat, and 22% protein.  This is a good source of vitamin a (12% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat the oven to 350°F.Spray a 9x13 inch Pyrex dish with non-stick spray.Combine the first 11 ingredients and mix well.Add the final 2 ingredients and mix together well.Spread batter into the Pyrex dish and bake for 30 minutes.Allow to cool. Then cut into 30 squares. Enjoy!

name: Lemon Fat Bombs
description:
1 bomb of lemon fat bombs  contains 80 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 2% carbs, 96% fat, and 2% protein.  This has a relatively high calorie density, with 520 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Melt the cream cheese in the microwave in short bursts. Then, add the butter and coconut oil and melt some more.Whisk together and then add the sweetener, lemon juice, and whipping cream.Whisk and then pour into silicone molds. Freeze to set, then store in the refrigerator.

name: Curried Vegetarian Meatballs
description:
1 serving of curried vegetarian meatballs  contains 430 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 22% carbs, 71% fat, and 7% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (22% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and iron (58% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions To make "meatballs:" Combine lentils and water in a medium pot. Bring to a boil, reduce to a simmer, and cook until lentils are tender, 23 to 25 minutes. If lentils are not tender and water has been absorbed, add more water and continue to cook. Drain off any excess water.Heat 1 tbsp olive oil in a skillet over medium-low heat and add the scallions, 1 clove minced garlic and carrots, cooking and cook for 4 to 6 minutes until carrots are tender.In a food processor, combine the cooked lentils, green onion mixture, nuts, panko, herbs, salt, and pepper. Pulse a few times to start combining the mixture. Crack the egg in and pulse a few more times until the mixture is combined but the lentils are still holding shape. Set aside and let rest while the oven preheats to 425˚ F.Take the lentil mixture and roll into 12 balls, roughly the size of a golfball. Place on a baking tray covered with parchment paper and brush with olive oil. Bake meatballs until browning and crisp, 25 to 30 minutes.Meanwhile, heat oil in a large Dutch oven or other heavy pot over medium. Add chopped onions, smashed remaining garlic, and ginger and cook, stirring often, until onions are translucent and starting to brown, 8–10 minutes.Stir in chiles, curry powder, cumin, turmeric, coriander, and peppercorns. Cook, stirring often, until mixture is very fragrant and spices begin to stick to the pot, about 2 minutes. Add tomatoes, stirring and scraping bottom of pot, and bring to a boil. Add bay leaf, 1 Tbsp. salt, and 2 cups water; return to a boil. Reduce heat and simmer until flavors have melded, 25–30 minutes.Let curry sauce cool slightly, then transfer to a blender; blend until very smooth. Wipe out any bits remaining in pot and transfer curry sauce back to pot. Stir in lemon juice and cayenne; taste sauce and season with more salt if needed.Bring sauce up to a gentle simmer over medium heat, add the lentil meatballs to the sauce and heat through for a few minutes and serve.

name: Artichoke & tomato bake
description:
1 artichoke of artichoke & tomato bake  contains 169 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 68% carbs, 17% fat, and 16% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (35% of your Daily Value), potassium (17% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (23% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Chop celery, carrots, onions, and mince garlic. Finely grate lemon rind. Combine rind and parsley in a bowl. Set aside. Cut lemon in half and squeeze juice into a large bowl of water.Remove artichoke stems. Cut 3 cm from the top of 1 artichoke. Rub cut sides with 1 lemon half. Peel 2 layers of outer leaves or until pale leaves are exposed. Scoop out and discard furry choke from the centre. Place the artichoke in the bowl of lemon water to prevent it going brown. Repeat with the remaining artichokes.Drain artichokes. Place in a large saucepan and cover with water. Bring to the boil over high heat. Reduce heat to medium and simmer for 15 minutes or until tender. Drain.Meanwhile, heat the oil in a saucepan over medium-low heat. Cook onion, carrot, celery and garlic, stirring, for 5 minutes or until soft. Add tomato. Increase heat to medium-high. Bring to a simmer. Cook for 15 minutes or until thickened. Season with salt and pepper.Preheat oven to 180°C. Spoon three-quarters of tomato mixture over base of a 2L (8-cup) capacity baking dish. Arrange artichokes over tomato mixture and fill with remaining sauce. Top with breadcrumbs. Bake for 30 minutes or until the breadcrumbs are golden. Top with the parsley mixture.

name: Lentil Cakes
description:
1 cake of lentil cakes  contains 277 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 48% carbs, 35% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (21% of your Daily Value), fiber (17% of your Daily Value), and potassium (7% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Place lentils and water in a saucepan, and bring to a boil. Cover, reduce heat to low, and simmer until tender, about 30 minutes. Drain.In a large bowl, mix together the cooked lentils, milk, wheat and barley cereal, eggs and walnuts. Season with onion soup mix and poultry seasoning. Mix well using your hands, as the mixture will be very thick. Let stand for 30 minutes, or refrigerate overnight.Heat oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Use an ice cream scoop to portion out balls of the lentil mixture. Drop the scoops into bread crumbs, and coat while flattening into patties. Fry burgers in the hot skillet until nicely browned on both sides, about 5 minutes per side, depending on the thickness of the patties.

name: Spiced Black Lentils with Yogurt and Mint
description:
1 serving of spiced black lentils with yogurt and mint  contains 288 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 49% carbs, 25% fat, and 26% protein.  This is a good source of protein (35% of your Daily Value), fiber (21% of your Daily Value), and potassium (11% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Chop the onions and garlic finely.
Crush the coriander,cumin and mustard seeds.
Stir coriander, cumin, mustard seeds,
and 2 tablespoons oil in a medium saucepan over
medium-high heat until sizzling, about
1 minute. Add onion and garlic; cook, stirring
often, until just softened, about 5 minutes.
Add lentils and 3 cups broth; bring to a boil.
Reduce heat and simmer, partially covered,
adding broth as needed to keep lentils
covered, until lentils are soft, 3040 minutes.
Stir in vinegar; season with salt and pepper.Transfer lentils to a large bowl and top with
yogurt. Season with salt and pepper, drizzle
with oil, and top with mint.DO AHEAD: Lentils can be cooked 2 days
ahead. Let cool; cover and chill.

name: Rice Bowl
description:
1 bowl of rice bowl  contains 445 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 81% carbs, 8% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of protein (22% of your Daily Value), fiber (35% of your Daily Value), and potassium (13% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare rice as per package directions.Fold in chopped tomatoes, shredded carrots, and chopped scallion.Drain chickpeas and fold into rice mixture. Place a bed of greens on a plate and top with rice. Enjoy!

name: Buffalo Chicken Sandwich
description:
1 sandwich of buffalo chicken sandwich  contains 364 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 26% carbs, 44% fat, and 30% protein.  This is a good source of protein (47% of your Daily Value), potassium (8% of your Daily Value), and calcium (26% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Throw chicken, hot sauce, and ranch mix in slow cooker for 8 hours on low. Shred chicken with 2 forks and return to slow cooker. Toss to coat.Make into a sandwich; top with ranch and cheese. Enjoy!

name: Mexican Chicken Stuffed Peppers
description:
1 serving of mexican chicken stuffed peppers  contains 484 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 17% carbs, 48% fat, and 35% protein.  This is a good source of protein (77% of your Daily Value), fiber (24% of your Daily Value), and potassium (39% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Prepare seasoning: In a small dry skillet on medium-low, toast cumin seeds for 1 to 2 minutes, until fragrant, shaking skillet occasionally. Remove from heat; cool 2 minutes. Transfer seeds to a spice grinder; grind to a powder. Transfer cumin to a small bowl and stir in remaining seasoning ingredients.

In a large skillet on medium, heat oil. Add onion, garlic, and chile; cook, stirring, 2 minutes. Add chicken; cook until no longer pink. Sprinkle with 2 tbsp seasoning mixture; stir well. 

Stir in tomatoes and bring to a boil. Reduce heat; then simmer, uncovered, 5 to 7 minutes or until most of the liquid has evaporated. Stir in 1/4 cup cilantro.

Meanwhile, cut bell peppers in half vertically (from stems to bottoms). Remove and discard stems, seeds, and membranes. In a large pot, blanch peppers in boiling water, 2 to 3 minutes or just until tender; drain. Fill peppers with chicken mixture.

For each serving, arrange 2 pepper halves on a plate. Sprinkle with remaining 1/4 cup cilantro and serve with lime wedges.

name: Vietnamese Diced Beef
description:
1 serving of vietnamese diced beef  contains 317 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 14% carbs, 60% fat, and 26% protein.  This is a good source of protein (37% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (47% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Combine sauces, garlic, sugar and sesame oil in a bowl. Season with salt and pepper. Add beef. Cover with plastic wrap. Refrigerate for 4 hours.To make lime dipping sauce, combine lime juice, sugar and chilli in a small bowl. Season with salt and white pepper. Stir until sugar dissolves. Cover with plastic wrap. Refrigerate until required.Heat a non-stick wok on high. Spray with oil. Drain beef, reserving marinade. Stir-fry onion for 3 minutes or until brown. Transfer to a plate. Spray wok with oil. Stir-fry one-third of beef for 2 minutes each side or until cooked to your liking. Transfer to plate. Repeat with oil and remaining beef, in 2 batches. Return onion and beef to wok. Add marinade and combine. Cook unitl marinade is well heated through. Enjoy!

name: Greek Chicken Salad
description:
1 serving of greek chicken salad  contains 383 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 14% carbs, 57% fat, and 29% protein.  This is a good source of protein (50% of your Daily Value), potassium (12% of your Daily Value), and calcium (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Heat oil in a pan over medium-high heat. Cook chopped chicken for 7-12 minutes until cooked through and no longer pink. Remove from heat and set aside.In a large mixing bowl combine chicken, cucumber, feta cheese, and olives; set aside.
In small mixing bowl, stir together mayonaisse, yogurt, oregano, garlic, and parsley.
Add dressing to large mixing bowl.Toss to coat. Enjoy!

name: Dynamite Chili
description:
1 serving of dynamite chili  contains 331 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 28% carbs, 29% fat, and 43% protein.  This is a good source of protein (65% of your Daily Value), fiber (21% of your Daily Value), and potassium (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Brown meat and onions in a sauté pan over medium-high heat until evenly cooked through, about 12 minutes.Add in remaining ingredients. Bring to a boil then reduce heat to a simmer for 15 minutes. Enjoy!

name: Tilapia Parmesan
description:
1 serving of tilapia parmesan  contains 402 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 4% carbs, 48% fat, and 49% protein.  This is a good source of protein (88% of your Daily Value), vitamin d (49% of your Daily Value), and potassium (16% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. In a buttered 13-by-9-inch baking dish or jellyroll pan, lay fillets in single layer. Do not stack fillets.Brush top with juice.In bowl combine cheese, butter, mayonnaise, onions, and seasonings. Mix well with fork.Bake fish in preheated oven 10 to 20 minutes or until fish just starts to flake. Spread with cheese mixture and bake until golden brown, about 5 minutes.Baking time will depend on the thickness of the fish you use.  Watch fish closely so that it does not overcook. Serve with sriracha and enjoy!

name: Baked Zucchini and Tomato with Mozzarella
description:
1 serving of baked zucchini and tomato with mozzarella  contains 216 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 27% carbs, 42% fat, and 31% protein.  This is a good source of protein (31% of your Daily Value), potassium (18% of your Daily Value), and calcium (41% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Chop garlic, dice onion, slice zucchini and tomato.Stir fry zucchini in the oil over medium-high heat, until tender.Stir fry tomato and onion until juice comes out, then add zucchini and stir together; add in salt and pepper to taste.Preheat oven to 350 degree F.Simmer vegetables in low heat for 10 minutes.Pour into a baking pan and bake for 5 minutes, then add mozzarella on top and bake for another 12 minutes. Enjoy!

name: Deep Dish Pizza
description:
1 serving of deep dish pizza  contains 378 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 23% carbs, 51% fat, and 26% protein.  This is a good source of protein (43% of your Daily Value), calcium (25% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b12 (77% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 425 degrees F.
Cook meat in a nonstick skillet over medium-high heat until browned through, stirring until it crumbles. Drain, if necessary, and return to skillet. Add tomatoes, and cook until heated through.
While meat cooks, coat a 13 x 9 inch baking dish with cooking spray. Unroll pizza crust dough, and press into bottom and halfway up sides of the baking dish. Top the pizza crust with meat mixture.
Bake, uncovered, at 425 degrees F for 12 minutes. Top with cheese, and bake 5 minutes or until crust is browned and cheese melts. Cool 5 minutes before serving. Enjoy!

name: Spinach and Mushroom Wrap
description:
1 serving of spinach and mushroom wrap  contains 831 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 23% carbs, 60% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (63% of your Daily Value), fiber (18% of your Daily Value), and potassium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Heat oil in a pan over medium heat. Sauté mushrooms and onions until onions are translucent and mushrooms are tender, about 5-7 minutes. Add garlic and sauté until fragrant, about 1 minute. Add spinach and sauté until just wilted, 1-2 minutes.Scramble the egg, and then pour over the mushroo/spinach mixture.Salt and pepper to taste.Lay flat the wonton wrapper. Spread the grated cheese and top with the eggs. Wrap and bake in oven for 15 minutes. Enjoy!

name: 30-Minute Chicken Stroganoff
description:
1 serving of 30-minute chicken stroganoff  contains 465 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 38% carbs, 27% fat, and 35% protein.  This is a good source of protein (68% of your Daily Value), potassium (19% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (18% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat ½ tablespoon of olive oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Season the chicken with ¼ teaspoon of salt and a pinch of black pepper.When the oil is heated, brown the chicken on all sides for about 2-3 minutes (it does not need to be fully cooked at this point). Remove the chicken and set it aside on a plate.Add the remaining oil to the skillet and cook the garlic, onions, and mushrooms. Turn the heat to low and cook for 12-15 minutes, until the mushrooms are very soft and cooked down, stirring frequently.Sprinkle the flour over the vegetables and stir to coat evenly.Take the skillet off of the heat and deglaze it with the cooking wine, scraping the bottom of the skillet with a wooden spoon. Allow the wine to cook for about 2 minutes.Return the previously set-aside chicken to the skillet. Stir in the sour cream, yogurt, and milk. Cook for an additional 5 minutes, or until the sauce thickens and the chicken is cooked through.While the stroganoff is cooking, cook the pasta in a large pot of salted water, according to package directions for al dente. Drain.Slice chicken and return to pan. To serve, spoon 1½ cups of egg noodles with ¾ cup of the chicken and sauce. Garnish with the parsley.Recipe inspired by: https://www.skinnymom.com/recipe-30-minute-chicken-stroganoff/

name: Banana Bruschetta
description:
1 serving of banana bruschetta  contains 329 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 62% carbs, 19% fat, and 19% protein.  This is a good source of protein (28% of your Daily Value), fiber (22% of your Daily Value), and potassium (11% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Toast bread.Spread toast with cottage cheese and top with banana slices.Sprinkle with cinnamon, honey, and chopped walnuts to serve. Enjoy!

name: Lemonade Tea Cake Cookies
description:
1 cookie of lemonade tea cake cookies  contains 95 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 65% carbs, 30% fat, and 5% protein.  This has a relatively high calorie density, with 382 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Preheat the oven to 375 degrees F. In the bowl of a stand mixer cream the butter and sugar until light and fluffy. Then whip in egg and add vanilla. Add in flour a little at a time until the dough comes together.  Let the dough rest on the counter for 5 minutes, then cover with a kitchen towel so that it does not dry out.Divide the dough in half. Sprinkle your working surface with additional flour, and then roll to 1/4 of an inch thickness. Use the cutter of your choice and place cut cookies on a cookie sheet, prepared with parchment, and bake for 6-7 minutes. Then place on a wire cooling rack. Lemon Glaze: Wisk together all remaining ingredients in a small bowl.Assembly: Dip warm cookies in the glaze.If your glaze begins to harden before you have dipped all of your cookies, you can pop it in the microwave for 10 seconds to warm it up a bit.

name: Ice Cream with Roasted Grapes and Walnut Oil
description:
1 serving of ice cream with roasted grapes and walnut oil  contains 421 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 37% carbs, 58% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (8% of your Daily Value) and vitamin a (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Remove pistachio nuts from shell and roast on sheet pan in a 325-degree oven for approximately 10 minutes.Preheat broiler.Toss grapes with 2 teaspoons oil in a shallow baking pan and broil 5 to 6 inches from heat just until grapes burst, about 6 minutes.Spoon grapes with juice over scoops of ice cream, then sprinkle with nuts and drizzle each serving with 1 teaspoon of remaining oil.

name: Fish Tagine with Tomatoes, Capers, and Cinnamon
description:
1 serving of fish tagine with tomatoes, capers, and cinnamon  contains 180 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 3% carbs, 50% fat, and 46% protein.  This is a good source of protein (37% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions PREPARATION:  Chop tomatoes. Heat cumin in oil in a 12-inch heavy skillet over medium heat, stirring occasionally, until fragrant, about 1 minute. Stir in tomatoes, capers, cinnamon, and 1/4 teaspoon each of salt and pepper and simmer, uncovered, stirring occasionally, until thickened, about 10 minutes.Pat fish dry and sprinkle with 1/4 teaspoon each of salt and pepper, then add to skillet. Cover and simmer until fish is just cooked through, 7 to 10 minutes.Combine the fish and tomato sauce and enjoy!

name: Crack Corn
description:
1 Corn of crack corn  contains 245 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 37% carbs, 57% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (6% of your Daily Value) and vitamin a (16% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat grill to high. Oil grates and add corn.Grill corn, turning after 5 minutes.Meanwhile, prepare the crack sauce by combining brown sugar, cayenne pepper, salt, pepper, and melted butter.Baste the corn with the crack sauce while grilling. Continue grilling until the corn is charred and tender, about 5 minutes more.Squeeze lime juice over the corn and serve.

name: Butternut Squash with Pumpkin-Seed Pesto
description:
1 serving of butternut squash with pumpkin-seed pesto  contains 167 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 43% carbs, 51% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (12% of your Daily Value), vitamin a (83% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (34% of your Daily Value).
