instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 500F with rack in middle.Toss butternut squash with 2 tablespoons oil and 1/2 teaspoon salt, then arrange in 1 layer in a 17- by 12- by 1-inch baking pan and roast, turning occasionally, until golden brown on edges, 20 to 25 minutes.Meanwhile, toast pumpkin seeds in 1 tablespoon oil in a large heavy skillet over medium-high heat, stirring frequently, until seeds are puffed and beginning to brown, 2 to 4 minutes. Transfer to a large plate and cool.Pulse cooled seeds in a food processor with cilantro, lemon juice, 1/4 teaspoon each of salt and pepper, and remaining tablespoon oil to a coarse paste (not finely ground).Toss squash with pesto and salt and pepper to taste. Serve immediately.

name: Golden Cauliflower Soup
description:
1 servings of golden cauliflower soup  contains 202 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 26% carbs, 64% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (8% of your Daily Value), magnesium (18% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (72% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Chop all vegetables.Heat the oil in a deep soup pot. Add the onion, garlic, cauliflower, cashews, and turmeric. Saute for 10 minutes or until very fragrant.Add the water and salt and bring to a simmer. Continue simmering until cauliflower is softened.Transfer the soup in batches to a blender and blend into a creamy consistency.Return to pot, add lemon juice, stir, and serve.

name: Sun-Dried Tomato & Lentil Salad
description:
1 serving of sun-dried tomato & lentil salad  contains 202 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 51% carbs, 31% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (16% of your Daily Value), fiber (20% of your Daily Value), and potassium (10% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Rinse lentils and set to simmer in water on medium heat for about 15 minutes until almost soft. Drain and reserve.Slice tomatoes and olives and dice bell pepper. Mince garlic.When lentils are cool, combine all ingredients in a bowl and toss until evenly distributed.

name: Tomato and Arugula Salad with Grilled Steak and Portabella Mushrooms
description:
1 serving of tomato and arugula salad with grilled steak and portabella mushrooms  contains 656 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 9% carbs, 75% fat, and 16% protein.  This is a good source of protein (48% of your Daily Value), potassium (23% of your Daily Value), and iron (44% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat the grill to medium.  Press the garlic cloves; take two pressed cloves and mix in a small bowl with two tablespoons of olive oil.  Brush some of the mixture on the mushrooms, and then on the steak.  Sprinkle mushrooms and steak liberally with salt and pepper, then set aside.  In another small bowl, make the vinaigrette by mixing the remaining garlic with the vinegar and lemon juice.  Whisk in the remaining oil.  Add salt and pepper.Grill the steak for about 4 minutes per side for medium rare (or longer; to preference), then the mushrooms for 2-3 minutes while the steak rests.  

While steak and mushrooms cook, place arugula on a serving platter and top with sundried tomatoes.  Thinly slice the grilled mushrooms and scatter them throughout the salad.  Slice steak across the grain into strips and add to the salad.  Drizzle the steak, tomatoes and mushrooms with the vinaigrette and sprinkle with a little additional salt and pepper.

name: Baked Blueberry Oatmeal
description:
1 Piece of baked blueberry oatmeal  contains 170 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 76% carbs, 12% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (7% of your Daily Value) and riboflavin (b2) (26% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven 375 degrees F.

Butter an 8x8 inch baking dish and cover bottom with 1/2" banana slices. Sprinkle 3/4 cup blueberries over top bananas and set aside.

In medium bowl mix together oats, baking powder, cinnamon, and salt. Stir to combine.

In another bowl beat together milk, egg, butter, vanilla, and maple syrup.

Add oats to dish and gently pour milk mixture over oats. Gently tap pan on the counter to make sure the milk has gone all the way through the oats.

Sprinkle the top with remaining blueberries and cook in oven for 35 to 45 minutes until the top is golden brown and the oatmeal is set. If desired, drizzle the top with more maple syrup.

name: Low-Carb Chicken Tenders
description:
1 serving of low-carb chicken tenders  contains 460 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 18% carbs, 65% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (37% of your Daily Value), potassium (7% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.
Combine all dry ingredients.
Line a shallow pan with foil.
Melt butter in a shallow dish.
Dip each piece in butter then roll in seasoning mixture and place in pan.
Bake for 20-30 minutes or until chicken is cooked through.

Recipe inspired by: http://www.thechunkychef.com/heroin-chicken-tenders

name: Tomato Lentil Soup
description:
1 serving of tomato lentil soup  contains 377 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 66% carbs, 13% fat, and 21% protein.  This is a good source of protein (37% of your Daily Value), fiber (37% of your Daily Value), and potassium (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Rinse all veggies thoroughly. Chop onion, carrots, celery, potatoes (skin on).

Add olive oil to large sauce pan over medium heat. Add onion, potatoes, carrots, and celery to pan and cook until onion is translucent (6-7 minutes).

Add lentils, tomatoes, vegetable broth, cumin, coriander, and salt, stir to combine. Increase heat to high and bring to boil.

Reduce heat to low, cover pan and simmer for 35-40 minutes or until done.

name: Pressure Cooker Tempeh Breakfast Bowl
description:
1 serving of pressure cooker tempeh breakfast bowl  contains 720 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 32% carbs, 36% fat, and 32% protein.  This is a good source of protein (112% of your Daily Value), fiber (57% of your Daily Value), and potassium (53% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Heat oil on medium-high in an uncovered pressure cooker (if using an electric pressure cooker, use the sauté, brown, or simmer function). Add carrot, green pepper, and garlic and sauté for a few minutes.
Add tempeh, broth, crushed tomatoes, cumin, and chili powder. Cover, bring to pressure and cook on high pressure for 3 minutes (if using an electric pressure cooker, cover, set on high for 3 minutes). Allow for a natural release.
Remove the cover and stir in the spinach and nutritional yeast; simmer until spinach is just wilted. Add salt and pepper, to taste (if desired). Enjoy!Recipe inspired by: http://jlgoesvegan.com/tempeh-breakfast-bowl/#more-28005

name: Garlic Basil Chicken with Tomato Butter Sauce
description:
1 serving of garlic basil chicken with tomato butter sauce  contains 686 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 27% carbs, 53% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (61% of your Daily Value), potassium (15% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cover the chicken with plastic wrap and pound each piece to an even thickness, about one inch or so in the thickest parts (this just helps it cook faster and more evenly). Remove the plastic and sprinkle each piece of chicken generously with sea salt and freshly ground pepper.Prep the tomatoes (dice), garlic (mince), and basil (ribbon slice) and set aside. Make the pasta according to package directions.Heat the olive oil in a large heavy skillet until a drop of water sizzles across the top. Add the chicken and pan-fry for several minutes on each side - the goal here is to get the chicken cooked AND get a nice browning on the outside. When the chicken is done, set aside. Chicken should be no longer pink, the juices run clear, and the internal temperature has reached 165 degrees F.Give the oil a few minutes to cool, add the tomatoes, and return to heat. Simmer to cook the tomatoes down into a chunky-sauce-like-mixture. Add the garlic and butter and stir to combine until the butter is melted. Add the chicken back in to soak in the sauce for a few minutes.Just before serving, stir in the basil. Top servings of pasta with the chicken and the sauce.

name: Strawberry Applesauce
description:
1 serving of strawberry applesauce  contains 249 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 94% carbs, 3% fat, and 3% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (44% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (114% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Core each apple (do not peel!) and cut into about 6 pieces. Add the apples and strawberries to a large pot. Add about 1/2" of water. Bring to a boil, cover, and simmer for about 30 minutes. Check about halfway through to make sure there's a little liquid on the bottom of the pot (to ensure that they don't stick). The apples should be very soft now. If they aren't, simmer in 5-minute increments until they are.Remove from the heat and let cool for about 20 minutes and then use an immersion blender to puree the applesauce. You can also use a blender or food processor but an immersion blender is quickest, easiest and the least messy.Cool completely and refrigerate in an airtight container for up to 4 days. Freeze any remaining applesauce after that.

name: Roasted Fennel and Baby Carrots
description:
1 serving of roasted fennel and baby carrots  contains 114 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 42% carbs, 53% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (18% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (67% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Peel and trim baby carrots leaving 1/2-inch of stems intact. Remove fennel stalks and discard. Cut fennel bulbs into 1/2-inch thick wedges. Put oven racks in upper and lower thirds of oven and preheat oven to 450F. (If you are making just this dish, you can put oven rack in middle position and roast vegetables on that rack throughout.)Toss carrots and fennel with olive oil, water, fennel seeds, salt, and pepper and arrange in 1 layer in a 17- by 11-inch shallow baking pan. Cover pan with foil and roast vegetables in lower third of oven 10 minutes, then uncover and roast, turning occasionally, 10 minutes more. Switch pan to upper third of oven and roast until vegetables are tender and browned, about 10 minutes more.

name: Creamy Avocado Chicken Pasta
description:
1 serving of creamy avocado chicken pasta  contains 706 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 38% carbs, 45% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (57% of your Daily Value), fiber (59% of your Daily Value), and potassium (31% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Remove the pits from two large avocados.Pulse-blend the avocados, Greek yogurt, garlic, basil, and juice from 1 lemon. Once blended and the texture is smooth, add salt and pepper to taste.Boil the pasta as per package directions and set aside.Season chicken with italian seasoning, salt, and pepper on each side. Heat a non-stick skillet over medium-high heat and coat wtih oil. Once hot add the chicken breast and cook for 5-7 minutes per side or until cooked through and no longer pink.Mix 1/3 of the avocado pasta sauce with the pasta, and then top with grilled chicken breast. Enjoy!

name: Carrot Ginger Soup
description:
1 serving of carrot ginger soup  contains 264 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 65% carbs, 24% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (33% of your Daily Value), potassium (24% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (249% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Heat oil in a sauce pot over medium heat. 

Add onions and sauté until they become translucent.
Add ginger and sauté for another minute.
Add chopped carrots, sweet potato, and vegetable broth and bring to a boil.
Reduce heat to low and simmer for about 30 minutes.
Purée soup with an immersion blender or in batches in a traditional blender. Season to taste with salt and pepper and serve.

name: Chicken and Chorizo Paella
description:
1 serving of chicken and chorizo paella  contains 688 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 38% carbs, 30% fat, and 32% protein.  This is a good source of protein (94% of your Daily Value), potassium (23% of your Daily Value), and iron (66% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat the oil in a large cast iron dutch oven over medium-high heat and brown the chicken pieces on all sides; you may have to do this in batches. Remove from the dutch oven and put to one side.Lower the heat, add the onion and pepper, and gently cook for 10 minutes until softened. Add the garlic and chorizo, and cook for a further 2 minutes until the chorizo has released some of its oils into the dish. Stir in the tomato purée and cook for 1 miuten more.Return the chicken pieces to the dish along with the thyme, white wine, and stock. Bring the liquid to a boil, cover the dish with a tight-fitting lid and lower the heat. Cook for 30 minutes.Tip in the rice and stir everything together. Cover, set over a low heat and cook for a further 15 mins, or until the rice is cooked and has absorbed most of the cooking liquid. Remove from the heat and leave the dish to sit for 10 mins to absorb any remaining liquid. Season to taste and garnish with parsley to serve.

name: Sweet and Salty Polenta
description:
1 serving of sweet and salty polenta  contains 188 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 82% carbs, 12% fat, and 7% protein.  This is a good source of calcium (19% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Combine polenta, almond milk, and water in a pot and cook over medium/low heat, stirring often, until tender; 15-20 minutes.Add salt, to taste.Drizzle with maple syrup and eat.

name: Pecan Crusted Honey-Mustard Salmon
description:
1 serving of pecan crusted honey-mustard salmon  contains 792 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 7% carbs, 52% fat, and 41% protein.  This is a good source of protein (144% of your Daily Value), potassium (43% of your Daily Value), and iron (50% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.In a small bowl, mix melted coconut oil, mustard, and honey.In another small bowl, mix bread crumbs, pecans, and parsley.Place salmon filets on a foil covered baking sheet. Season salmon with salt and pepper and pour the honey mixture over the tops. Sprinkle with the bread crumb mixture.Bake salmon until it flakes easily with a fork, about 20 minutes. Enjoy!

name: Roasted Fingerling Potatoes with Chive Pesto
description:
1 serving of roasted fingerling potatoes with chive pesto  contains 304 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 33% carbs, 62% fat, and 5% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (14% of your Daily Value), vitamin b6 (32% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (42% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Coarsely chop parsley. Cut potatoes in half lengthwise.Preheat oven to 425F. In a medium bowl, toss potatoes with 1 tablespoon oil to coat; season generously with salt and pepper. Spread potato halves in a single layer on a rimmed baking sheet. Roast potatoes, turning occasionally, until tender and golden brown,25-30 minutes.Meanwhile, combine 1/2 cup chives, parsley, almonds, and garlic in a processor. Pulse until finely chopped. With machine running, gradually add remaining oil through feed tube and process until incorporated. Transfer chive pesto to a small bowl. Stir in lemon juice, then 2 tablespoons water. Season pesto with salt and pepper.Transfer potatoes to a platter. Drizzle with half of pesto; sprinkle with additional chopped chives. Serve with remaining pesto.

name: Buffalo Cauliflower Quinoa Balls
description:
1 serving of buffalo cauliflower quinoa balls  contains 337 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 61% carbs, 25% fat, and 14% protein.  This is a good source of protein (22% of your Daily Value), fiber (27% of your Daily Value), and potassium (17% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375°.Cook quinoa with water over stovetop according to package instructions; simultaneously, steam chopped cauliflower in a separate pot with some water.Prepare the buffalo sauce by melting butter and stirring in hot sauce, garlic powder, and chili powder; set aside.Pulse HALF the cooked cauliflower with garlic in a food processor for 5-10 seconds, then repeat with the second half; combine in a bowl.Mix quinoa, breadcrumbs, oregano, and HALF the buffalo sauce with cauliflower; refrigerate for 10-15 minutes.Form the mixture into golf ball-sized balls and cook in a skillet with olive oil until golden brown on all sides.Drizzle remaining buffalo sauce over meatballs, ensuring they are covered but not soaked.Bake meatballs on a baking sheet for 15 minutes at 375°.

name: Peanut Butter Oatmeal and Berries
description:
1 serving of peanut butter oatmeal and berries  contains 605 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 62% carbs, 28% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of protein (28% of your Daily Value), fiber (79% of your Daily Value), and potassium (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook everything except berries for 8 minutes in a pan over medium heat until oats are tender.Add berries to the bowl and mix well. Enjoy!

name: Fennel Soup
description:
1 serving of fennel soup  contains 208 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 41% carbs, 49% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (32% of your Daily Value), potassium (27% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (26% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Melt the butter in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the quartered fennel bulbs; cook and stir until golden brown, about 10 minutes. Pour in the broth, and simmer until fennel is tender, about 15 more minutes. Ladle into soup bowls, and season with salt and pepper.

name: Bulgar Salad with Grilled Chicken and Parsley Pesto
description:
1 serving of bulgar salad with grilled chicken and parsley pesto  contains 795 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 22% carbs, 57% fat, and 21% protein.  This is a good source of protein (77% of your Daily Value), fiber (40% of your Daily Value), and potassium (24% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Sliver, toast & cool almonds. Chop shallots coarsely. Halve & pit apricots.Place 3 cups water and bulgur in medium
saucepan; sprinkle with salt. Bring to
boil. Cover, reduce heat to medium-low,
and simmer until bulgur is tender but still
slightly chewy, stirring occasionally, 11 to 12
minutes. Drain. Rinse under cold water until
cool. Drain well. Transfer to large bowl.Meanwhile, place parsley, almonds,
shallots, and 1 1/2 tablespoons lemon juice in
processor. Using on/off turns, process until
parsley is coarsely chopped. With machine
running, gradually add 1/2 cup oil and process
to coarse puree. Season pesto to taste with
salt and pepper.Stir 3/4 cup pesto and remaining 1
tablespoon lemon juice into drained bulgur.
Season to taste with salt and pepper and
additional lemon juice, if desired.
Prepare barbecue (medium heat).
Brush chicken and apricot halves with oil.Sprinkle with salt and pepper. Grill chicken
and apricot halves until chicken is cooked
through and apricots are slightly charred,
7 to 8 minutes per side for chicken and 2
minutes per side for apricots.Line 4 plates with lettuce leaves. Divide
bulgur salad among plates. Place 1 grilled
chicken breast on each plate. Spoon dollop
of pesto atop chicken. Divide apricot halves
among plates and serve.

name: Spicy Napa Cabbage Slaw with Cilantro Dressing
description:
1 serving of spicy napa cabbage slaw with cilantro dressing  contains 126 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 43% carbs, 49% fat, and 8% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (18% of your Daily Value), potassium (8% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (78% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Coarsely chop cilantro. Finely chop pepper. Core and cut cabbage crosswise into 1/2-inch slices.Whisk together vinegar, sugar, ginger, oil, chile, and 1/2 teaspoon salt. Add remaining ingredients and toss well. Let stand, tossing occasionally, 10 minutes.

name: Zesty Chicken Cobb Salad
description:
1 serving of zesty chicken cobb salad  contains 1180 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 9% carbs, 70% fat, and 21% protein.  This is a good source of protein (111% of your Daily Value), fiber (47% of your Daily Value), and potassium (43% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Place eggs in a pan and cover with water. Bring to a boil, cover, remove from heat, and let rest 10 minutes. Drain, rinse, peel, and set aside.Slice strips of bacon into 1-inch pieces. Aggressively season chicken breast on both sides with salt and pepper.Over medium-high heat, cook bacon until desired crispness. Remove from the pan and strain over a paper towel. Drain excess fat .Cook the chicken breast for 7 minutes on each side, or until internal temperature reaches 165 degrees F.In a bowl, whisk together shallots, apple cider vinegar, dijon mustard, salt and pepper. Slowly drizzle in the olive oil until emulsified.Chop romaine into bite size pieces and dice chicken into cubes.In a serving bowl, add a bed of romaine lettuce. In lines across the bowl, place chicken, blue cheese, bacon pieces, avocado, egg, and tomatoes. Drizzle the dressing over the top.Recipe inspired by: https://www.buzzfeed.com/clairenolan/try-this-zesty-chicken-cobb-salad-for-lunch-next-week?b=1&utm_term=.qqq6Yd1Y6#.lkkkAZMAk

name: Aloo Tikki
description:
2 pieces of aloo tikki  contains 288 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 74% carbs, 16% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (24% of your Daily Value), potassium (24% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (58% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Boil potatoes in pressure cooker or in a pan until soft. Peel and mash them. Boil peas in boiling water for 5 minutes. Drain water and transfer them to a small bowl.Take mashed potatoes in another bowl. Add boiled peas, 4 tablespoons breadcrumbs, cornstarch, grated ginger, coriander leaves, finely chopped green chilli, garam masala powder, red chilli powder, lemon juice, sugar, and salt.Mix them to prepare smooth dough like mixture. Divide mixture into 12 equal portions and roll them into small size balls.Take one ball and gently press it between your palms and make a round shaped 1/2-inch thick patty. Take 4 tablespoons breadcrumbs in a plate. Coat prepared pattie with breadcrumbs on all sides by rolling it in breadcrumbs filled plate.Heat non-stick flat pan (tawa) or griddle to shallow fry patties. When pan or griddle is hot enough, drizzle 2-3 teaspoons oil over it. Put 3-4 patties over oil and cook until bottom surface turn golden brown.Flip each pattie up side down, drizzle some oil around its edge and cook until second side also turns golden brown. Based on the size of your pan, you can shallow fry more than 3-4 tikkis at a time.Transfer prepared tikkis to a plate and serve.Recipe inspired by: http://foodviva.com/snacks-recipes/spicy-aloo-tikki-recipe/

name: Paleo "Cocoa Puffs"
description:
1 bowl of paleo "cocoa puffs"  contains 198 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 33% carbs, 55% fat, and 11% protein.  This has a relatively high calorie density, with 425 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Add the almond meal, melted coconut oil, sea salt, coconut flour, egg white, honey, and cocoa power to a bowl and mix with a spoon until you have a dough.Place the dough onto a piece of parchment paper. Place a second piece of parchment paper over the top and roll it until it is ¼” thick. With a wet knife, score it into 1” squares. Place the parchment paper on a baking sheet when finished.Bake for 8 to 12 minutes. Remove and cool on the pan.Top with your favorite mix-ins, eg, berries, bananas, etc. Enjoy!

name: Frittata with Spinach, Potatoes, and Leeks
description:
1 serving of frittata with spinach, potatoes, and leeks  contains 273 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 36% carbs, 38% fat, and 26% protein.  This is a good source of protein (32% of your Daily Value), potassium (21% of your Daily Value), and calcium (29% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Melt butter in a Dutch oven over medium heat. Add leek; sauté 4 minutes. Add spinach; sauté 2 minutes or until spinach wilts. Place mixture in a colander, pressing until barely moist.Combine milk, basil, salt, pepper, eggs, stir well with a whisk. Add leek mixture and potato. Pour into a 10-inch round ceramic baking dish or pie plate coated with cooking spray. Sprinkle with breadcrumbs and top with cheese. Bake for 25 minutes or until center is set.Preheat broiler.Broil frittata 4 minutes or until golden brown. Cut into wedges.Recipe inspired by: http://www.cookinglight.com/food/vegetarian/vegetarian-egg-recipes/frittata-spinach-potatoes-leeks-vegetarian-recipe

name: Slow Cooker Minestrone Soup
description:
2 cups of slow cooker minestrone soup  contains 385 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 75% carbs, 8% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (31% of your Daily Value), fiber (32% of your Daily Value), and potassium (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions In a microwave safe bowl, add onions, carrots and celery. Cook for 3 minutes to soften.Add to a slow cooker the onions, carrots, celery, garlic, broth, pasta sauce, beans, drained tomatoes, bay leaves, seasonings, and pepper. Mix well. Cover and cook on LOW heat a total of 6 to 7 hours or cook on HIGH heat a total of  3-3½ hours. Time varies depending on your slow-cooker.Meanwhie, prepare pasta as per package directions; set aside.Note: One hour before the soup is done, add zucchini. Cover and cook on high heat for the last hour. Or, cooked chopped zucchini in microwave for 2-3 minutes and add to soup with cooked pasta and spinach and continue to cook 10 minutes. Remove bay leaves. Adjust seasonings, if desired.To serve: Add 2 cups of soup to each bowl and top with grated parmesan cheese , if desired.Makes 12 cups total. Each serving, 2 cupsRecipe inspired by: http://www.skinnykitchen.com/recipes/crock-pot-hearty-minestrone-soup/

name: Cheesy Cauliflower Biscuits
description:
2 Biscuits of cheesy cauliflower biscuits  contains 52 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 24% carbs, 42% fat, and 34% protein.  This is a good source of vitamin c (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F.

Boil water in a pan with a steam tray. Add cauliflower and cover. Steam cauliflower for about 10-12 minutes or until very tender, then transfer to a food processor. Add minced garlic and pulse several times until smooth and creamy.


Transfer mashed cauliflower into a large mixing bowl. Add in two whole eggs, cheddar cheese, nonfat Greek yogurt, salt, and pepper, and mix together.

In a separate bowl, beat egg whites until stiff. Then, slowly fold the egg whites into the cauliflower mixture.

Coat a mini muffin pan with cooking spray of your choice. Then fill the cups to the top with the cauliflower mixture. Bake for 20-25 minutes, until golden brown.

Remove from the pan, and set on a cooling rack.

name: Hawaiian Pineapple Egg Scramble
description:
1 serving of hawaiian pineapple egg scramble  contains 596 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 13% carbs, 55% fat, and 32% protein.  This is a good source of protein (85% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and calcium (50% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat oil in a pan over medium heat. Add chopped ham to the pan and cook until it begins to brown. Remove from pan. Add pineapple and cook until it begins to brown. Remove from pan.Mix egg with egg whites and cook on heated skillet. Return ham and pineapple to the skillet. Add cheese. Cover and cook until cheese has melted and eggs are cooked to desired doneness.Enjoy!

name: Poached Eggs Alla Pizzaiola
description:
1 serving of poached eggs alla pizzaiola (http://www.skinnykitchen.com/recipes/skinny-poached-eggs-alla-pizzaiola/) contains 325 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 27% carbs, 51% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (34% of your Daily Value), fiber (15% of your Daily Value), and potassium (23% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook onions and red bell peppers in microwave for about 1 minute, to soften.In a medium non-stick pan heat butter over medium heat, add cooked onions/peppers and garlic; sauté for 1 minute. Stir often. Mix in oregano, salt, black pepper, and a small pinch of red pepper flakes. Stir in tomato sauce and simmer 5 minutes. Stir often. Gently drop in eggs. Be sure to keep the yolks in tact. Cover and simmer on medium-low heat for about 6-8 minutes, until the eggs whites are cooked through and the yolks are cooked to your liking.To serve: Using a spatula, remove 2 eggs to each plate and add tomato sauce around it. Sprinkle each serving with 1 tablespoon Parmesan cheese. Enjoy!

name: Dill Chicken Paillards with Tomato-Dill Relish
description:
1 serving of dill chicken paillards with tomato-dill relish  contains 284 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 7% carbs, 54% fat, and 39% protein.  This is a good source of protein (49% of your Daily Value), potassium (13% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (81% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Finely chop dill and shallots. Cut cherry tomatoes into quarters.Prepare grill for direct-heat cooking over hot charcoal (medium-high heat for gas).Pound chicken breasts 1/4 inch thick between 2 sheets of plastic wrap with flat side of a meat pounder or with 
a rolling pin.Whisk together oil, dill, shallot, mustard, and vinegar in a large bowl. Set aside 1/4 cup. Sprinkle chicken evenly with 1 teaspoon salt and 1/2 teaspoon pepper, then add to dill mixture, turning to coat.Toss tomatoes with reserved dill mixture and 1/4 teaspoon each of salt and pepper.Grill chicken, turning once, until just cooked through, 3 to 4 minutes total. Serve topped with relish.

name: Parsleyed Potatoes with Saffron
description:
1 serving of parsleyed potatoes with saffron  contains 707 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 82% carbs, 9% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of protein (32% of your Daily Value), fiber (57% of your Daily Value), and potassium (91% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Peel and steam potatoes in a steamer rack, covered, over boiling water until tender, 18 to 20 minutes.Melt butter with saffron in a medium skillet over medium heat until it foams, then add potatoes, chopped parsley, 1/4 teaspoon salt, and 1/8 teaspoon pepper. Cook, shaking skillet to coat potatoes well, until heated through, about 1 minute.

name: Simple Pasta Salad
description:
1 serving of simple pasta salad  contains 128 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 79% carbs, 4% fat, and 17% protein.  This has a moderate calorie density, with 160 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Boil water for noodles. Peel garlic cloves and put in boiling water with the noodles. When noodles are done, drain and separate garlic. Chop up garlic and add to noodles. Add can of tomatoes, kidney beans, and Italian dressing. Season with salt to taste. Serve and enjoy!

name: Cranberry Quinoa Salad
description:
1 serving of cranberry quinoa salad  contains 280 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 65% carbs, 23% fat, and 12% protein.  This is a good source of protein (15% of your Daily Value), fiber (24% of your Daily Value), and potassium (10% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Pour the water in a large saucepan.  Cover with a tight fitting lid, and place over high heat.  Once water starts to boil, pour in the quinoa, reduce heat to low, and cover. Simmer until the water has been absorbed, about 15 – 20 minutes. Transfer the quinoa to a large mixing bowl and place in the refrigerator until cold.Once the quinoa is chilled, stir in the bell peppers, red onion, curry powder, cilantro, lime juice, sliced almonds, carrots, cranberries, salt, and pepper.

name: Baked Garlic Pork Chop
description:
1 serving of baked garlic pork chop  contains 423 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 11% carbs, 47% fat, and 42% protein.  This is a good source of protein (76% of your Daily Value), potassium (21% of your Daily Value), and iron (46% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375 degrees F.Season the pork chops with salt and pepper and place in a casserole dish.Add in the oil, bay leaves, garlic, lemon juice, and the white wine; rub into the meat.Let it rest for 10-15 minutes.Bake the meat with the the juices until fully cooked and internal temperature has reach 155 degrees F; approximately 30 minutes.Serve and enjoy!

name: Kentucky Chili
description:
1 serving of kentucky chili (tur) contains 540 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 51% carbs, 28% fat, and 22% protein.  This is a good source of protein (56% of your Daily Value), fiber (58% of your Daily Value), and potassium (35% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Brown ground turkey in a skillet over medium heat. Add diced onion and cook until transparent. Drain.Cook spaghetti as per package directions; drain and set aside.Add all ingredients in a large pot. Salt to taste. Cook over medium heat until simmering and evenly heated through.Enjoy!

name: Gluten-Free Pumpkin Pancakes
description:
1 serving of gluten-free pumpkin pancakes  contains 260 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 56% carbs, 31% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of protein (16% of your Daily Value), fiber (16% of your Daily Value), and potassium (12% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions In a large bowl, whisk the oat flour, baking powder, baking soda and salt. Add the remaining pancake ingredients and whisk until just combined and smooth. The batter will thicken slightly while you wait for the griddle pan to heat up. Heat a griddle pan or a cast iron skillet over medium heat and grease with oil. Pour the batter into a liquid measuring cup, then pour about ¼ cup's worth for one pancake. Wait until some bubbles start to form on top. Allow to cook for 2 more minutes and then flip the pancakes over. Cook for about 3 more minutes until batter is cooked through. Serve pancakes hot.

name: Sausage Gravy and Biscuits
description:
1 serving of sausage gravy and biscuits  contains 226 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 28% carbs, 52% fat, and 21% protein.  This is a good source of protein (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Prepare biscuits as per package directions.Meanwhile, tear small pieces of sausage and add them in a single layer to a large heavy skillet. Brown the sausage over medium-high heat until no longer pink. Reduce the heat to medium-low. Sprinkle on half the flour and stir so that the sausage soaks it all up, then add more little by little. Stir it around and cook it for another minute or so, then pour in the milk, stirring constantly.Cook the gravy, stirring frequently, until it thickens. (This may take a good 10 to 12 minutes.) Sprinkle in the seasoned salt and pepper and continue cooking until very thick and luscious. If it gets too thick too soon, just splash in another 1/2 cup of milk or more if needed. Taste and adjust the seasoning with salt and pepper.Spoon the sausage gravy over the warm biscuits and serve immediately. Enjoy!

name: Strawberry Spinach Green Smoothie
description:
1 serving of strawberry spinach green smoothie  contains 149 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 89% carbs, 4% fat, and 7% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (21% of your Daily Value), potassium (17% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (27% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Combine all ingredients in a blender and pulse until smooth. Enjoy!

name: Italian Quinoa & Lentils
description:
1 serving of italian quinoa & lentils  contains 390 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 63% carbs, 14% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (41% of your Daily Value), fiber (38% of your Daily Value), and potassium (26% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat the olive oil in a large pot or Dutch oven over medium heat. Add the chopped onion and cook for 5 minutes, or until the onion is clear and soft, stirring frequently.Add the garlic and mushrooms. Cook until the mushrooms have released their juices and reduced in size, about 4-5 minutes.Add the lentils, quinoa, salt, thyme, and broth. Bring the mixture to a boil, then reduce heat to low. Cover and simmer for 30 minutes, or until the lentils are tender. If all of the liquid has been absorbed, add a splash of extra broth or water.Add the tomatoes and baby spinach to the pot. Stir until the spinach has wilted completely into the quinoa and lentil mixture. Add a splash of lemon juice, along with black pepper to taste and extra salt as needed.

name: Chicken Peek-a-Boos
description:
1 serving of chicken peek-a-boos  contains 534 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 5% carbs, 51% fat, and 45% protein.  This is a good source of protein (105% of your Daily Value), potassium (21% of your Daily Value), and calcium (28% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 375 degrees F.Combine cheeses, basil, and mustard in bowl. Mix until blended, then salt and pepper to taste.Cut chicken breasts in half (like you would cut a loaf of bread). Using a meat mallet, tenderize and flatten chicken.Place 2 slices ham on chicken, cover completely. Spread 1/4 of the cheese mixture on ham. Roll up chicken and ham. Use toothpicks to secure the chicken roll.In an oven-safe frying pan drizzle olive oil. Turn heat to medium. Once hot brown the chicken rolls.Move pan into oven for 18-25 minutes or until center of chicken has reached 165 degrees F.Let rest for about 5 minutes before enjoying.

name: Scallops with Brussels Sprouts and Mustard Sauce
description:
1 serving of scallops with brussels sprouts and mustard sauce  contains 260 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 18% carbs, 57% fat, and 25% protein.  This is a good source of protein (30% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b12 (67% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Dry the scallosp, add salt and pepper to taste, and dust on both sides with flour. Set aside. 

In a small bowl, combine the butter (cut into small pieces), lemon juice, mustard, salt and pepper (to taste), and 2 tbsp water. Set aside. 

In a food processor, shred the Brussels sprouts,  then season with salt and pepper. 

Heat 2 tbsp of the oil in a 12-inch nonstick skillet over medium-high heat until shimmering hot. Add the Brussels sprouts and toss to coat with the oil. Cover and cook a few minutes until starting to soften. Transfer to a platter and keep warm.

Heat the remaining 1 tbsp oil in the skillet over medium-high heat until shimmering hot. Add the scallops and cook, flipping once, until browned and just cooked through, about 5 minutes total. Put the scallops on top of the Brussels sprouts on the platter 

Turn the heat on the skillet down to medium-low. Add the butter-juice-mustard mixture, stirring and scraping up any browned bits, until the butter is incorporated and the sauce has thickened, about 1 minute. Spoon over the scallops, and serve.

name: Creamy Asparagus Tagliatelle
description:
1 serving of creamy asparagus tagliatelle  contains 916 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 49% carbs, 34% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (73% of your Daily Value), potassium (15% of your Daily Value), and calcium (70% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Put cream in a sauce pan and bring to a boil. Reduce to a low simmer for 10 minutes, until thickened.Meanwhile, cook pasta according to package instructions. 2 minutes before pasta is finished, add asparagus to the boiling water. Drain well and return to the warm pan with the cream, lemon juice, parsley, and 1/2 of the Parmesan cheese.Toss together and season well with salt and pepper. Sprinkle remaining cheese on top. Enjoy!

name: BLT Ranch Burger
description:
1 Burger of blt ranch burger  contains 688 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 17% carbs, 65% fat, and 18% protein.  This is a good source of protein (54% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and iron (62% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook bacon in a skillet over medium heat until cooked to desired crispiness.For the dressing: Combine the mayonnaise, buttermilk, chives, parsley, salt, pepper, and garlic powder in a medium bowl and mix well. Refrigerate until ready to serve.For the burgers: Preheat an outdoor grill to medium-high heat.In a bowl, combine the beef, Worcestershire sauce, egg, and salt and pepper to taste. Shape into 4 patties.Grill the patties for about 5 minutes per side for medium doneness.Place each patty on a bun and top with bacon, tomato, lettuce and a generous dollop of dressing. Close the burgers with the top bun half and serve immediately. Enjoy!

name: Cider-Glazed Lamb Chops
description:
1 serving of cider-glazed lamb chops  contains 582 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 11% carbs, 45% fat, and 44% protein.  This is a good source of protein (112% of your Daily Value), potassium (21% of your Daily Value), and iron (78% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Mince garlic. Finely chop scallion.Boil apple juice, ginger, garlic, soy sauce, vinegar, and honey in a small saucepan until reduced to about 1/4 cup, 10 to 12 minutes. Cool completely. Reserve 2 tablespoons glaze for drizzling.Preheat broiler.Pat lamb chops dry and sprinkle with 1/2 teaspoon salt (total). Arrange on rack of a broiler pan and brush top of chops with half of glaze. Broil 3 to 4 inches from heat 3 minutes. Turn over and brush with remaining glaze, then broil 3 to 4 minutes more for medium-rare. Transfer chops to a plate and drizzle with reserved glaze. Let stand 5 minutes, then sprinkle with scallion.

name: Chestnut Pancakes with Bacon and creme fraiche
description:
1 serving of chestnut pancakes with bacon and creme fraiche  contains 52 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 43% carbs, 45% fat, and 13% protein.  This has a moderate calorie density, with 174 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Coarsely chop chestnuts.Cook bacon in large skillet over medium heat until brown and crisp. Using slotted spoon, transfer bacon to paper towels to drain. Transfer 2 tablespoons bacon drippings to blender; add milk and next 3 ingredients, then 1 cup chestnuts. Blend until batter is smooth. Pour batter into bowl; stir in remaining 1/2 cup chestnuts.Pour remaining drippings into small bowl. Brush same skillet with some drippings; heat over medium heat. Drop in batter by rounded tablespoonfuls. Cook pancakes until brown and cooked through, about 3 minutes per side. Transfer to plates. Top with sour cream and chopped or crumbled bacon, then chives or maple syrup.

name: Spicy Chicken Fried Quinoa
description:
1 serving of spicy chicken fried quinoa  contains 1843 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 34% carbs, 35% fat, and 31% protein.  This is a good source of protein (259% of your Daily Value), fiber (80% of your Daily Value), and potassium (106% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook quinoa using low-sodium chicken broth according to package instructions. Allow to cool to room temperature.Mix liquid aminos, chutney, sriracha, and teriyaki sauce in a small bowl; set aside.Spray a nonstick skillet with coconut oil and set over medium heat. Cook garlic, carrots, and red onions until onions are translucent.Add ground chicken to the skillet, breaking it apart as it cooks until fully cooked. Increase heat to medium-high and add the cooled, dry quinoa. Stir well.Stir in the sauce quickly to avoid burning. Add eggs, stirring and chopping to distribute evenly. Reduce heat to medium, add frozen edamame, and cook until thawed.

name: Broccoli Chicken Zucchini Boats
description:
1 serving of broccoli chicken zucchini boats  contains 515 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 10% carbs, 64% fat, and 26% protein.  This is a good source of protein (61% of your Daily Value), fiber (15% of your Daily Value), and potassium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400°F.Heat olive oil in a pan over medium-high heat. Once hot, add the chicken and cook for 4-5 minutes per side, or until cooked through and no longer pink. Set aside.Cut the zucchini in half lengthwise and, using a spoon, scoop out most of the flesh until you’re left with a shell about ½-1 cm thick.Pour 1 tbsp of melted butter into each zucchini boat, season with salt and pepper, and place them in the oven for about 20 minutes.While the zucchini is cooking, shred the chicken. Cut the broccoli florets into small pieces and combine both the chicken and broccoli with sour cream. Season with salt and pepper.Once the zucchini is tender, remove from the oven and add the chicken and broccoli filling.Sprinkle with cheddar cheese and bake for an additional 10-15 minutes, or until the cheese is melted and browning.Garnish with chopped scallions and enjoy with more sour cream or mayo!

name: Indian Spiced Roasted Chickpeas
description:
1 serving of indian spiced roasted chickpeas  contains 301 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 44% carbs, 41% fat, and 16% protein.  This is a good source of protein (22% of your Daily Value), fiber (41% of your Daily Value), and potassium (9% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F.

Place the chickpeas into a large bowl. Mix the spices and salt into the melted coconut oil. Pour the spiced oil over the chickpeas. Combine the chickpeas and spiced oil thoroughly, ensuring the chickpeas are well coated.

Spread the spiced chickpeas onto a baking tray. Roast for 35-40 minutes, stirring frequently. Watch the chickpeas carefully towards the end of the cooking time as they burn easily.

The chickpeas are ready when they are lightly browned and crispy. To test the chickpeas, remove one from the oven and allow to cool. If the chickpeas are still chewy rather than crispy, they need a little more time in the oven.

Allow the chickpeas to cool on the tray, then store in an airtight container.

name: Cauliflower Tots
description:
1 serving of cauliflower tots (Crispy and perfect for dipping) contains 189 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 38% carbs, 39% fat, and 23% protein.  This is a good source of protein (20% of your Daily Value), fiber (14% of your Daily Value), and potassium (12% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions In a food processor, pulse chopped cauliflower until it resembles the shape and size of rice. You can also use a box grater or mince the cauliflower by hand. Preheat the oven to 400°F. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper and spray it generously with nonstick spray.Squeeze excess moisture from the prepared cauliflower using paper towels or a tea towel and transfer to a large bowl.Add the scallions, parsley, cheese, garlic powder, cayenne, egg and egg white; mix to combine. Add the breadcrumbs and mix to combine.Scoop out 2 tablespoons of the mixture and form it into a tater tot, cylindrical shape and place on the prepared baking sheet. Repeat with the rest of the mixture leaving space between each tot. Spray the surface of the tots with nonstick spray.Bake until the bottoms turn golden brown, about 17 to 20 minutes. Rotate the tots and bake another 5 to 10 minutes more to brown the other side. Serve immediately and enjoy!

name: Glazed Apricot Twists
description:
1 serving of glazed apricot twists  contains 255 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 52% carbs, 44% fat, and 4% protein.  This has a relatively high calorie density, with 416 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Put oven rack in middle position and preheat oven to 425F. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper.Thaw and roll out pastry on a lightly floured surface into a 12- by 10-inch rectangle, then cut in half lengthwise. Cut each half crosswise into 4 (5- by 3-inch) strips (for a total of 8 strips).Spread each strip with 1/2 tablespoon of melted jam, then fold strips in half lengthwise to form 1 1/2-inch-wide strips. Twist each strip 3 times and place on baking sheet.Bake until golden brown, 15 to 20 minutes. Transfer twists to a rack set over a sheet of parchment. Stir together confectioners sugar, cream, and lemon juice until smooth, then brush over warm twists. Serve warm.

name: Peaches with Serrano Ham and Basil
description:
1 serving of peaches with serrano ham and basil  contains 16 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 45% carbs, 24% fat, and 30% protein.  This has a relatively low calorie density, with 65 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions PREPARATION:  Cut peaches into 8 wedges.  Thinly slice ham.Toss together peaches, sugar, vinegar, and cumin and let stand 10 minutes.Cut ham slices in half lengthwise, then wrap each piece around a wedge of peach. Top with a basil leaf and secure with a wooden or metal pick.

name: Quinoa Porridge
description:
1 serving of quinoa porridge  contains 295 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 79% carbs, 11% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (27% of your Daily Value), potassium (15% of your Daily Value), and magnesium (28% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Cook quinoa as per package directions.Add sliced banana, almond milk, vanilla, and cinnamon. Serve warm and enjoy!

name: Gouda & Green Onion Omelet
description:
1 serving of gouda & green onion omelet  contains 729 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 3% carbs, 75% fat, and 22% protein.  This is a good source of protein (73% of your Daily Value), potassium (8% of your Daily Value), and calcium (70% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Whisk the eggs in a bowl with pepper and half of the butter broken apart in pieces. Chop green onion.Heat the remaining butter in a skillet on medium-high heat. Let the butter completely melt. Once it begins to bubble and darken in color, pour the eggs in the skillet. Cover and reduce heat to medium, let cook for about 2 minutes.Add slices of gouda on top of the eggs, along with half of the chopped green onion, cover and let the cheese melt.Once melted, fold the eggs to make an omelet, place on a plate and garnish with remaining chopped green onion.Serve and enjoy!

name: Green Bean Stir Fry
description:
1 serving of green bean stir fry  contains 97 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 65% carbs, 22% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (18% of your Daily Value), potassium (9% of your Daily Value), and vitamin c (34% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Drizzle olive oil in a large sauté pan over medium-high heat. Combine all ingredients in the pan and sauté for 10-15 minutes or until vegetables are tender and slightly charred.Serve immediately and enjoy!

name: Italian Wedding Soup
description:
1 serving of italian wedding soup  contains 288 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 32% carbs, 27% fat, and 41% protein.  This is a good source of protein (52% of your Daily Value), potassium (13% of your Daily Value), and iron (54% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions In a medium bowl, combine the beef, egg, bread crumbs, cheese, basil, and onion. Shape mixture into 3/4-inch balls and set aside.In a large stockpot heat chicken broth to boiling; stir in the spinach, shell pasta, carrot, and meatballs. Return to boil; reduce heat to medium. Cook, stirring frequently, at a slow boil for 10-20 minutes or until pasta is al dente, and meatballs are no longer pink inside. Serve hot with Parmesan cheese sprinkled on top.

name: Taco Stuffed Zucchini Boats
description:
1 serving of taco stuffed zucchini boats  contains 311 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 25% carbs, 37% fat, and 39% protein.  This is a good source of protein (57% of your Daily Value), fiber (23% of your Daily Value), and potassium (32% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Bring a large pot of salted water to boil. Preheat oven to 400 degrees F. Place 1/4 cup of salsa in the bottom of a large baking dish.

Using a small spoon or melon baller, hollow out the center of the zucchini halves, leaving 1/4-inch thick shell on each half. Chop the scooped out flesh of the zucchini in small pieces and set aside 3/4 of a cup to add to the taco filling, (squeeze excess water with a paper towel) discarding the rest or save to use in another recipe. Drop zucchini halves in boiling water and cook 1 minute. Remove from water.

Brown turkey in a large skillet, breaking up while it cooks. When no longer pink add the spices and mix well. Add the onion, bell pepper, reserved zucchini, tomato sauce, and water. Stir and cover, simmer on low for about 20 minutes.

Using a spoon, fill the hollowed zucchini boats dividing the taco meat equally, about 1/3 cup in each, pressing firmly. Top each with 1 tablespoon of shredded cheese. Cover with foil and bake 35 minutes until cheese is melted and zucchini is cooked through. Top with scallions and serve with salsa on the side. Enjoy!

name: Grilled Cheese Turkey Burger Wraps
description:
1 wrap of grilled cheese turkey burger wraps  contains 330 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 20% carbs, 48% fat, and 32% protein.  This is a good source of protein (48% of your Daily Value), potassium (10% of your Daily Value), and calcium (25% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions In a medium to large skillet coated with cooking spray cook the turkey on medium heat until almost cooked through but still a little pink (about 7-10 minutes). Break turkey up as it cooks.Add worcestershire, ketchup, grated parmesan, dried onion flakes, salt, and pepper to the ground turkey. Mix together until thoroughly combined.Continue cooking until turkey is cooked all the way through and is no longer pink.Turn on indoor grill to 350 degeres F; you can also use a grill plan.In the center of the wrap place a slice of cheese and ½ cup of the turkey mixture. Add tomato and lettuce. Then if you are using, add some ketchup and mustard.Roll the wrap and place seam side down on grill. Once there are nice grill marks turn over. Grill for another 2-3 minutes then remove.Repeat steps 4 and 5 for the rest of the wraps. Enjoy!

name: Spinach Stuffed Chicken
description:
1 stuffed breast of spinach stuffed chicken  contains 236 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 55% fat, and 37% protein.  This is a good source of protein (39% of your Daily Value), potassium (12% of your Daily Value), and calcium (20% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Grate cheeses, beat the eggs, slice the onion, and crush garlic.Butterfly chicken breast (i.e. split it so that you can stuff it with stuff) and drizzle with olive oil.Sprinkle chicken breast to taste with cayanne pepper, salt, and pepper; set asideIn a sauté pan cook spinach, onion, and garlic until spinach has started to wilt, 2-3 minutes. Remove spinach from heat and add to a medium bowl with Parmesan cheese, half of the mozzarella cheese, and beaten egg.. Mix all ingredients until well incorporated.Place a large spoonful of spinach mixture in the middle of each chicken breast and fold over, covering the spinach mixture completely.Sprinkle with remaining cheese and place on baking sheet. Bake for 30 minutes or until a thermometer reaches 165 degrees F when chicken is tested. Serve and enjoy!

name: Spinach and Poached Egg Muffins
description:
1 serving of spinach and poached egg muffins  contains 375 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 39% carbs, 35% fat, and 26% protein.  This is a good source of protein (45% of your Daily Value), fiber (38% of your Daily Value), and potassium (21% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Put a pan of water on to boil and add the vinegar. Toast the muffin halves until lightly browned. Meanwhile, heat the spinach through on a saucepan, just a few minutes; season to taste and add some freshly ground nutmeg and the sour cream.When the water is at a simmer, break the eggs into a small cup and then carefully slide them into the water. Turn the heat down and simmer for 3 minutes until the white has set and it's firm, but the yolks are still soft and runny. Remove the eggs from the water with a slotted spoon. Spoon the warm, cooked spinach on top of the muffin halves and then put the eggs on top of the spinach. Season with salt and freshly ground black pepper and serve straight away.

name: Cottage Pie
description:
1 serving of cottage pie  contains 328 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 27% carbs, 53% fat, and 21% protein.  This is a good source of protein (30% of your Daily Value), fiber (15% of your Daily Value), and potassium (16% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F and place a rack in the middle.

Melt one tablespoon of butter in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Add onions and carrots, and sauté, stirring every so often, until onion is soft, about 5 to 6 minutes.  Season with salt and pepper, and stir in tomato paste.

Add ground beef and cook, breaking up with a wooden spoon, until browned, about 5-10 minutes. Add thyme and beef stock and bring to a boil. Cook, stirring constantly, until it starts to reduce, about 3 minutes.

In a bowl mix cornstarch with ½ cup of cold water. Add to beef mixture and cook until it thickens, about 2 minutes. Stir in peas and adjust seasoning, if needed.

Transfer mixture to a 2-quart baking dish. Top with potatoes, overlapping slices. Melt the remaining tablespoon of butter and drizzle over the potatoes.

Bake until the potatoes are browned around the edges, about 40 to 45 minutes. Let cool 10 minutes before serving.

name: Spinach Salad With Warm Onions and Crispy Salami
description:
1 serving of spinach salad with warm onions and crispy salami (http://www.realsimple.com/food-recipes/browse-all-recipes/spinach-salad-hot-salami-cubes) contains 295 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 12% carbs, 69% fat, and 19% protein.  This is a good source of protein (26% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin a (40% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Heat 1 tablespoon of the oil in a medium skillet over medium heat. Add the salami and cook, stirring occasionally, until browned, 2 to 3 minutes. Transfer to a paper towel–lined plate.
Add the vinegar, mustard, honey, the remaining tablespoon of oil, and ¼ teaspoon each salt and pepper to the skillet. Whisk to combine.
Add the onion and cook, stirring occasionally, until it begins to soften, 3 to 4 minutes. Stir in the salami.
Divide the spinach among 4 individual plates and spoon the onion and salami over the top. Serve with the eggs, if desired.

name: Dried Fruit and Almond Granola
description:
1 Serving of dried fruit and almond granola  contains 220 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 54% carbs, 39% fat, and 7% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (17% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Combine oats, coconut, and almonds in a large baking dish. Drizzle with oil and toss until well blended. Bake in preheated oven for 15-20 minutes, tossing every 5 minutes, until lightly toasted.Allow mixture to cool slightly before mixing in dried fruit and raisins.Store in airtight container and serve with soy milk, fresh fruit, and/or fruit juice.

name: Wilted Spinach with Nutmeg Butter
description:
1 serving of wilted spinach with nutmeg butter  contains 91 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 24% carbs, 57% fat, and 19% protein.  This is a good source of potassium (20% of your Daily Value), calcium (17% of your Daily Value), and iron (58% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Rinse spinach under cool water. Remove the coarse stems. This may seem like a lot of spinach, but it will reduce down significantly when it wilts.Bring 1 cup water to a boil in a wide large pot over high heat, then cook spinach, tossing with tongs, until completely wilted, about 5 minutes. Drain in a colander, pressing with back of a spoon to extract as much liquid as possible.Heat butter in same pot over medium heat until foam subsides, then stir in nutmeg, 1/2 teaspoon salt, 1/4 teaspoon pepper, and spinach. Cook, tossing with tongs, until just heated through.

name: Coconut Chicken Soup
description:
1 serving of coconut chicken soup  contains 317 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 8% carbs, 72% fat, and 20% protein.  This is a good source of protein (29% of your Daily Value), potassium (10% of your Daily Value), and iron (47% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Sauté chopped white onion and garlic in the coconut oil in a medium pot over medium-high heat until translucent. Chop chicken into thin slices.Add chicken stock, coconut milk, and all seasonings and simmer about 15 minutes, reduce heat if it starts to boil.Add the chicken and then bring soup back up to temperature, usually takes 5-10 minutes to cook through. Top each bowl of soup with basil and/or cilantro and garnish with the green onions.

name: Sweet & Sour Chickpeas
description:
1 serving of sweet & sour chickpeas  contains 186 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 70% carbs, 16% fat, and 14% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (21% of your Daily Value), potassium (7% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (50% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Mix sugar, vinegar, ketchup, soy sauce, garlic powder, 2 tbsp water in a bowl and set aside.Heat oil over medium high heat in a large skillet. Add minced garlic and cook for 2 minutes or until translucent. Add chopped peppers and mix in. Cover and cook for 2 minutes.Add the chopped broccoli and mix in. Cover and cook for 1 minute. Add the chickpeas, sauce ingredients, a generous dash of salt, black pepper and cayenne. Reduce heat to medium. Cover and cook for 10 minutes.Taste the sauce carefully and adjust to preference. Add more sour, sugar or salt.Mix cornstarch in room temperature water and add the mixture to the pan. Mix in. Cover and cook for 2 to 3 minutes until the sauce thickens. Enjoy!

name: Cabbage Pie
description:
1 serving of cabbage pie  contains 452 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 28% carbs, 55% fat, and 17% protein.  This is a good source of protein (33% of your Daily Value), potassium (11% of your Daily Value), and vitamin b6 (36% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Pre-heat oven to 350°F.In stockpot, brown ground beef over medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes or until beef is thoroughly cooked, stirring frequently. Add coleslaw mix. Cover pan and cook, stirring often, until cabbage softens, about 10 minutes. Mix in potatoes. Stir in soup. Cover and reduce heat to low to keep warm.Unroll 1 can of dough. Press in 13x9-inch glass baking dish to form bottom crust. Spread cabbage mixture evenly over crust. Unroll second can of dough on wax paper. Press seams together to make one sheet. Place over top to form top crust. Press and tuck edges to seal.Bake 25 minutes or until golden brown. Let stand 5 minutes. Cut into 8 squares.

name: Breakfast Sweet Potato
description:
1 serving of breakfast sweet potato  contains 368 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 50% carbs, 39% fat, and 11% protein.  This is a good source of protein (18% of your Daily Value), fiber (30% of your Daily Value), and potassium (18% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions To bake sweet potatoes: Preheat oven to 400 degrees F. Pierce washed sweet potatoes with a fork. Place on a baking sheet and bake for 45 minutes to an hour, or until fork tender.

For breakfast sweet potatoes: Slice baked sweet potato in half. Top each one with ¼ cup granola, 1 tablespoon of almond butter and 1 teaspoon of maple syrup. Add a dash of cinnamon and enjoy!

name: Cuban Picadillo
description:
½ cups of cuban picadillo  contains 182 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 14% carbs, 31% fat, and 55% protein.  This is a good source of protein (46% of your Daily Value), potassium (14% of your Daily Value), and iron (47% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Brown meat on medium flame in large sauté pan and season with salt and pepper. Use a wooden spoon to break the meat up into small pieces. When meat is no longer pink, drain all juice from pan.Meanwhile, while meat is cooking, chop onion, garlic, pepper, tomato, and cilantro.Add sofrito (onion mixture) to the meat and continue cooking on a low flame. Add alcaparrado and about 2 tbsp of the brine from the jar, cumin, bay leaf, and more salt if needed. Add tomato sauce and 1/4 cup of water and mix well. Reduce heat and simmer covered about 15-20 minutes.

name: Flourless Chocolate Cake
description:
96 g of flourless chocolate cake  contains 398 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 33% carbs, 61% fat, and 7% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (18% of your Daily Value), potassium (6% of your Daily Value), and iron (50% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Grease and line a 9 inch springform pan with parchment. Preheat oven to 300 degrees F.In a bowl of an electric mixer, with the whisk attachment, whisk the egg yolks with the 1st sugar for 10 minutes until very pale in colour and tripled in volume.In a bain marie, gently melt the butter and chocolate. Remove from the heat and mix in the cocoa powder.In a new clean bowl, whisk the egg whites with remaining sugar and the salt until soft peaks form.Fold the chocolate mix into the yolks and then gently fold the whites, trying to keep as much volume as possible.Pour the cake mix into prepared pan.Bake for a bout 35 minutes, until a toothpick comes out clean. Enjoy!

name: Cauliflower and Chickpea Coconut Curry
description:
1 serving of cauliflower and chickpea coconut curry  contains 687 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 58% carbs, 31% fat, and 10% protein.  This is a good source of protein (32% of your Daily Value), fiber (50% of your Daily Value), and potassium (22% of your Daily Value).
instructions:
Directions Cut cauliflower into florets. Dice onion. Mince garlic. Drain and rinse chickpeas.Heat the coconut oil in a large Dutch oven over medium heat. Add the onion, garlic, and ginger, and cook until softened, 5-7 minutes. Stir in the spices and cook until they're fragrant, about 1 minute. 

Add the chickpeas, tomatoes, coconut milk, and cauliflower. Increase the heat to medium-high and bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low, cover, and simmer for 15 minutes. Uncover and cook 5 minutes more, or until sauce has thickened slightly. Season with salt and pepper to taste and garnish each serving with cilantro.Steam rice as per package directions. Serve with the curry and enjoy!

name: Cranberry Almond Energy Balls
description:
2 balls of cranberry almond energy balls  contains 151 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 57% carbs, 35% fat, and 9% protein.  This has a relatively high calorie density, with 386 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.Chop almonds, shred coconut, grind flaxseed and chop cranberries, if they aren't already.Bake oatmeal, almonds and coconut for 8-10 minutes, stirring after 5 minutes. Allow the mixture to cool.In a medium bowl microwave the nut butter for 20-30 seconds until runny, add the baked mix along with flaxseed, honey, chia seeds and cranberries to the bowl. Form into 1.5" balls and refrigerate. Store in an airtight container refrigerated for up to one week or freezer for 3 months.

name: Zucchini Chocolate Protein Powder Brownies
description:
1 serving of zucchini chocolate protein powder brownies  contains 68 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 47% carbs, 23% fat, and 30% protein.  This has a relatively low calorie density, with 97 Calories per 100g.
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. Prepare a 9x9" baking dish.Combine all ingredients in a bowl and mix together well. Pour into prepareed baking dish. Bake for about 20 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean. Enjoy!

name: Curry Beans
description:
1 serving of curry beans  contains 470 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 60% carbs, 27% fat, and 13% protein.  This is a good source of protein (27% of your Daily Value), fiber (59% of your Daily Value), and potassium (35% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Heat a pan on the stove over medium heat. Add about 1-2 tbsp of oil.  Add two chopped onions. Make sure they are finely chopped, the onions help give the curry a thick gravy.Allow onions to soften then add the ginger, garlic, and curry.Add the cinnamon and chilli powder. Braise the spices and onions for 2-3 minutes then add chopped tomatoes and 1 cup of the water. Cover and allow to simmer.Once the tomatoes form a chutney like texture add the chopped potatoes. Allow to cook for 10 minutes.Add the boiled beans (and the water from the beans) into the curry mixture. Stir then cover. Allow to cook for 20 minutes. When the water evaporates add more water depending on the consistency you would like. If you prefer more gravy then add more water.Once the potatoes have cooked remove from stove. Serve with rice or roti.

name: Simple Cacao Macaroons
description:
3 cookies of simple cacao macaroons  contains 425 Calories. The macronutrient
  breakdown is 24% carbs, 70% fat, and 6% protein.  This is a good source of fiber (30% of your Daily Value) and potassium (8% of your Daily Value).
instructions: Directions Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.Put coconut in a small bowl. Add the cacao nibs.  Add one egg white, 2-3 tsp of sweetener, and vanilla extract.  Mix.  Press mixture into tbsp, invert on baking sheet and tap. Bake for about 11 minutes or until golden brown.
